<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Wary of Tax Credit Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican presidential candidate John McCain  
said Friday that Congress shouldn't ``tamper with a much-needed tax 
credit for working Americans'' and suggested cutting special 
interest subsidies would be a better way to meet budget targets. 
</P>
<P>
	``If our goal is to have lower-income Americans lifted up into  
the middle class, this is the wrong way to do it,'' said McCain, a 
senator from Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP-led Congress is mulling several bookkeeping maneuvers to  
keep a promise to avoid spending portions of the federal surplus 
reserved for Social Security. 
</P>
<P>
	One proposal under consideration by Republican House leaders  
would produce $8 billion in savings by spreading the earned income 
tax credit over 12 monthly payments rather than the lump sum now 
paid with tax refunds. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats have criticized the tactic, saying it would take money  
from working families that earn less than $30,000 a year. George W. 
Bush, Texas governor and front-runner in the race for the GOP 
nomination, also has criticized the proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	In a telephone interview from his Phoenix campaign headquarters,  
McCain said he has found at least ``$9 billion worth of pork and 
wasteful spending'' in the appropriations bills now being 
considered by Congress that could fill the budget gaps. He 
specified subsidies for oil, ethanol and sugar as examples. 
</P>
<P>
	``Congress has found the funds to raise their own salaries but  
they can't find enough to help and lower and middle-income 
Americans,'' said McCain, who called the phase-in an ``accounting 
gimmick and Americans are tired of this kind of gimmick from 
Congress.'' 
</P>
<P>
	House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R. Ill., said Friday that House  
leaders ran the tax credit phase-in by Bush's staff, ``as well as 
others,'' but got no response. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain spokesman Howard Opinsky said House leaders did not  
consult with the senator before suggesting the phased-in tax credit 
as a budget option. ``We have not had a discussion with the House 
leadership,'' Opinsky said. ``We would have told them we need to 
put working families ahead of special interests.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
