<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dolphins' Underwood To Get Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- Dimitrius Underwood, who cut his neck with  
steak knives in an apparent suicide attempt, was released from the 
hospital and will get psychological care elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	The Miami Dolphins rookie was in good spirits and ``very  
peaceful,'' Underwood's agent, Craig Domann, said Thursday. He did 
not identify his client's new treatment center. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood's mother, Eileen Underwood, did not return messages to  
her Philadelphia home Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood had been at Sparrow Hospital since slashing his neck  
Sunday. The hospital said he was released, but declined further 
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	A police report Thursday said Underwood chanted ``I'm not worthy  
of God'' before he used two steak knives to cut his throat at the 
Lansing home of his girlfriend and their twin toddlers. 
</P>
<P>
	His girlfriend said Underwood was confused and upset. She and  
her stepfather were driving Underwood to the hospital when he 
jumped from the car. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood was covered with blood and saying, ``You are Satan and  
you're going to hell'' and ``I want to be saved, I want to meet 
God,'' when officers arrived to help him, according to reports 
obtained by the Lansing State Journal. 
</P>
<P>
	A day before the stabbing, Underwood was arrested on a warrant  
accusing him of nonpayment of child support. 
</P>
<P>
	Police found him with the knife wound 13 hours after a woman  
posted his bond and Underwood left the jail. 
</P>
<P>
	His friend and former Michigan State teammate, Sedrick Irvin of  
the Detroit Lions, told the Detroit Free Press he visited Underwood 
at the hospital Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He had tubes and machines all around him, but he said, `This  
ain't nothing. The Man upstairs is real,''' Irvin said. ``He's 
confused right now and he did what a person who's confused does.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood, who played at Michigan State, was a first-round draft  
pick by the Minnesota Vikings. But he left the team in August 
without explanation a day after signing a five-year, $5.3 million 
contract. 
</P>
<P>
	A reporter later found him in a Philadelphia hotel, where  
Underwood said he was torn between his religious faith and his 
football career. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood returned to football to support his family, and the  
Dolphins picked him up on waivers. He played one exhibition game on 
Sept. 2, then injured his shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dolphins said they are placing Underwood on the  
reserved-nonfootball injury list. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm really disappointed that as his coach, there wasn't  
something that I could do to help this guy accomplish what he wants 
to accomplish,'' Nick Saban, Underwood's coach at Michigan State, 
told Detroit TV station WJBK. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
