<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Political Donor's Home Searched </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- FBI agents on Friday searched the home of a  
political donor who was implicated in a fund-raising scandal by a 
former county Republican official. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency would not disclose what it sought or took from the  
Englewood home of David Chang. FBI spokeswoman Monica M. Patton 
said Chang was not charged or arrested. 
</P>
<P>
	Chang could not be reached for comment. The house does not have  
a listed number, and a message left at his international trading 
firm was not immediately returned. 
</P>
<P>
	Chang contributed $41,586 to candidates and organizations of  
both parties during the 1997-98 election cycle, according to Mother 
Jones magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, the former head of the Republican Party in New Jersey's  
Bergen County pleaded guilty to evading campaign finance rules. 
Berek Paul Don admitted he funneled up to $11,000 to the successful 
1996 Senate campaign of the county's Democratic congressman, Robert 
Torricelli. 
</P>
<P>
	Don said he and a onetime law partner took that sum in a  
corporate check labeled ``legal fees'' from Chang and used it to 
reimburse ``straw donors'' because Chang had asked him to get the 
money into Torricelli's campaign fund. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, Chang's company was a client of Don's law firm.  
</P>
<P>
	Federal election law limits individual contributions to $1,000  
per election to a single candidate for federal office, and 
prohibits corporate donations to candidates for federal office. 
</P>
<P>
	Chang also was linked to the campaign financing problems that  
toppled former Rep. Jay Kim, R-Calif. Chang cooperated with federal 
authorities and was not charged. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
