<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Replaces Longtime Pollster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore continued his campaign  
house cleaning Friday, replacing a longtime pollster, Mark Penn, 
with Democratic operative Harrison Hickman. 
</P>
<P>
	A senior Gore official, speaking on the condition of anonymity,  
said the move was made because Penn was unable to devote his full 
attention to the primary battle with former New Jersey Sen. Bill 
Bradley. Penn will continue polling for the Democratic National 
Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Hickman and his partner Kirk Brown will take over the polling  
operation from Penn, who had authority to hire other pollsters. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Gore supporters had complained privately that Penn had  
underestimated the threat posed by Bradley, though the official 
stressed that Gore's senior advisers considered Penn's polling 
accurate and insightful. The shakeup in the polling operation comes 
two days after Gore announced he was moving his headquarters to 
Tennessee in an effort to revitalize a campaign that was shaken by 
Bradley's surprisingly strong showing in primary voter polls and in 
the fund-raising race. 
</P>
<P>
	Hickman's other clients include the National Abortion and  
Reproductive Rights Action League and Democratic Rep. Marty Meehan, 
Sen. Barbara Mikulski of Maryland, Sen. John Edwards of North 
Carolina and Sen. Bob Kerrey of Nebraska, as well as Philadelphia 
mayor Ed Rendell, the newly installed general chairman of 
Democratic National Committee. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
