<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 10:54:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Possible Nazi Victims Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINSK, Belarus (AP) -- The remains of 375 people believed to be  
victims of the Nazis were found during excavation work near a 
Belarusian cathedral that had served as a Nazi prison, officials 
said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The remains were unearthed on the premises of the abandoned  
Assumption Cathedral in the northwestern city of Vitebsk, said an 
official in charge of the excavations, Alexander Gutsev, according 
to the Interfax news agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Experts believe the remains date from the early 1940s, the  
report said. The cathedral served as a Gestapo prison during the 
Nazi occupation of Belarus during World War II. Several bullets and 
cartridges found near the mass grave are similar in caliber to 
those used in German weapons during the war, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	A preliminary inspection indicated that up to 1,000 people may  
be buried in the cathedral grounds. 
</P>
<P>
	The report didn't say when the remains were discovered. Interior  
Ministry officials in Vitebsk and the capital Minsk confirmed the 
find, but provided no details. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
