<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Quake Hurts Hewlett-Packard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Hewlett-Packard Co. warned Friday it  
will report quarterly sales at the low end of Wall Street 
projections after an earthquake last month in Taiwan slowed 
production of parts that power its computers and other machines. 
</P>
<P>
	Hewlett-Packard is the first major U.S. technology company to  
formally warn of financial damage from the massive 7.6 magnitude 
earthquake last week in Taiwan, one of the world's top producers of 
the semiconductor chips used to run computers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Palo Alto, Calif.-based company is a major maker of  
computers, printers and imaging products. 
</P>
<P>
	``While the situation is still somewhat fluid, we are sure of  
some disruptions and delays in the PC supply chain,'' 
Hewlett-Packard chief executive Carly Fiorina said in a conference 
call with analysts. 
</P>
<P>
	Taiwan accounts for about 10 percent of semiconductors used  
worldwide, plus about 60 percent of the motherboards, the main 
circuit board for chips, analysts said. Taiwan also is a key 
supplier of memory chips, flat-panel screens used in notebook 
computers, small microprocessors used in toys and other consumer 
electronics, and core-logic chipsets, the chips that link the 
processor to the rest of the computer. 
</P>
<P>
	Fiorina said the company's revenue would grow about 10 percent  
in the fiscal fourth quarter, which ends Oct 30. Wall Street had 
expected Hewlett-Packard to report sales growth ranging from 10 
percent to 13 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	H-P's stock, which has been under pressure in recent months,  
fell 3.7 percent, down $3.37 1/2 a share to $87.37 1/2 in trading on the 
New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	But Hewlett-Packard said it would meet profit projections of 99  
cents a share in the quarter, according to the most recent survey 
of analysts by First Call Corp. In the year-earlier period, profit 
was $832 million, or 79 cents a share before charges, on sales of 
$12.2 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Hewlett-Packard also announced a realignment of its executive  
ranks to ensure accountability and teamwork to motivate its sales 
force. Fiorina suggested the changes would make it less 
conservative and more nimble in responding to competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Ann Livermore, the chief executive of its enterprise computing  
group and head of its Internet services business, will head its top 
100 business accounts. Antonio Perez will oversee digital imaging, 
and Duane Zitzner will head the servers and software business. 
Carolyn Ticknor will oversee the printer business. 





  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
