<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Votes on Violence to Fetuses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House, over the objections of abortion  
rights lawmakers, has approved legislation that would make it a 
crime to harm a fetus during a violent act against a pregnant 
woman. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters of the bill, passed Thursday by a 254-172 vote,  
argued that the fetus should have the same legal protections as the 
mother from criminal assault. Opponents said it was another attempt 
to erode abortion rights guaranteed by the 1973 Roe vs. Wade 
Supreme Court decision. 
</P>
<P>
	The intent was not to reopen the abortion debate, insisted the  
bill's sponsor, Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., but to ensure that the 
criminal who injures or kills a fetus ``is going to pay a separate 
debt to society.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration, calling it an ``unprecedented''  
effort to make the mother and fetus separate victims, threatened a 
presidential veto. Senate action on the bill this year is uncertain 
at best. 
</P>
<P>
	But the bill still served as the most visible showdown this year  
between supporters and opponents of abortion rights. 
</P>
<P>
	Family Research Council spokeswoman Janet Parshall said  
recognizing ``the personhood of the preborn child'' was a 
``profoundly significant moment in pro-life history.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kate Michelman, president of the National Abortion and  
Reproductive Rights Action League, said the bill ``does nothing to 
protect women against violence'' and is meant ``to forge new legal 
ground that would eventually undermine'' the Roe vs. Wade decision. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation makes it a separate offense to injure or kill a  
fetus in the commission of a federal crime of violence against a 
pregnant woman. 
</P>
<P>
	A person need not have knowledge of the pregnancy to be charged  
with harming a fetus. When an assailant intentionally kills or 
attempts to kill a fetus, the punishment is the same as that for 
similar acts against a person. 
</P>
<P>
	Exceptions are that the death penalty would not apply and the  
bill would not apply to abortions performed with the mother's 
consent. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 24 states have laws concerning violence against fetuses,  
and Graham said federal laws must also allow a prosecutor to bring 
murder charges when a fetus dies in an attack that the mother 
survives. 
</P>
<P>
	``How can you recognize the baby's need for prenatal care and  
reject the baby's right to protection from violence?'' House 
Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, asked abortion rights 
supporters. ``I just can't believe anyone could be that cruel, 
heartless and selfish.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents of the bill said its backers were equally callous in  
using a popular cause, stopping violence against women, to promote 
an anti-abortion agenda. ``This time they found a brand-new way of 
chipping away at a woman's right to choose,'' said Rep. Carolyn 
Maloney, D-N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent years, the most contentious abortion issue coming  
before Congress has been the effort to ban a form of late-term 
abortion opponents call ``partial birth abortion.'' But after two 
vetoes by President Clinton, the bill has not come up again this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House issued a statement saying it would veto the  
``Unborn Victims of Violence Act'' in its present form. The Justice 
Department, in a letter to Congress in September, said the 
identification of a fetus as a separate and distinct victim of 
crime is ``unprecedented as a matter of federal statute'' and could 
be seen as ``gratuitously plunging the federal government'' into a 
complex religious and scientific issue. 
</P>
<P>
	House Democrats, led by Rep. Zoe Lofgren, D-Calif., offered a  
substitute that would have created a federal criminal offense for 
violence against pregnant women without mentioning the fetus. It 
was defeated 224-201. 
</P>
<P>
	----	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is H.R. 2436.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
