<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pack's Bidwell Gets Help With Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Green Bay Packers punter Josh Bidwell  
could amass more than $100,000 in medical bills as he recovers from 
testicular cancer, but teammates and even school children want to 
help him. 
</P>
<P>
	The 23-year-old Bidwell so far has more than $50,000 in medical  
bills, but is ineligible for NFL medical benefits because he was 
never on Green Bay's active roster. Bidwell punted in exhibition 
games, but before the final one against Miami on Sept. 2, the 
Packers announced he was out for the season because of the cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Another reason Bidwell cannot get league money is that his  
injuries were not caused in a game, said Carl Francis of the NFL 
Players Association. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an unfortunate and an ironic situation,'' Francis said.  
</P>
<P>
	The punter's teammates have contributed about $50,000 out of  
their pockets to help out the fourth-round draft pick, said Green 
Bay players programs director Gil Byrd. 
</P>
<P>
	More funds are expected to be raised next week, when the Packers  
hold their annual golf tournament. A group of players and their 
wives also have organized a dinner and auction later in the month 
to benefit Bidwell. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the Packers' young fans want to help out, too. A group  
of middle school students in Appleton is holding a car wash 
Saturday to raise money for Bidwell's treatment and the American 
Cancer Society. 
</P>
<P>
	``The kids were talking about it, and they were saying Josh  
Bidwell is not getting insurance and this is not fair,'' said 
Madison Middle School teacher Denise Steiner, who is supervising 
the event. ``We all said, `What can we do?' And we decided, why not 
have a car wash?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bidwell said in an interview Thursday with The Post-Crescent of  
Appleton that his insurance under his father's policy expired at 
the beginning of the summer. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought I was OK through the NFL,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	``The moment I realized I wasn't insured was very difficult. It  
was the icing on the cake of a bunch of bad situations. The 
financial situation was one more burden I didn't need. I was 
concentrating on my form of cancer and ways to beat it. To find out 
the financial part was very stressful for my family and I.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bidwell, who is at his home in Eugene, Ore., for his recovery,  
was stunned when he heard of the children's event. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's amazing. It warms my heart to think a school is doing  
this for me,'' Bidwell said. ``I'm really in shock. I'm really 
floored by the love and the respect shown by these kids. They are 
going to wash cars in about 50-degree weather for a guy like me. I 
really don't know what to say about that. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm also so grateful to my teammates for helping me. I'm just  
some rookie who they knew for a couple of months. It's just such a 
nice feeling that both the Packers and the community are doing 
this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bidwell hopes to start kicking in January and is expecting to  
participate in minicamps in the spring. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mentally, I feel great now,'' he said. ``But physically, I  
still have a ways to go. When I stand up, it's a reality check. It 
hurts. ... But I know I'm healing and I will be well. I will be 
back with the Packers next year.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
