<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ford May Spin Off Parts Division </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. plans to spin off its auto parts  
division directly to shareholders and give wage and job guarantees 
to factory workers, The New York Times reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal is expected to be announced within a month, the Times  
reported, citing sources familiar with the matter. 
</P>
<P>
	What to do with Visteon Automotive Systems has been a problem  
for Ford as it tries to reach a new labor contract with the United 
Auto Workers. The union has opposed a spinoff of Visteon, which has 
28,500 UAW members, saying it could lead to pay cuts, plant 
closures and fewer union jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford had considered selling Visteon, but decided against it  
because of labor issues and tax considerations, the Times reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, the UAW reached tentative agreements with  
General Motors Corp. and Delphi Automotive Systems, which was spun 
off from GM. 
</P>
<P>
	The deals reportedly provided 185,000 workers with 3 percent pay  
raises each year for four years and a signing bonus of $1,350, 
among other things. 
</P>
<P>
	The union is expected to allow Ford to follow the same pattern  
for Visteon's 23,500 workers, making a tax-free spinoff of the 
division to shareholders an attractive option, the Times reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Visteon would reportedly agree to a four-year contract with the  
same wage, benefit and job protections reached in a Ford pact. 
</P>
<P>
	Visteon had $17.8 billion in revenue in 1998.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
