<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 03:30:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nieman Foundation Curator To Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- Bill Kovach, curator of the Nieman  
Foundation for Journalism at Harvard University, has announced he 
will step down from the post in June. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to the foundation's advisory board, Kovach, 67,  
cited ``personal and practical'' reasons for the decision. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to wanting to spend more time with his family,  
Kovach said he believes it's time for the program to be led by 
someone with broader knowledge of communications technology. 
</P>
<P>
	``The university and future fellows are, as we say these days,  
ready for an upgrade,'' Kovach wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Kovach said he also plans to write books, including a memoir.  
</P>
<P>
	Kovach came to Harvard as a Nieman fellow himself in 1988 after  
resigning as editor of the Atlanta Journal and Constitution 
following a dispute with the newspaper's owners over editorial 
independence. He was named curator of the program in August 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	Kovach, who submitted his resignation this week, is the third  
head of a major university-based journalism program to resign in 
the past year. James V. Risser, director of the John S. Knight 
Fellowships at Stanford, and Marvin Kalb, head of the Shorenstein 
Center for Press, Politics and Public Policy at the Kennedy School 
of Government at Harvard, announced their retirements earlier this 
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
