<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marilyn Monroe Suit Sold at Auction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The brown wool suit Marilyn Monroe wore when she  
married Joe DiMaggio in 1954 sold for $33,350 at auction. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit, with a white mink collar and six rhinestone buttons,  
was sold to an American collector who made the bid by telephone 
Thursday night. Its pre-sale price was valued between $15,000 to 
$20,000, Sotheby's auction house said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of Monroe's rhinestone jewelry and two photographs of her  
by Milton H. Greene also were part of Sotheby's ``Cocktail'' sale 
Thursday. The items, sold as one lot, fetched $11,500, from an 
anonymous phone bidder. 
</P>
<P>
	An evening gown worn by Princess Diana in 1989 failed to sell.  
Diana wore the burgundy silk velvet gown gathered and draped bodice 
for an event at the French embassy. Its pre-sale estimate was 
between $30,000 and $40,000. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991001.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 15:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> HUD Aids Welfare-to-Work Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Putting dollars behind the effort to guide  
welfare recipients to employment, the government awarded $280 
million in vouchers designed to help about 50,000 families across 
the country. 
</P>
<P>
	This initial distribution of the welfare-to-work vouchers by the  
Department of Housing and Urban Development will subsidize rents of 
low-income families receiving welfare or recently off welfare to 
enable them to rent apartments near available jobs, child care and 
transportation. 
</P>
<P>
	The vouchers will be distributed to 121 state and local housing  
agencies, Indian tribes and tribally designated housing agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	The eight largest awards were designated by Congress and went to  
Anchorage, Alaska; San Bernardino County, Calif.; Miami-Dade 
County; Prince George's County, Md.; Kansas City, Mo.; Charlotte, 
N.C.; New York City; and Cleveland. Each of the largest awards was 
about $4 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're helping members of struggling families get jobs so they  
can work their way out of poverty and build better lives,'' HUD 
Secretary Andrew Cuomo said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our economy is booming, and many suburban employers can't find  
all the workers they need. When we help unemployed people get 
housing closer to these unfilled jobs, we enable them to move off 
the welfare rolls and onto payrolls,'' Cuomo said. 
</P>
<P>
	The vouchers are designed to correct an imbalance that has  
hindered the transition for some who left welfare. It arises 
because two-thirds of new jobs are in suburbs, while most welfare 
recipients live in rural areas or central cities, Cuomo said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those of us blessed with good housing and good jobs shouldn't  
turn our backs on those left behind,'' Cuomo said. 
</P>
<P>
	In August, a federal report showed the percentage of Americans  
on welfare at the lowest level since 1967. Welfare rolls were 49 
percent lower than their all-time high in 1994, and 29 states had 
cut their rolls by more than half. 
</P>
<P>
	As of March, just 2.7 percent of the population -- or 7.3 million  
Americans -- was on welfare, the fewest since Lyndon Johnson's 
presidency. In 1967, the figure was 2.5 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991001.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 13:00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> UAW Presents Tentative GM Contracts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- The United Auto Workers presented tentative  
contracts with General Motors Corp. and its former parts unit to 
its local union leaders Friday, while negotiations at Ford Motor 
Co. intensified. 
</P>
<P>
	About 500 union officials gathered here to hear details of the  
contracts covering 185,000 workers at GM and Delphi Automotive 
Systems. The union said the deal gives the average assembly worker 
$29,900 in wage increases, bonuses and holidays over the next four 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	The union's executive council unanimously recommended the  
contract to the local unions, where ratification votes are expected 
to be completed by Oct. 10. 
</P>
<P>
	UAW President Stephen P. Yokich said labor relations between GM  
and the UAW have improved since last summer's 54-day strike at two 
Flint parts factories. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Hawkins, chairman of Local 598 in Flint, said the deal  
gives workers more money and greater job security, and hopefully 
sets the stage for smoother relations between the union and GM. 
</P>
<P>
	UAW officials and Ford spokesman Ed Miller said committee  
meetings were planned at Ford through the weekend. Miller said 
there was progress in the talks. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Times reported Friday that Ford plans to spin off  
its auto parts division to shareholders and give wage and job 
guarantees to factory workers -- the same steps GM took with Delphi 
when it spun it off last May. 
</P>
<P>
	The possible spinoff of Ford's Visteon Automotive Systems has  
been opposed by UAW leaders, who fear that Visteon's 23,500 UAW 
members would face pay cuts, plant closures and fewer union jobs 
under an independent company. 
</P>
<P>
	The Times said an announcement about Visteon was expected in  
about a month. Yokich said Friday the issue had not been discussed 
yet with Ford. ``They know more about it than I do,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford declined to comment on the report.  
</P>
<P>
	The GM and Delphi deals closely follow the UAW's contract with  
DaimlerChrysler AG, according to a union summary of the agreements. 
They give workers an annual increase of 3 percent a year for all 
four years, a $1,350 signing bonus and improved cost of living 
adjustments. 
</P>
<P>
	The new deals have several clauses aimed at protecting union  
jobs. If employment drops below 80 percent of a set level in a 
bargaining unit, GM and Delphi must replace each job lost. If the 
level is between 80 percent and 90 percent, one of every two empty 
positions must be filled; between 90 and 100 percent, the ratio is 
1-to-3. 
</P>
<P>
	The job minimums drop 5 percent over the life of the contract.  
</P>
<P>
	GM and Delphi also agreed not to spin off any division into a  
separate business or close or sell any factories. GM and Delphi 
also pledged to take a neutral stance toward union organizing 
drives, and would not take work away from a plant that forms a 
union. 
</P>
<P>
	The Delphi contract allows workers to transfer back to GM when  
openings occur, and gives them until Jan. 1 to retire with GM 
pensions. If Delphi goes out of business during the contract, the 
workers' layoff benefits would come from GM. 
</P>
<P>
	The contract also improves pensions -- an important goal for the  
UAW's older workforce. For a GM or Delphi worker who retires with 
30 years of experience and is not yet eligible for Social Security, 
monthly benefits would rise from $2,295 under the existing pact to 
$2,730 by the end of the new agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies also increased the lump sum payment retirees would  
get based on inflation. If inflation increases by up to 2 percent a 
year, retirees would get a lump sum of $885. 
</P>
<P>
	There were a few new clauses. GM agreed to involve the union  
earlier in the design process of a new vehicle or part, including 
fuel cell projects. Workers won the right to ask for a review of a 
work assignment if they believe it to be dangerous. 
</P>
<P>
	GM and Delphi will hire 3,000 new apprentices in skilled trades,  
and increased the maximum moving payment to $23,500, a raise of 
$1,500. Workers will get the federal Election Day off in 2000 and 
2002, and the UAW flag will be flown over plants the union 
represents. 
</P>
<P>
	UAW negotiators with Ford have presented the DaimlerChrysler  
contract to the company as a starting point. The Times reported 
that the union is expected to allow Ford to follow the lead of GM's 
spinoff of Delphi, which the union also opposed. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford had considered selling Visteon, but decided against it  
because of labor issues and tax considerations, the Times reported. 
Visteon had $17.8 billion in revenue in 1998. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991001.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 18:40:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Teacher Drops Restroom Fee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAPHNE, Ala. (AP) -- A high school teacher who charged students  
25 cents to go to the bathroom ended the practice after a student 
who didn't have the money soiled himself. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheila Floyd said her 14-year-old son could not go to to the  
restroom during Robert McKillion's computer class because he didn't 
have a quarter. The boy waited until the end of class but could not 
make it to the restroom in time. 
</P>
<P>
	``The teacher told him that he should have said it was an  
emergency,'' Mrs. Floyd said Thursday. ``He shouldn't have had to 
do that. Kids don't like to call attention to themselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McKillion, who teaches at Daphne High School in southwest  
Alabama, did not return a call for comment Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	But Principal Barry Pennington said students in McKillion's four  
computer classes unanimously approved the charges. Pennington said 
the intention was to use the accumulated money for a pizza party at 
the end of the semester. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said students were not required to pay.  
</P>
<P>
	District Attorney David Whetstone said he would investigate.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't believe you can take money from students to go to the  
bathroom, even if the payment is voluntary,'' Whetstone said. ``I'm 
quite sure we could not treat prisoners that way.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991001.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 14:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Manufacturing Grew in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The nation's manufacturing sector grew in  
September much more strongly than expected, while prices of raw 
materials soared to the highest level in more than four years, 
according to a business survey released Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The report by the National Association of Purchasing Management  
confirms that industry is recovering from the setbacks of the Asian 
financial crisis and provides further evidence that the overall 
economy rebounded from a sluggish second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, the Commerce Department said the personal income of  
Americans climbed in August for the eighth consecutive month. But 
their spending rose faster, leaving the nation's savings rate 
matching a record low. 
</P>
<P>
	The combination of reports kept alive Wall Street's fears that  
the economy is overheating, sending stocks and bonds tumbling on 
worries that the Federal Reserve will try to cool things off by 
raising interest rates for a third time this year. Fed 
policy-makers meet Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average was down nearly 153 at one  
point Friday and closed with a drop of 63.95 points at 10,273.00. 
</P>
<P>
	The purchasing managers' group said the manufacturing sector  
grew in September for the eighth consecutive month. Its index rose 
to 57.8 percent -- the highest since a reading of 59.2 percent in 
November 1994 -- and was up sharply from 54.2 percent in August. 
Analysts had expected little change in September. 
</P>
<P>
	A reading of more than 50 is a sign of an expanding industrial  
economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The index is closely watched because it is the first national  
reading for September on U.S. manufacturing performance, a key 
sector of the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The government said earlier this week that the U.S. economy grew  
at an annual rate of just 1.6 percent in the April-June quarter, 
but many analysts viewed the spring lethargy as a brief pause, 
predicting stronger growth for the second half of this year. 
</P>
<P>
	David Huether, director of economic analysis for the National  
Association of Manufacturers, said Friday's purchasing managers' 
report appeared to support expectations of renewed economic 
strength. He said he believed the nation's gross domestic product 
grew by at least 3 percent in the July-September period. 
</P>
<P>
	Huether said that while there were signs of recovery from the  
Asian crisis, which began in the summer of 1997, exports still 
remain sluggish. ``I don't see exports increasing a lot until 
probably mid-2000,'' Huether said. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's economic expansion, which began in March 1991,  
already is the longest period of peacetime growth in U.S. history. 
It would match the record of 106 months -- set in the period of 
February 1961 until December 1969 -- of it continues through January 
2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Norbert J. Ore, chairman of the management group's business  
survey committee, said in a statement releasing the September 
results that NAPM's price index jumped to its highest level since 
May 1995, ``indicating that manufacturers continue to pay higher 
prices for their purchases.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The price index surged to 67.6 percent in September from 59.8  
percent in August. That was the highest since 70.5 percent in May 
1995, the association said. 
</P>
<P>
	The price reading could signal a squeeze for manufacturers, said  
Mark Vitner, an economist at First Union Corp. in Charlotte, N.C. 
But he said it does not necessarily mean a rise in consumer prices. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's little evidence manufacturers will be able to pass on  
higher prices to consumers because of a lot of import 
competition,'' he said. As a result, he said, manufacturers 
probably will have to find ways to absorb the added costs or to 
increase productivity further. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department report showed that personal income --  
which includes wages, interest and government benefits -- rose 0.5 
percent in August, the eighth straight monthly increase. 
</P>
<P>
	The increase was a bit more than the 0.4 percent forecast by  
analysts and followed a 0.2 percent increase in July. 
</P>
<P>
	But spending went up 0.9 percent in August, also more than  
analysts had expected. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, the nation's savings rate -- savings as a percentage  
of after-tax income -- fell to minus 1.5 percent, matching the 
record low set in May. 
</P>
<P>
	In another report, the Commerce Department said that  
construction spending fell an unexpected 0.4 percent in August to a 
seasonally adjusted annual rate of $692 billion, a sign that one of 
the economy's strongest sectors is beginning to slow. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
