<DOCNO> APW19991001.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 03:10:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                           *Eva Israelsen    	
</P>
<P>
	LOGAN, Utah (AP) -- Eva Israelsen, who lived long enough to have  
271 great-grandchildren, died Thursday, five days before her 105th 
birthday. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Israelsen appeared in Life magazine in October 1993 in an  
article noting the birth of her 200th and 201st 
great-grandchildren. Since then, her progeny has grown to 271 
great-grandchildren and 40 great-great-grandchildren. She had 11 
original children, and they had 67 kids. 
</P>
<P>
	Born Eva May Butler on Oct. 5, 1894, she met Victor E. Israelsen  
while attending Utah Agricultural College, now Utah State 
University, in the 1920s and later married him. 
</P>
<P>
	They spent their lives on a dairy farm. Mrs. Israelsen remained  
active well past her 100th birthday, walking at least a mile a day. 

</P>
<P>
                           *James M. Kelso    	
</P>
<P>
	PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- James M. Kelso, a popular state  
representative and restaurateur, died Wednesday from cancer. He was 
55. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelso was a political novice in 1996 when he ran for the state  
House as a Democrat. He became a deputy majority leader. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelso also was a partner in the Coast Guard House restaurant in  
Narragansett for 20 years. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Jack Kiefer    	
</P>
<P>
	PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Jack Kiefer, a two-time winner on  
the Senior PGA Tour who was diagnosed last year with cancer in his 
spinal cord, died Sept. 24. He was 59. 
</P>
<P>
	Kiefer won the 1994 Ralphs Senior Classic and the du Maurier  
Champions in 1997, when he finished 16th on the money list. He 
played 12 events in 1998 before he was diagnosed with cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Kiefer was a pitcher for Millersville State College in 1961, and  
his knuckleball earned him a contract with the Detroit Tigers. But 
after three days in camp, he left baseball and took up golf. 
</P>
<P>
	He turned professional in 1967 and joined the senior tour in  
1990. He had a reputation as an iron man for playing at least 30 
tournaments a year every season except 1992. 

</P>
<P>
                     *Cotesworth Pinckney Lewis    	
</P>
<P>
	WILLIAMSBURG, Va. (AP) -- The Rev. Cotesworth Pinckney Lewis, who  
once told President Lyndon Johnson that Americans needed a 
``straightforward explanation'' about the Vietnam war, died 
Wednesday. He was 86. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis' 1967 sermon to the visiting Johnson at Bruton Parish  
Episcopal Church prompted the church's vestry and the governor of 
Virginia to apologize to the president. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis was rector of the church from 1956-85. The congregation  
more than doubled during his tenure. 
</P>
<P>
	A native of Birmingham, Ala., Lewis earned two divinity degrees  
and spent nearly 50 years in the ministry. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Dmitry Likhachyov    	
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Dmitry Likhachyov, a literary historian who was  
one of Russia's most respected cultural figures, died Thursday. He 
was 92. 
</P>
<P>
	Likhachyov, sometimes described as ``the conscience of Russia,''  
spent four years, from 1928-32, in one of the Soviet Union's most 
dreaded prison camps, Solovki, located in a former monastery on a 
northern Russian island. 
</P>
<P>
	Afterward, he became a prominent defender of the country's  
cultural heritage. He fought to protect the purity of texts written 
by Russia's most famous poet, Alexander Pushkin, to whom 
counterfeiters have long attributed fake diaries. 
</P>
<P>
	A year ago, President Boris Yeltsin awarded Likhachyov one of  
the country's highest honors, the Order of St. Andrew, for 
contributions to the development of national culture. 
</P>
<P>
	Likhachyov, an expert in Russian literature of the 11th-17th  
centuries, held honorary doctorates from Oxford and several other 
foreign universities. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Jules Rind    	
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Jules Rind, a veteran of radio news and  
sports, died Sept. 23 of acute leukemia. He was 82. 
</P>
<P>
	His career of about 60 years included stints with the Mutual  
Broadcasting System, NBC radio, the U.S. Information Agency, and 
local stations WPEN, WFLN and WWDB. At various times, he also 
broadcast games of the Phillies, the Eagles, and University of 
Pennsylvania football. 
</P>
<P>
	Rind covered the Three Mile Island nuclear accident for NBC and  
served as the sole radio announcer for many radio networks when 
Pope John Paul II went from Veterans Stadium to Logan Circle in 
1979. 
</P>
<P>
	Rind is survived by his wife of 50 years, Helen High Rind; a  
son, a daughter and two grandchildren. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Arville Schaleben    	
</P>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Arville Schaleben, a reporter and editor who  
filed dispatches from six continents and interviewed Will Rogers in 
Alaska just before the humorist's death in an airplane crash, died 
Thursday. He was 92. 
</P>
<P>
	Schaleben was hired by The Milwaukee Journal as a reporter in  
1929 and became an assistant city editor about eight years later. 
He was named executive editor in 1962 and an associate editor soon 
after. 
</P>
<P>
	He was a major factor in the Journal's coverage of water  
pollution, which won a Pulitzer Prize in 1967, retired editor 
Richard Leonard said. 
</P>
<P>
	Schaleben interviewed Rogers while in Alaska to write about the  
more than 1,100 members of Depression-era families from the Midwest 
who colonized the Matanuska Valley as part of President Roosevelt's 
New Deal. The interview would be Rogers' last. Shortly after that 
his plane crashed, killing both Rogers and pilot Wiley Post. 
</P>
<P>
	Schaleben was a past president of the Wisconsin Associated Press  
Managing Editors Association and sat on the national APME board. 
</P>
<P>
	From 1936-40 he was president of the Milwaukee Press Club.  
</P>
<P>
	He lectured at about 50 college campuses and, after retirement  
from The Journal, taught journalism at the University of 
Wisconsin-Madison, Northwestern University in Evanston, Ill., and 
Indiana University in Bloomington. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include his wife and four children.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991001.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 17:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> State Farm Deliberations To Resume </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MARION, Ill. (AP) -- Jurors deliberating a breach of contract  
case against State Farm went home Friday without reaching a 
decision. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury is scheduled to resume its work on the class-action  
lawsuit at 9 a.m. Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for policyholders suing the Bloomington-based insurer  
claim the company's requirement that body shops use generic 
auto-body repair parts on its customers' cars violates its 
contractual promise to restore vehicles to the way they were before 
an accident. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics of so-called aftermarket parts say they fail to meet the  
standards for fit, finish, corrosion protection and, in some cases, 
safety, provided by original equipment parts. Aftermarket parts are 
modeled on parts made for automakers but produced without benefit 
of factory specifications. 
</P>
<P>
	State Farm says use of the parts does not affect driver safety  
and helps hold premiums down. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate consumer fraud count being decided by Williamson  
County Judge John Speroni, the lawyers are accusing State Farm of 
consumer fraud for concealing concerns about the parts' quality. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, the plaintiffs are seeking nearly $5.4 billion in  
damages. The lawsuit combines the potential claims of 4.7 million 
current and former State Farm policyholders. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991001.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 15:00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Candidates Woo Christian Coalition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As Republican presidential candidates showed  
off their conservative credentials Friday, Christian Coalition 
founder Pat Robertson deemed Gary Bauer a ``lost cause,'' Elizabeth 
Dole ``a Southern belle'' and George W. Bush ``worthy of support.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Pat Buchanan, Robertson gave a stern warning that Christian  
conservatives will desert him if he ditches the GOP for a 
third-party presidential run with the Reform Party. 
</P>
<P>
	Reform supporters are ``180 degrees out in terms of social  
issues. They don't share any of the views that Pat Buchanan claimed 
to espouse so vociferously,'' Robertson told a news conference at 
the coalition's annual ``Road to Victory'' conference. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't see him taking many Christian conservatives with him --  
not to the Reform Party,'' Robertson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The two-day conference drew 3,500 of the coalition's 2.1 million  
members and six of the eight Republicans running for president. 
</P>
<P>
	It was Bush, the Texas governor and front-runner for the GOP  
nomination, who filled all the seats -- and lined the perimeter's 
standing room -- in a cavernous hotel ballroom. ``Every child born 
and unborn must be protected by law and welcomed to life,'' he 
declared. 
</P>
<P>
	He advocated parental-notification laws on abortion, saying  
``Parents should be the first to help, not the last to know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robertson, the religious broadcaster who commands the  
grass-roots army of Christian activists that helped sweep 
Republicans into control of Congress in the 1994 elections, said he 
will not endorse any presidential candidate during the primary 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	But his preferences were clear.  
</P>
<P>
	In an interview, Robertson all but dismissed Bauer, whose  
teen-aged supporters in campaign T-shirts worked Friday's 
convention in droves. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's not going to win,'' Robertson told The New York Times.  
``You don't win with 1 or 2 percent. Most people are not terribly 
keen on riding a lost cause.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer, who once ran the Family Research Council and prides  
himself on his Christian conservative appeal, appeared taken aback 
when informed of Robertson's remark. He said he was disappointed 
Robertson was not taking a straw poll of members at this year's 
convention. ``Then we wouldn't have to sit around and speculate on 
where the leaders are,'' Bauer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Robertson said some of what he's heard from Bush's ``centrist''  
campaign ``so far would cause me to believe he would be worthy of 
support of the coalition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Robertson added he is eager to see a series of debates  
force Bush to ``crystallize his positions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his speech, Bauer promised that, unlike Bush, he would make a  
judge's opposition to abortion rights a prerequisite for 
appointment to any federal bench. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, Bauer shouted, ``My judges are going to understand that  
marriage is between a man and a woman -- not two men.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dole took the stage to the rolling crescendos of the music from  
``Gone With the Wind'' and talked of her religious upbringing. She 
called her grandmother's tattered Bible her dearest treasure. 
</P>
<P>
	``My commitment is to strive to lean on the lord with my whole  
heart, reading his word daily and earnestly seeking his will in my 
life,'' Dole said. ``I learned from the best -- President Reagan -- 
that you have to lead with the convictions of your heart, not with 
the latest polling data.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robertson said later that she gave a ``wonderful speech'' and  
enjoys ``real support'' from his members. Asked to explain the 
music organizers chose for her entrance, Robertson boyishly 
shrugged. ``She's the Southern belle, right?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch promised to be a ``conservative president  
with guts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barbara Penberth of Bethlehem, Penn., remained undecided.  
``These 20-minute speeches don't get you anywhere. It's just 
rah-rah,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona Sen. John McCain declined an invitation to speak. And  
though Buchanan appeared on Saturday's program, he canceled earlier 
this week, his campaign said. Alan Keyes was addressing the Friday 
evening session. Steve Forbes issued an open invitation to picnic 
by the pool after his Saturday morning speech. 
</P>
<P>
	From atop a massive, political-convention-styled dais and  
accompanied by the ``Rocky'' fight song, Robertson opened the 
conference with an eye on the 2000 elections and appeal to his 
followers. ``If we aren't in the field in this coming election, 
Republicans will lose,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton was Robertson's primary target. ``As we  
prepare for a new millennium, I want to start with cleansing the 
highest office of the land from the sleaze and the equivocation and 
the moral rot which has embarrassed us all,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Aside from Clinton, the villain in abstentia here was Minnesota  
Gov. Jesse Ventura, who, in a Playboy magazine interview this week, 
called organized religion ``a sham and a crutch for weak-minded 
people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robertson said Ventura was ``off his rocker.'' Bauer suggested  
the former pro-wrestler change his name to ``Jesse 'the Bigot' 
Ventura.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991001.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 15:00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
