<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Sample Stock Portfolio Survives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	There's no getting around the fact that the third quarter was a  
loser for stocks -- even the most well-diversified portfolios took a 
big hit. But a sample portfolio for small investors put together by 
The Associated Press found a small hedge in a once-unlikely place: 
Pacific Rim stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	The portfolio, which contains three mutual funds and three  
widely-held stocks, lost 6.5 percent of its value during the 
quarter, faring slightly worse than the Dow Jones industrial 
average, which lost nearly 5.8 percent, and just beating the 6.6 
percent decline in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index. 
</P>
<P>
	But the portfolio, put together in October 1997, is still up  
nearly 8.2 percent for the year, behind the Dow's 12.6 percent but 
ahead of the S&AMP;P's 4.4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Worries about interest rates dominated Wall Street during the  
quarter, pulling major market indexes including the Dow industrials 
down from record highs. 
</P>
<P>
	The portfolio's worst performer was Coca-Cola, which fell 22.2  
percent as the company's own problems, including a warning that 
third-quarter earnings would fall short of expectations, were 
compounded by the overall market's malaise. 
</P>
<P>
	A relatively minor 1.4 percent drop in Wal-Mart's stock helped  
lessen some of the damage to the portfolio. The third stock 
holding, IBM, was off 6.4 percent during the quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The brightest spot in the portfolio was the Morgan Stanley Dean  
Witter Pacific Growth Fund, which had the only gain among the 
portfolio's six holdings. The fund, which along with other Asian 
investments continued its recovery from devastating losses that 
began two years ago, was up 4.5 percent in the just-ended quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan and other Asian nations showed increasing signs that their  
economies were regaining strength, and investors who have patiently 
waited for Pacific stocks and funds to recover found these 
investments were a good buffer against losses in U.S. investments. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the T. Rowe Price U.S. Treasury Long-Term Fund, added  
to the portfolio to help cushion against stock market declines, 
fell short of that goal during the third quarter. The fund suffered 
a 1.7 percent loss as the bond market was consumed by its own 
interest rate concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	The last component of the portfolio, the Vanguard Index Trust  
500 Portfolio fund, which tracks the S&AMP;P 500, fell 6.5 percent 
</P>
<P>
	The portfolio was valued at $25,299.85 at its inception and was  
worth $39,242.51 as the third quarter ended. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
