<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nixon Secret Tapes To Be Destroyed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Copies of President Nixon's tapes wound around  
5,000 plastic reels will be shredded and burned in the next few 
months because they contain personal and political talk the court 
says the public isn't allowed to hear. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Archives holds 3,700 hours of Nixon tapes the  
government seized when the president resigned in August 1974 
following a break-in of the Democratic National Committee 
headquarters at the Watergate complex and the White House cover-up 
that followed. 
</P>
<P>
	Archives spokeswoman Susan Cooper emphasized that no original  
tapes are being destroyed, saying those being destroyed are just 
copies made from the originals. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are not archival records,'' she said. ``We are simply  
cleaning house and we're doing it in response to the court 
ruling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The tape from the copies ``will be taken off the reels and  
deposited in burn bags,'' said Ms. Cooper. ``We will take them to 
the Pentagon where they are shredded and then burned. All of these 
procedures are witnessed by two of our employees.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1977, the Supreme Court ordered the archives to destroy or  
return to the Nixon estate all portions of the tapes that contain 
personal or private conversations, such as Nixon's chats with his 
wife or daughters. The court also ordered the archives to destroy 
or return purely political conversations in which Nixon was 
speaking as head of the Republican Party, not president. Subsequent 
court rulings affirmed the 1977 decision. 
</P>
<P>
	John Taylor, executive director of the Nixon Library &AMP;  
Birthplace Foundation in Yorba Linda, Calif., said he is not 
disturbed by the planned destruction of the tapes. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the course of working on the tapes over the last quarter  
century, the archives has made all kinds of different copies -- some 
of which are no longer state-of-the-art and are not digital,'' 
Taylor said. ``With all this dramatic burning and splicing and 
everything that the archives talks about, not a single second of 
information is being lost or destroyed. They're not destroying 
anything that's otherwise irreplaceable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While no portions of the original Nixon tapes are being  
destroyed now, the archives is working on a tedious project to cut 
an estimated 15,000 snippets of conversation determined to be 
personal, private or political that are scattered throughout the 
fragile originals. This project was also required by the 1977 court 
decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're waiting to get a response from the Nixon estate as to  
what they want us to do with the excised material,'' said Karl 
Weissenbach, director of Nixon materials at the archives. ``It's up 
to them whether we can dispose of it or return it to the Nixon 
estate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although Nixon resigned 25 years ago, only about 420 hours of  
the 3,700 hours of his tape recordings have been released. On 
Tuesday, the archives plans to release 445 more hours of Nixon 
tapes recorded in 1971. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
