<HEADLINE> Five Family Members Shot in N.C. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WAYNESVILLE, N.C. (AP) -- Five family members who had just come  
home from a fair were shot to death by two men who stole their 
pickup truck and car, police said. One suspect was arrested Friday 
and charged with murder. 
</P>
<P>
	Shotgun shells littered the winding driveway leading to the  
rural home where the victims were slain Thursday night. Four were 
found dead inside, while the fifth was outside. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators said the killers apparently stole the pickup but  
wrecked it at the bottom of the family's driveway, went back and 
took another car, which was discovered smashed into a guard rail on 
Interstate 40 two miles east of the murder scene. 
</P>
<P>
	Charles Wesley Roache, 25, was caught by a neighbor of the  
victims and later charged with murder. The neighbor held him at 
gunpoint until police arrived, while the other suspect fled. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are good people who live down here,'' Haywood County  
Sheriff Tom Alexander said. ``They look out for each other.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About 50 officers, aided by tracking dogs and helicopters,  
searched the rugged Blue Ridge Mountain foothills for the second 
man, who was believed to be on foot. 
</P>
<P>
	David Barnes, an agent with the State Bureau of Investigation,  
said blood was found in both vehicles, meaning the gunman was 
probably injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander identified the victims as Earl Phillips, 72; his wife,  
Cora, 71; their son Eddie, 40; their daughter-in-law, Mitzi, 44; 
and their granddaughter, Katie, 14. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're good people, they were churchgoing people, they never  
harmed nobody,'' neighbor Rita Messer said. ``It's awful. You ain't 
safe in your own home, you're not safe in church. I don't know what 
this world is coming to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The elder Phillipses were retired. Eddie Phillips was a dump  
truck driver, and his wife worked at a textile plant and ran a 
beauty shop out of her home, relatives said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is hard to comprehend something like this happening where,  
you know, nothing ever happens,'' said Robert Rose, a 66-year-old 
cousin of Earl Phillips. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
