<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Closer to SBC Merger Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators are nearing a decision on  
the fate of the proposed merger between Ameritech Corp. and SBC 
Communications, which would create the nation's largest local 
telephone company. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Communications Commission approval is the last step in  
completing the deal -- originally valued at $57 billion. The Justice 
Department and state regulators have already signed off on it. 
</P>
<P>
	Industry officials and analysts have predicted that the deal --  
which brings together two regional Bell companies -- would go 
through, but with conditions to preserve competition in local 
markets. The combined business would control 57 million, or 
one-third, of the nation's local phone lines spread across 13 
states. 
</P>
<P>
	FCC Chairman Bill Kennard voted to approve the deal several  
weeks ago, according to agency sources speaking on condition of 
anonymity. Two other commissioners, Gloria Tristani and Susan Ness, 
also have voted on the matter but aides would not say whether they 
supported or opposed the merger. 
</P>
<P>
	Only one commissioner has not voted, according to the FCC  
sources. Commissioner Michael Powell's office would not reveal 
whether he had voted. Calls to Commissioner Harold 
Furchtgott-Roth's office were not returned. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal needs only three votes for approval, but all five  
commissioners must cast a vote for the action to be binding. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennard has placed the merger on the agenda for the commission's  
Oct. 8 meeting to force a final decision on the matter, but it 
could come before then. 
</P>
<P>
	The 13 states involved in the proposed merger are Arkansas,  
California, Connecticut, Kansas, Missouri, Nevada, Oklahoma, Texas, 
Illinois, Indiana, Michigan, Ohio and Wisconsin. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC's staff recommended approval of the deal, based on  
conditions that the two companies had submitted to the government. 
Under the deal, SBC-Ameritech would enter 30 new markets within 30 
months to compete with established local phone companies. It also 
would establish a separate subsidiary to provide advanced 
telecommunications services such as high-speed Internet access. At 
least 10 percent of its upgraded services would go to low-income 
regions. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies also would have to provide deep discounts on key  
pieces of their networks to competitors who want to buy them. 
Failure to meet the conditions could mean stiff penalties. Just for 
failing to meet the new market deadline, the companies could face a 
$40 million fine for each market, up to a maximum of $1.2 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	San Antonio-based SBC and Chicago-based Ameritech say the merger  
is good for consumers. They contend it will spur local phone 
competition and possibly reduce prices, accelerate the rollout of 
high-speed Internet access and data services and create jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	But long-distance companies trying to get into the local phone  
market -- including MCI, Sprint and AT&AMP;T -- said the concessions were 
accompanied by so many other limitations that they would do nothing 
to aid competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer groups also have opposed the deal, saying they do not  
believe the merger conditions go far enough to protect the public 
interest. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
