<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ohio Mayor Girds for Toughest Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BROOKLYN, Ohio (AP) -- Mayor John Coyne has run City Hall his way  
for 52 years, longer than any of his colleagues across the nation 
have been in office. 
</P>
<P>
	Day in, day out, he's balanced the books of this Cleveland  
suburb, pushed through groundbreaking laws and led the Cuyahoga 
County Democratic Party. He's been courted by presidents and 
presidential candidates, and pictures of him with everyone from 
Jimmy Carter to Robert Kennedy hang in his memorabilia-stuffed 
office. 
</P>
<P>
	But at 82, the spry, straight-talking mayor may be in his  
toughest political fight yet against an opponent who hadn't been 
born when Coyne was first elected. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first time, the party has endorsed Coyne's opponent,  
Kenneth Patton, in Brooklyn's nonpartisan mayoral election on Nov. 
2. 
</P>
<P>
	The move punishes Coyne for backing Republican Gov. Bob Taft's  
successful 1998 campaign -- a ``mortal sin,'' said Jimmy Dimora, 
chairman of the county's Democratic Party. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Coyne backed Taft because of bad blood between the mayor  
and Lee Fisher, the Democratic gubernatorial candidate. The mayor 
will say only that he backed Taft because he thought the Republican 
would do more for Ohio's schools. 
</P>
<P>
	``If people think by any stretch of the imagination I'm the only  
Democrat who voted for Taft, they've got a lot to think about,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Coyne says he doesn't regret his decision. It's true to form,  
supporters and critics agree: The mayor's always done things 
according his own plan. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Conference of Mayors believes Coyne, first elected in  
1947, is the nation's longest-serving mayor currently in office. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters say he's kept his job through a mix of tight control  
over the city's money and by offering extensive public services for 
the nearly 12,000 residents in Brooklyn, just outside Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	The city has received a dozen recent state awards for  
bookkeeping. It offers services like $5 snow removal and grass 
cutting for seniors and a host of recreational facilities, 
including indoor and outdoor swimming pools, racquetball courts and 
batting cages. 
</P>
<P>
	It is the same community that in 1966 passed a law requiring  
seat belts for drivers, a move considered a national first. This 
year came another pioneering rule: a ban on cellular telephone use 
while driving unless both hands are on the wheel. 
</P>
<P>
	But Coyne's big-boss style has its critics, who say he holds  
grudges and is unable to tolerate dissent. 
</P>
<P>
	As county Democratic chairman from 1982-93, Coyne earned the  
nickname ``the Irish Godfather.'' Former county Commissioner Tim 
Hagan and ex-Congressman Ed Feighan, a Democrat, once blasted him 
in a joint statement. ``To those who think Fidel Castro is the last 
dictator in the Western Hemisphere,'' they said, ``come to Cuyahoga 
County.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Patton, 48, was Brooklyn's service director for 17 years until  
quitting last December to become public works director in nearby 
Parma. 
</P>
<P>
	Both men say they want to improve public services. But Patton  
said he's offering as much a change in style as in substance. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to talk to the people,'' he said. ``I'm just letting  
them know that I would not be the old iron-fisted mayor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coyne says he can only improve as mayor in the next four years.  
Would he ever consider retiring? 
</P>
<P>
	``You retire when you're in a hole in the ground,'' he said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991001.0051 </DOCNO>
