<HEADLINE> EU Clears Siemens-Fujitsu Venture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- European Union regulators Friday  
granted antitrust approval to a joint venture between Japan's 
Fujitsu Ltd. and Siemens AG of Germany that will create one of 
Europe's largest personal computer vendors. 
</P>
<P>
	The approval came after the companies agreed to reduce their  
hold on the market for financial workstations like automatic teller 
machines and cash dispensers. 
</P>
<P>
	The European Commission said Siemens has agreed to sell its  
subsidiary Siemens Nixdorf Retail and Banking Systems GmbH, to 
address ``serious competitive concerns in the financial 
workstations market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two companies announced their joint-venture in June. It will  
have estimated sales of over $8.1 billion for fiscal 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agreement, Siemens and Fujitsu will cooperate in PCs,  
server and mainframe computer systems, aiming to achieve a position 
among the world's three leading manufacturers in the computer 
industry. 
</P>
<P>
	A new company, called Fujitsu Siemens Computers, is expected to  
start operations this month and will be active in Europe, former 
the former Soviet Union, the Middle East and Africa. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
