<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Highway Safety Head Leaves Govt. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Dr. Ricardo Martinez, chief of the federal  
government's highway safety agency, said Thursday he was stepping 
down to spend more time with his family and work as a health care 
executive in the private sector. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez, head of the National Highway Traffic Safety  
Administration for five years, was at the helm of the regulatory 
agency when it crafted a series of initiatives to respond to the 
public outcry over deaths from automobile air bags. 
</P>
<P>
	He also recently lead a successful effort to phase in a  
universal anchorage system in cars for child seats so they would be 
less complicated to install and used correctly. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a remarkable opportunity, but it has meant my family  
life was on hold,'' Martinez said in an interview. ``Now I'm going 
to change my focus.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez has a wife and two children, ages 2 and 4. He has  
accepted a job as vice president of health affairs for Web MD, 
Inc., an Atlanta-based company that provides health news and 
services to physicians and consumers over the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez said he will leave the agency in mid-October.  
</P>
<P>
	Some groups expressed concern that Martinez is leaving before  
the completion of a controversial rulemaking on regulating future 
generations of automobile air bags. The agency has blamed air bags 
for 143 deaths -- mostly to children, while also crediting them with 
saving 4,400 lives. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't know how the decision-making is going to be made or  
who would be most involved in the process,'' said Gloria Bergquist 
of the Alliance of Automobile Manufacturers, an association 
representing 11 automakers including General Motors Corp., Ford 
Motor Co., and DaimlerChrysler AG. 
</P>
<P>
	But Martinez said the proposed rule, which is to be announced in  
October, has mostly been crafted and that experienced staffers 
would keep it on track. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez was an emergency-room physician and Stanford University  
professor when he joined the agency in September 1994. He has had a 
longtime interest in auto safety, once taking a sabbatical to study 
vehicle performance during crashes and injury patterns involving 
occupants. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
