<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Vows Rugby World Cup Effort </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) -- The United States, a decided underdog at  
the Rugby World Cup, isn't satisfied with just being there. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a big heart and we'll get in there and try to play  
like dogs,'' American George Sucher said. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. team, which has only four professional players and  
comes into the tournament following a 106-8 defeat by England last 
month, opens against Ireland Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Sucher, one of the American amateurs, had to ``scrounge'' for  
money to play at the tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``Being able to represent your country is a huge honor,'' he  
said. ``Whenever you put the red, white and blue on, or sing the 
Star Spangled Banner, it gets the blood pumping and makes you want 
to go out and fight hard for your country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Rugby World Cup began Friday when Prince Charles welcomed  
the ``World in Union'' to Wales at the opening ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
	Expected to reach television audiences of 3 billion in 150  
countries and attract 2 million spectators at 20 sites in five 
countries, the tournament will have 41 games over the next five 
weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. coach Jack Clark tried to play down talk that his team  
might be initimidated by the Irish. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would expect Ireland's going to come out and play hard,''  
Clark said. ``We wouldn't want it any other way. 
</P>
<P>
	``But it's important not to confuse the fact that we acknowledge  
we're underdogs and that they're a more skilled team with the 
thought that we're at all frightened -- that's not what's at stake 
here.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
