<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bernadette O'Farrell Dies at 75 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Bernadette O'Farrell, the Irish-born actress who  
played Maid Marian in the long-running 1950s television series, 
``The Adventures of Robin Hood,'' has died at 75, the Daily 
Telegraph reported. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not immediately clear which day this week she died. The  
newspaper report was published Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. O'Farrell was often seen in film parts written by her  
husband Frank Launder, who with Sidney Gilliat created the St. 
Trinian's films about lively pranks in a girls' school. 
</P>
<P>
	But it was as Maid Marian that she made her name. ``The  
Adventures of Robin Hood,'' which ran from 1955 to 1959, was very 
popular with younger viewers, not least because of its catchy theme 
tune, sung by Dick James, which became a hit in 1956. 
</P>
<P>
	The series, a traditional version of the Robin Hood legend, was  
one of the first British productions to succeed in the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
	But, after 78 episodes, Ms. O'Farrell became worried that she  
was being typecast and in 1957, she quit the series, despite 
thousands of letters from fans begging her not to leave Robin. 
</P>
<P>
	She said the turning point came when shopkeepers in the Chelsea  
district of London, where she lived, began to greet her with, 
``Good morning, Maid Marian.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Born at Birr in County Offaly, she attended convent school.  
While working as a lawyer's secretary, she met Launder, 17 years 
her senior, who gave her a small part in ``Captain Boycott,'' the 
1947 film that starred Stewart Granger. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years later, she appeared as the glamorous sports teacher in  
Launder and Gilliat's ``The Happiest Days of Your Life,'' with 
Alastair Sim and Margaret Rutherford, and in 1950, she and Launder 
were married. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1950s, she combined repertory stage work with film parts,  
including ``Lady in the Fog'' (1952) with Cesar Romero and ``The 
Square Ring'' (1953) with Robert Beatty. After leaving ``Robin 
Hood,'' she appeared in Launder and Gilliat's ``The Bridal Path'' 
(1959). 
</P>
<P>
	Her husband died in 1997. She is survived by their two  
daughters. 
</P>
<P>
	Funeral details were not immediately available.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
