<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Closer to SBC Merger Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators are inching closer to a  
final decision on a merger that would bring together two regional 
Bell companies to form the largest local phone company in the 
nation. 
</P>
<P>
	Industry officials and analysts predicted the merger between  
Ameritech Corp. and SBC Communications would go through, but with 
conditions to preserve competition in local markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Communications Commission approval is the last step in  
completing the deal -- originally valued at $57 billion. The Justice 
Department and state regulators have already approved it. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined business would control 57 million, or one-third, of  
the nation's local phone lines spread across 13 states. 
</P>
<P>
	FCC Chairman Bill Kennard voted to approve the deal several  
weeks ago, according to agency sources speaking on condition of 
anonymity. Two other commissioners, Gloria Tristani and Susan Ness, 
have voted on the matter. But their offices would not reveal how 
they voted. 
</P>
<P>
	Only one commissioner has not yet voted on the deal, according  
to the FCC sources. Commissioner Michael Powell's office would not 
reveal whether he had voted. Calls to Commissioner Harold 
Furchtgott-Roth's office were not returned. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal needs only three votes for approval, but all five  
commissioners must cast a vote for the action to be binding. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennard has placed the merger on the agenda for the commission's  
Oct. 8 meeting to force a vote by the remaining commissioner. But a 
final decision could come before then. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies have expressed confidence that the merger would  
receive approval. 
</P>
<P>
	The 13 states in the proposed merger are Arkansas, California,  
Connecticut, Kansas, Missouri, Nevada, Oklahoma, Texas, Illinois, 
Indiana, Michigan, Ohio and Wisconsin. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC's staff this summer recommended approval of the deal,  
based on conditions that the two companies had submitted to the 
government. Under the deal, SBC-Ameritech would enter 30 new 
markets within 30 months to compete with established local phone 
companies. It also would establish a separate subsidiary to provide 
advanced telecommunications services such as high-speed Internet 
access. At least 10 percent of its upgraded services would go 
toward low-income regions. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies also would have to provide deep discounts on key  
pieces of their networks to competitors who want to buy them. 
Failure to meet the conditions could mean stiff penalties. Just for 
failing to meet the new market deadline, the companies could face a 
$40 million fine for each market, up to a $1.2 billion cap. 
</P>
<P>
	San Antonio-based SBC and Chicago-based Ameritech claim the  
merger is good for consumers, claiming it will spur local phone 
competition and possibly lower prices, accelerate the roll-out of 
high-speed Internet access and data services, and create jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	But long-distance companies trying to get into the local phone  
market -- including MCI, Sprint and AT&AMP;T -- said the concessions were 
accompanied by so many other limitations that they would do nothing 
to aid competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer groups also have opposed the deal, saying they do not  
believe the merger conditions go far enough to protect the public 
interest. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991001.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 16:10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Missouri Admits Possible Violations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The future of new men's basketball coach Quin Synder's first two  
prospective recruits is in question after Missouri reported 
possible NCAA recruiting violations. 
</P>
<P>
	Missouri athletic director Mike Alden notified the NCAA on  
Friday that the university may have violated recruiting rules by 
allowing the mothers of Detroit basketball prospects Rickey 
Paulding and Arthur Johnson to join their sons on a chartered plane 
to Columbia, Mo. 
</P>
<P>
	The NCAA told Missouri late Friday afternoon that a ruling on  
the violation will arrive on Monday. The NCAA was working on 
several other eligibility cases from other schools Friday, and 
could not immediately investigate Missouri's situation. 
</P>
<P>
	A Missouri sports information spokesman said Friday the  
university will release a statement when the infraction ruling 
arrives on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	NCAA spokeswoman Jane Jankowski wouldn't speculate on when a  
ruling might be made or any possible implications it might hold for 
Missouri. 
</P>
<P>
	Alden said the university interpreted NCAA rules to mean a  
prospect could be accompanied on a noncommercial flight if the 
extra party paid fair market value for the ticket. 
</P>
<P>
	The women paid the university between $200 and $300 each for  
their tickets prior to flying from Detroit to Columbia Regional 
Airport on Sept. 17 and returning Sept. 19, Alden said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel confident in the process. I feel confident in our  
basketball program. And, I feel confident in the NCAA,'' Alden 
said. ``Do I feel confident in a great result? I have no idea.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although Jankowski would not comment specifically on Missouri's  
situation, she said NCAA rules are clear regarding transportation 
of prospective recruits and their relatives and friends. 
</P>
<P>
	A school can use commercial flights or noncommercial flights --  
the school's own plane, charter or private planes -- to bring 
prospects to campus for official visits, Jankowski said. But 
relatives, friends and legal guardians can accompany prospects only 
on commercial flights. On those flights, the prospect's fare is 
paid by the school. Anyone accompanying the prospect must pay his 
or her own way. 
</P>
<P>
	``The NCAA does not support that a parent can be on a  
noncommercial flight,'' Jankowski said. It does not matter whether 
the parents pay for the flight, she added. 
</P>
<P>
	Paulding and Johnson, both seniors, orally committed to Missouri  
last week. But now they could be declared ineligible, at least 
temporarily, before the Nov. 7 signing day. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once an institution determines there's been a violation  
involving an athlete or prospective athlete, it's their 
responsibility to make an eligibility ruling,'' Jankowski said. The 
university would then seek to have the athlete reinstated by the 
NCAA. 
</P>
<P>
	None of this would affect a student's ability to play at another  
school, Jankowski said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Alden said Missouri had yet to decide what to do with  
Paulding and Johnson's eligibility. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't know if an infraction has indeed taken place,'' Alden  
said. ``The NCAA is the only one that can determine if an 
infraction has taken place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alden said the call to the NCAA followed one Wednesday to the  
Big 12 Conference, which advised Missouri that it would be 
``beneficial'' to notify the NCAA. 
</P>
<P>
	Snyder, who was heavily involved with recruiting as an assistant  
coach at Duke before being hired by Missouri in April, told the St. 
Louis Post-Dispatch on Friday that he bears responsibility if an 
infraction had taken place. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unequivocally I do,'' he said. ``I'm the head basketball  
coach. That's what it means to be the head coach.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Paulding, a 6-foot-4 guard, averaged 25.6 points, 11.2 rebounds,  
4.0 assists and 3.0 blocked shots last season at Detroit 
Renaissance High. He said having his mother on the visit made it 
easier to choose a college. Paulding also visited Ohio State, Miami 
and Michigan State, but his mother made only the trip to Columbia. 
</P>
<P>
	Paulding and his mother, Virginia Robinson, told the St. Louis  
Post-Dispatch that the two mothers and their sons were the only 
passengers on the chartered plane. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a nice plane,'' Paulding said.  
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, a 6-9 forward, averaged 16.4 points last season at  
Detroit Pershing High. He only visited Miami before choosing 
Missouri. Both players made an unofficial visit together to 
Missouri in August. But the September trip to Columbia over Parents 
Weekend solidified their choices. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
