<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ill. Court Says HMOs May Be Sued </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) -- The Illinois Supreme Court has ruled  
that patients may sue health maintenance organizations over alleged 
malpractice, affirming a right consumer advocates failed to win 
from lawmakers. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for the successful plaintiff called Thursday's decision  
a landmark that holds HMOs responsible for the actions of doctors 
they promote and for cost-containment measures that hurt patients. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think anyone with a straight face can deny that not  
all, but some HMOs are interfering with the care patients are 
receiving from their doctors to the patients' detriment,'' said 
attorney Lynn Dowd of Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	Inga Petrovich of Chicago sued Share Health Plan of Illinois  
Inc. as well as two physicians who attended her, claiming the 
doctors failed to diagnose cancer in her mouth quickly enough after 
she complained of pain in fall 1990. Ms. Petrovich, 73, died of 
complications from the cancer last October. 
</P>
<P>
	A circuit court ruled Ms. Petrovich could not sue Chicago-based  
Share because the doctors were independent contractors. 
</P>
<P>
	But in Thursday's decision, Justice Michael Bilandic wrote that  
Share is liable for the doctors' action because Ms. Petrovich had 
reason to believe they were Share employees based on what Share 
said in its advertising. And, he added, Share had control over the 
doctors because HMOs often make decisions about what treatment is 
medically necessary and encourage doctors to keep costs low by 
making them responsible for referrals. 
</P>
<P>
	``Where an HMO effectively controls a physician's exercise of  
medical judgment and that judgment is exercised negligently, the 
HMO cannot be allowed to claim that the physician is solely 
responsible for the harm that results,'' Bilandic wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	No justices wrote dissents in the case.  
</P>
<P>
	This spring, Illinois lawmakers approved legislation that gives  
HMO customers more rights in challenging coverage decisions and 
getting emergency treatment. But it passed only after sponsors 
dropped a provision letting customers file malpractice suits 
against HMOs. 
</P>
<P>
	Joshua Vincent, a lawyer for Share, declined to comment until  
the company has time to study the opinion. The case now goes back 
to Cook County Circuit Court. 
</P>
<P>
	Several other states are broadening HMO patients' rights. Just  
this week, California Gov. Gray Davis signed a health reform 
package into law that lets patients to sue HMOs -- a right enjoyed 
by patients in Texas and a handful of other states. 
</P>
<P>
	On Capitol Hill, Congress is weighing a measure that would  
create uniform nationwide regulations on managed health care plans. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the U.S. Supreme Court this week agreed to take up  
an Illinois case that could decide whether patients have an 
unlimited right to sue HMOs. Current federal law limits lawsuits 
against health plans. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991001.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 12:40:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Oct. 1, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Japan Lifts Nuclear Plant Advisory  
</P>
<P>
	TOKAIMURA, Japan (AP) -- Hundreds of thousands of people were  
told they could safely leave their houses today, one day after 
Japan's worst nuclear accident sent radiation levels soaring, put 
three workers in the hospital and exposed nearly 50 more to 
radiation. Officials said the accident at the uranium processing 
plant has been contained. A spokesman said radiation levels in the 
area are back to normal and the government was lifting an advisory 
that ordered more than 310,000 residents to stay indoors. A 
380-yard radius around the plant is still off-limits. 

</P>
<P>
	Robertson Warns Buchanan  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Christian Coalition founder Pat Robertson  
warned Pat Buchanan today that Christian conservatives will desert 
him if he ditches the GOP for a third-party presidential run with 
Ross Perot's Reform Party. Robertson claimed Reform supporters are 
``180 degrees out in terms of social issues. They don't share any 
of the views that Pat Buchanan claimed to espouse so 
vociferously.'' He also accused congressional Republicans of 
betraying -- by inaction and timidity -- the Christian conservatives 
who helped the GOP take control of Congress. 

</P>
<P>
	F-22 Deal Would Restore House Cuts  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House and Senate negotiators today ended a  
long deadlock over the high-tech F-22, giving the Air Force only 
half the $1.8 billion it had requested for next year to get the 
world's most expensive jet fighter off the ground. Still, the 
compromise spared the $65 billion program from being scrapped, as 
the House had voted last July. Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, told 
reporters that basic agreement on the F-22 had been achieved, and 
that a House-Senate conference panel would meet Monday to act on it 
and on the larger $270 billion Pentagon spending bill to which it 
is attached. 

</P>
