<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> F-22 Deal Would Restore House Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional negotiators have agreed to  
restore much of the $1.8 billion the House cut from the Air Force's 
F-22 ``stealth'' fighter program, while delaying production of 
combat-ready models for at least a year. 
</P>
<P>
	A House-Senate conference committee may announce as early as  
today that it has restored $1.3 billion for the F-22 program in the 
final defense spending bill for fiscal 2000, according to those 
close to the negotations. 
</P>
<P>
	The compromise includes $1 billion to buy test models of the  
ultra-sophisticated warplane and $300 million in ``termination 
liability'' for Lockheed Martin, manufacturer of the plane. 
</P>
<P>
	The $300 million would be released for procurement in fiscal  
2001 if the program is not canceled. 
</P>
<P>
	But production of final versions of the radar-evading aircraft,  
which are being built at the Lockheed Martin plant in Marietta, 
Ga., would have to wait at least until 2001, under the compromise. 
</P>
<P>
	House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., told reporters on Thursday  
that a deal on the F-22 was close and ``I would hope we would 
finish that bill quite quickly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Air Force had wanted to begin buying production planes  
during the coming year. It has already spent $25 billion to develop 
the F-22 and plans to spend an additional $40 billion to build 339 
of them. They would replace the F-15 jet fighter. 
</P>
<P>
	The F-22s, which the Air Force envisions as the core of its  
fleet for the early 21st century, would cost nearly $200 million 
apiece, making it the most expensive jet fighter ever built. 
</P>
<P>
	But House critics, led by defense appropriations subcommittee  
chairman Jerry Lewis, R-Calif., argued that the money was needed 
for other military projects and that the F-22 was not ready for 
production. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal was struck during closed-door meetings of Republican  
congressional leaders Wednesday night and Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	It should end a stalemate that blocked progress on a nearly $270  
billion bill to run the military through fiscal 2000, which begins 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	The compromise would probably be enough to purchase three or  
four of the test aircraft, instead of the six that the full $1.8 
billion would have bought. 
</P>
<P>
	The Air Force could buy up to six of the test models under the  
deal, but probably would have to request additional money next year 
to buy that many. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate earlier approved the full $1.85 billion while the  
House voted to scrap the program, arguing that the plane's 
computers were not fully tested and that the money was needed for 
other defense programs. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
