<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> After-Hours Trading Confuses Some </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Confusion is mounting across a wide range of  
industries as to how U.S. stock markets will determine a closing 
price for stocks as trading days get longer. 
</P>
<P>
	The changes wrought by the nation's evolving stock markets are  
rippling far beyond Wall Street as a result of the recent surge in 
after-hours trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawsuits are just one example of how broader society is affected  
when it no longer is clear what stock price should be counted as 
the final one of the day. 
</P>
<P>
	Consider a divorce case in which the assets of a couple are to  
be divided. One lawyer may argue that the value of a couple's stock 
portfolio should be determined by the traditional 4 p.m. Eastern 
time closing price of the New York Stock Exchange and the Nasdaq 
Stock Market. The other lawyer may argue that the value should be 
settled at midnight to provide for trading activity during the 
after-hours sessions. 
</P>
<P>
	Estate settlements are expected to get bogged down by similar  
controversies. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do on occasion have the need to determine the value of a  
stock, and an issue can arise where we'll need to establish a 
cutoff time for that value. But now the market may never close, and 
that becomes a problem,'' said Jeff Advokat, a general practice 
attorney in Morristown, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	And as after-hours trading becomes more popular, and more and  
more stocks are traded during the sessions, the likelihood 
increases that the value of a client's assets will change after 4 
p.m., Advokat said. ``The more stocks we're talking about, the more 
it's going to affect us,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Until the exchanges or the law profession itself sets definitive  
guidelines, judges will be forced to rule on a case by case basis, 
Advokat added. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, in response to calls for more information  
during after-hours sessions, the organization that distributes 
stock prices for the NYSE said it will extend its hours to 6:35 
p.m. Eastern time from 5:15 p.m. The Nasdaq agreed to do the same 
thing last month. That means the time at which closing stock prices 
are determined is effectively being pushed back one hour and twenty 
minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	Many areas of the securities industry will be affected. They  
include: investment bankers who complete transactions -- such as 
mergers and acquisitions or stock splits -- based on a company's 
stock price; options traders and investors, who must decide whether 
to exercise stock options contracts based on a closing price; and 
stock quote vendors who sell price information to a wide range of 
customers. 
</P>
<P>
	``All this stuff is up in the air. Nobody knows how its going to  
play out,'' said Charles Jones, a finance professor at Columbia 
University's business school in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of those impacted say they are waiting for direction from  
the two primary exchanges -- the NYSE and the Nasdaq, both of which 
plan on extending their trading hours next year. 
</P>
<P>
	NYSE and Nasdaq spokesmen said Friday that both exchanges still  
consider 4 p.m. to be the official close of the trading day. That 
could change, however, once the Big Board and the Nasdaq open their 
own after-hours sessions. 
</P>
<P>
	The mutual fund industry, which prices its funds based on the 4  
p.m. closing prices on the NYSE and Nasdaq, is also keeping the 
status quo in place -- at least until the after-hours sessions prove 
active enough to warrant changes. The nation's two largest fund 
families -- Fidelity and Vanguard -- have both said they will 
continue to price their funds based on the traditional closing 
time. 
</P>
<P>
	But more complex issues remain unresolved.  
</P>
<P>
	Barbara Keefe, director of marketing for quote vendor DTN  
Financial Services in Omaha, Neb., said her company provides its 
customers, mostly individual investors, with timely, in-depth stock 
information, including the price of a share's last recorded sale of 
the day, which is frequently used to determine the direction a 
stock might head the following day. 
</P>
<P>
	DTN Financial, she said, received a memo from the Nasdaq which  
recommended taking a ``snapshot'' of last sale prices anytime after 
5:15 p.m. ``But that's not an official price by anyone's standards, 
and you're going to see discrepancies among the vendors,'' she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The hundreds of newspapers that publish previous day stock  
prices in their morning papers are expected to adapt to the changes 
on an individual basis. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
