<HEADLINE> Jays Offer Deals to Delgado, Green </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Carlos Delgado and Shawn Green, both eligible for  
free agency after the 2000 season, were offered long-term contracts 
by the Toronto Blue Jays on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Green was hitting .317 with 41 homers and 121 RBIs entering  
Friday night's game against Cleveland and could win a Gold Glove 
for his outfield play. 
</P>
<P>
	Delgado, Toronto's first baseman, hit .272 with 44 homers and  
134 RBIs before his season was cut short last week because of a 
broken bone in his right leg. 
</P>
<P>
	After the 1998 season, Delgado turned down a four-year contract  
worth about $34 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Green's agent, Jeff Moorad, said a major factor in Green's  
decision will be whether Delgado re-signs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ownership has stepped up. They understand the dynamics of a  
major league club. We have a payroll for next year and a plan,'' 
said general manager Gord Ash, who didn't receive a set budget last 
year until December. 
</P>
<P>
	Ash said next season's payroll will be in the $47 million to $49  
million range, an increase of about $5 million. 
  	   	
</P>
