<HEADLINE> Five Family Members Killed in N.C. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WAYNESVILLE, N.C. (AP) -- Five family members who had just come  
home from a fair were shot to death by two men who stole their 
pickup truck and car, police said. One suspect was arrested Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Shotgun shells littered the winding driveway leading to the home  
where the victims were slain Thursday night. Four were found dead 
inside, while the fifth was outside. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators said the killers apparently took off separately,  
wrecked both vehicles and abandoned them. The pickup was found off 
an embankment below the house; the car was on Interstate 40 a few 
miles away. 
</P>
<P>
	One suspect was arrested after someone who recognized him from a  
description heard on news reports held him at gunpoint until a 
sheriff's deputy arrived, said David Barnes, an agent with the 
State Bureau of Investigation. No immediate charges were filed. 
</P>
<P>
	The other gunman was believed to be on foot. Barnes said blood  
was found in both cars, meaning the gunman was probably injured, 
though Barnes said it wasn't clear how. 
</P>
<P>
	The slayings took place in a rural area about 20 miles west of  
Asheville. 
</P>
<P>
	A neighbor, Rita Messer, identified the victims as Cora and Earl  
Phillips, a couple in their 70s; their son Eddie, 40; their 
daughter-in-law, Mitzi, 42; and their granddaughter Katie, a middle 
school student. 
</P>
<P>
	The elder Phillipses were retired. Eddie Phillips was a dump  
truck driver, and his wife worked at a textile plant and ran a 
beauty shop out h+er home, relatives said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're good people, they were churchgoing people, they never  
harmed nobody,'' Ms. Messer said. ``It's awful. You ain't safe in 
your own home, you're not safe in church. I don't know what this 
world is coming to.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
