<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indianapolis News Ends Publication </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Staffers of the city's oldest newspaper knew  
this day would come. 
</P>
<P>
	They had prepared for the closing since July, when the  
management of Indianapolis Newspapers Inc. announced it would cease 
publication of The Indianapolis News, blaming television and 
changing reader habits for the afternoon daily's declining 
circulation. 
</P>
<P>
	That didn't make it any easier Friday, as the final edition  
rolled off the presses at 10:31 a.m. Some cried and hugged as the 
morning passed, some laughed and joked in typical newsroom 
jocularity. All reflected. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like you go to see a friend, and you know this friend has  
six months to live and you see this friend go steadily downhill,'' 
said longtime reporter Skip Hess. ``And you're kind of happy to see 
the end come because there's no more suffering. I think the News 
had gotten to that point.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper was founded in 1869. Rumors of its demise had  
circulated for years as changes in lifestyles and mass media eroded 
its readership. In the end, there were only about 30,000 
subscribers -- down from about 100,000 a decade ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The Star and the News merged newsroom staffs in 1995, and the  
News' late-afternoon edition ceased publication shortly after 
longtime publisher Eugene S. Pulliam's death on Jan. 21. Saturday 
editions of the papers were merged in April. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was no single economic event or catastrophe that  
overwhelmed it or crushed it,'' The News said in its own front-page 
obituary. ``Like Gen. Douglas MacArthur, it just faded away, a pale 
shadow of its earlier self when it was the most-circulated 
newspaper in Indiana.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The obituary was below a headline in 1 3/4-inch type that said,  
``Farewell.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The final edition also included a special 34-page section  
commemorating the newspaper's history, from the day it was founded 
to Friday, when 100,000 copies of its farewell were printed. 
</P>
<P>
	Closing The News eliminated about 20 newsroom jobs, but most are  
being absorbed through existing openings at The Star and voluntary 
severance. 
</P>
<P>
	Afternoon newspapers have suffered declining circulation for  
years. In the past year, two others -- The Evansville Press and The 
Chattanooga Times -- ceased publication. When the Honolulu 
Star-Bulletin shuts down by the end of the month, there will be 46 
U.S. cities with two or more newspapers, according to figures 
compiled by The Associated Press. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
