<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McHale, Thompson Head to Hoops Hall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) -- Kevin McHale drove himself to the very  
edge. John Thompson pushed others to the limit, and sometimes 
beyond. 
</P>
<P>
	``He always thinks about what he says,'' Hall of Fame coach  
Clarence Gaines said of Thompson, the voluble Georgetown coach. 
``Then he goes ahead and says it anyway.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McHale and Thompson shared some common ground Friday -- a spot in  
the Basketball Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's other inductees were former NBA star Wayne Embry,  
women's college coach Billie Moore and the late NBA pioneer and 
owner Fred Zollner. 
</P>
<P>
	Playing on a frontline with Larry Bird and Robert Parish, McHale  
helped shape the 1980s as another era of greatness for the Boston 
Celtics. They played with size, smarts and championship intensity, 
winning titles in 1981, 1984 and 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	McHale arrived in 1980 from the University of Minnesota as a  
gangly, 6-foot-10 sixth man. But he eventually transformed himself 
into one of the most feared attackers in the game with his jump 
hook, fadeaway jumper and agile moves. He shot 55 percent from the 
field for his 13 seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was ... one of the best low-post scorers in the NBA I've  
ever seen. There were times he was unstoppable,'' Bird said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was always a lot more concerned with how good I could be,''  
said McHale, who used to spend 10-15 minutes after each game 
sorting out his play. ``I was always self-analyzing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But McHale also borrowed inspiration and ideas from Bird and  
others on the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``Larry helped everyone improve their games,'' McHale said. ``As  
you saw him do things, you thought, maybe I'm going to do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like Bird, McHale was ready to grunt through pain. In the 1987  
failed playoff effort against the Lakers, McHale played with a foot 
so badly battered he sometimes needed to lean on furniture to 
stand. 
</P>
<P>
	Another habitue of postseason play, Thompson was the backup  
center for Bill Russell on the Celtic championship teams of 1965 
and 1966. Later, with the hulking Thompson draping a towel over his 
shoulder, his 27 Georgetown teams made 24 postseason appearances. 
They went to three NCAA Final Fours and captured the national 
championship in 1984, the first time a black coach won the national 
basketball title. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet his unyielding standards for both basketball and academics  
challenged and sometimes frustrated his players. His demands for 
greater minority access in sports gave him more than a few 
detractors. 
</P>
<P>
	He endured racial taunts when he first fielded a predominantly  
black team at Georgetown. He later boycotted two games in 1989 to 
protest NCAA Proposition 42, saying its financial limits hurt 
minority athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	He thinks such views hurt his two earlier nominations to the  
Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	``Somebody asked me what I think I'll be remembered most for,''  
he said Friday. ``I said, `The things that kept me out of the Hall 
of Fame.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
