<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congress On Verge of Deal on F-22's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Air Force appears to have been thwarted in  
its quest to get the first, combat-ready models of its prized F-22 
stealth fighter as a House-Senate fight over the 
ultra-sophisticated warplane draws to a close. 
</P>
<P>
	Congressional leaders were expected to announce as early as  
today that they have agreed to provide $1 billion for the Air Force 
to buy test models of the F-22. 
</P>
<P>
	But production of final versions of the radar-evading aircraft  
would have to wait at least until 2001, said congressional 
officials who spoke on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	While cautioning that ``it's never done until it's done,'' House  
Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., told reporters today that a deal on 
the F-22 was close. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would hope we would finish that bill quite quickly,''  
Hastert said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Air Force had wanted to begin buying production planes  
during the coming year. It has already spent $25 billion to develop 
the F-22 and plans to spend an additional $40 billion to build 339 
of them. They would replace the F-15 jet fighter. 
</P>
<P>
	The F-22s, which the Air Force envisions as the cornerstone of  
its fleet for the early 21st century, would cost nearly $200 
million apiece, making it the most expensive jet fighter ever 
built. 
</P>
<P>
	But House critics led by Rep. Jerry Lewis, R-Calif., argued that  
the money was needed for other military projects and that the F-22 
was not ready for production. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision would mark a setback for the Lockheed Martin Corp.,  
the prime contractor, the Clinton administration and the Air Force. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, struck during a closed-door meeting of Republican  
congressional leaders Wednesday night, would end weeks of stalemate 
that blocked progress on a nearly $270 billion bill to run the 
military through fiscal 2000, which begins Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We made a good breakthrough,'' House Majority Leader Dick  
Armey, R-Texas, an F-22 supporter, said while leaving the meeting. 
But he and other lawmakers would provide no details. 
</P>
<P>
	The $1 billion would probably be enough to purchase three or  
four of the test aircraft, one official said, which would be used 
for trials that would help determine the plane's final 
configuration. The Air Force could buy up to six of the test 
models, but probably would have to request additional money next 
year to buy that many. 
</P>
<P>
	In its defense bill, the Senate had provided $1.85 billion this  
year, enough to buy six of the planes. But the House deleted the 
money in July, arguing that the plane's computers were not fully 
tested and that the money was needed for other defense programs. 
</P>
<P>
	During weeks of bargaining, the House offered about $1 billion,  
or enough for three or four test fighters. 
</P>
<P>
	House negotiators also offered to support $500 million the  
Senate has approved for construction of a giant LHD-8 transport 
ship at the Ingalls shipyard in Pascagoula, Miss., hometown of 
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not immediately learned whether the money for the  
Mississippi ship was included in the agreement. Lott has long 
favored the shipbuilding project, but had been unable to persuade 
the House to go along. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
