<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Arrested in University Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- A white former vending machine company  
employee whose route included Florida A&AMP;M University was arrested 
Friday in two bombings at the predominantly black school after he 
was recognized on a surveillance tape buying the pipe used in the 
blasts, the FBI said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawrence Michael Lombardi, 41, an unemployed, married father of  
two, was held without bail on two counts of manufacturing a bomb. 
He could face up to 20 years in prison if convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	Lombardi's attorney, R. Tim Jansen, said, ``He is absolutely  
innocent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first bomb exploded Aug. 31 in the restroom of an  
administration building. The second went off Sept. 22, damaging a 
restroom surrounded by classrooms and offices. 
</P>
<P>
	No one was injured in either blast, but the explosions spread  
fear across the 12,000-student campus. Dozens of police officers 
searched every campus building each morning, and everyone had to 
show ID to enter. Surveillance cameras were installed at state 
expense. 
</P>
<P>
	Lombardi worked for a vending company and his route had included  
machines at two buildings where bombs exploded, the FBI said. An 
employee told investigators that Lombardi had been issued a 
university ID card and that he did not surrender the card when he 
left the company in July. 
</P>
<P>
	``The vending company employee described Lombardi as having no  
personality and as an individual who did not like blacks and has 
used the `N' word,'' the FBI wrote in its affidavit. 
</P>
<P>
	Jansen said that was not true. ``They did not find any  
identification card at his house. He did not have one at the time 
of this event,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In both bombings, the FBI said there were anonymous calls filled  
with racial slurs and threats of more violence. 
</P>
<P>
	One said: ``FAMU has seen the beginning of this. ... They got no  
business having a college where there ain't nobody ... smart enough 
to get a degree. ... This is just the beginning, brother.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another call warned that something else would happen at the  
university Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Lombardi denied building any bombs but admitted to making a  
phone call tinged with racist comments to a Tallahassee TV station 
hours after the second bomb went off Sept. 22, according to FBI 
agent Matthew Pellegrino. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators said they matched bomb fragments with PVC pipe  
that Lombardi bought at a Lowe's home improvement store the day 
before the first explosion. 
</P>
<P>
	According to state records, Lombardi holds an embalmer's license  
and resigned from a funeral home about a year ago. Investigators 
said three former co-workers identified Lombardi from a store 
surveillance tape and recognized his voice on a recording of the 
threatening phone calls. 
</P>
<P>
	One former co-worker told investigators Lombardi had talked  
about finding bomb-making instructions on the Internet, the FBI 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities would not say whether Lombardi was part of a larger  
group, but indicated they felt the campus was safe after the 
arrest. Hundreds of people are expected to attend school's annual 
parents' weekend, which started Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It looks like our nightmare may be over,'' FAMU President  
Frederick S. Humphries told students at a rally Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said some of the increased security will remain at the  
school, including the surveillance cameras. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone has been on edge because you couldn't be sure when  
the next one was going to happen,'' said Charles Slaton, 21, a 
student from Atlanta. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
