<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senator Warns on Y2K Air Readiness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A senator says he will publicize in the  
Congressional Record all companies with Federal Aviation 
Administration certificates that have not responded to a survey 
about their readiness for the year 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., is drafting  
legislation to ground as of Dec. 31 any certificate holder involved 
in flying passengers that has not responded to the survey by 
mid-November. 
</P>
<P>
	The threatened action came after a hearing Thursday in which the  
Transportation Department's inspector general, Kenneth Mead, said 
1,900 companies regulated by the FAA had not responded to the 
agency's readiness survey issued in April. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike other federal regulatory agencies, the FAA did not  
require a response. 
</P>
<P>
	``Knowing what I know -- that 1,900 carriers have failed to  
respond to the agency responsible for regulating them about whether 
or not they're Y2K ready -- I think, frankly, knowing that and not 
taking some action could cause this Congress to be held accountable 
for lacking responsibility on this issue,'' Dodd said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, the FAA checked the figures and said 1,700 companies  
-- instead of the 1,900 companies cited by Dodd and Mead -- had 
failed to respond to the survey, and they include about 200 that 
regularly carry passengers. Of the 200, most operators were small, 
and some, like Kiwi International Air Lines, had gone out of 
business, the agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the remaining 1,500 companies, some were aerospace  
manufacturers and others were on-demand commercial carriers, 
roughly half of which are charter operators in Alaska. 
</P>
<P>
	FAA Administrator Jane Garvey told Dodd at Thursday's hearing  
that she welcomed his proposal to publicize the non-respondents and 
ground them if necessary. ``I think the idea of legislation could 
be helpful to us,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency always retains the right to ground unsafe operators,  
Garvey said, although the Transportation Department said in recent 
days that a lack of Y2K readiness does not necessarily constitute a 
safety threat. 
</P>
<P>
	The year 2000 problem stems from the design of some older  
computers, which recognize years in a two-digit format, such as 
``99'' for 1999. Some could malfunction when the new century starts 
if they confuse ``00'' for 1900 instead of 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Computer problems are especially troubling in the aviation  
industry, where everything from radar screens to runway lights are 
computerized. In June, the FAA said it had repaired and tested all 
computers critical to safe operations. U.S. and Canadian airlines 
recently offered the same assurance. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
