<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> British Airline Put in Receivership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Hundreds of passengers were left stranded Friday  
after low-cost airline Debonair was placed in receivership, a 
victim of fierce competition in the discount flights market. 
</P>
<P>
	Debonair Holdings PLC, based at Luton Airport, north of London,  
announced that its 14 aircraft had been grounded. Shares in the 
group were suspended late Thursday on the European Easdaq stock 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our primary concern now is to try to secure continued  
operations or to make alternative arrangements for passengers who 
have already purchased tickets,'' said Nick Dargan of the 
accounting firm Deloitte &AMP; Touche, which has been called in to try 
to save the company. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am currently seeking finance to see if we can get the  
Debonair planes to fly, but at the moment they are all grounded,'' 
Dargan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said administrators would be looking for offers for  
Debonair, which became one of Britain's first low-cost airlines 
when it launched flights on short-haul European routes in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Offers could come from Lufthansa, Swissair and Richard Branson's  
Virgin, the analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Low-cost airlines spawned by the recent deregulation of Europe's  
aviation industry are able to offer cheaper fares by avoiding many 
of the costlier, big-city airports favored by their larger rivals. 
</P>
<P>
	They include Go, British Airways' cut-price service based at  
Stansted Airport; the Irish carrier Ryanair; and easyJet, also 
based at Luton. 
</P>
<P>
	Inspired by Southwest Airlines and other low-cost U.S. carriers,  
they have attracted customers despite their no-frills service and 
spotty record for punctuality. But the battle for passengers has 
intensified as more players enter the market. 
</P>
<P>
	The airline, which employs 480 people, had charged $188 for a  
round-trip betwen Luton and Rome, compared with Lufthansa's typical 
economy-class fare of $306. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
