<HEADLINE> Olympic Transportation Funds OKed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- The first congressional funding for  
Olympic transportation projects in Utah advanced Friday when the 
House of Representatives voted to allocate $76 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate negotiators on a conference panel have agreed on the  
funding, part of $290 million sought by Olympic organizers. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not certain they will get all the money.  
</P>
<P>
	``The biggest requests will come next year,'' said John Njord,  
the Olympic coordinator for the Utah Department of Transportation. 
</P>
<P>
	The $76 million includes the final federal installment for the  
north-south light-rail line from downtown Salt Lake to suburban 
Sandy. The final payment was $37.9 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The Utah Transit Authority hopes to tap more federal funding to  
build an east-west line from downtown to the University of Utah in 
time for the 2002 Winter Olympic Games. The opening and closing 
ceremonies will be held at the U.'s Rice-Eccles Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	The House Friday also approved:  
</P>
<P>
	-- $10 million in unitemized ``Olympic transportation  
investment'' funding. 
</P>
<P>
	-- $6.5 million for Park City transit buses.  
</P>
<P>
	-- $3 million for electronic signs alerting Interstate 15 drivers  
to congestion and alternate routes. 
</P>
<P>
	-- $5 million for transportation planning for the Winter Games.  
</P>
<P>
	-- $3.7 million to widen state Route 248 between Park City and  
Kamas. 
</P>
<P>
	-- $3 million for road improvements near Soldier Hollow, the  
biathlon venue at Wasatch Mountain State Park. 
</P>
<P>
	-- $2.5 million for repair and fueling stations in Salt Lake City  
for additional transit buses that will be used for the games. 
</P>
<P>
	-- $2.5 million for Olympic park-and-ride lots.  
</P>
<P>
	-- $1.5 million for ``intermodal'' stations linking transit buses  
and light rail. 
</P>
<P>
	-- $500,000 to cover the expense of shipping and deploying  
transit buses that Salt Lake plans to borrow from other cities. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
