<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Five Family Members Shot in N.C. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WAYNESVILLE, N.C. (AP) -- A search continued in the rugged Blue  
Ridge Mountain foothills for a second suspect in the shooting 
deaths of a family of five, while relatives and friends came to 
grips with the tragedy. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is just a terrible thing,'' Robert Rose, 66, a cousin of  
shooting victim Earl Phillips, said Friday. ``It is hard to 
comprehend something like this happening where, you know, nothing 
ever happens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About 50 officers, aided by tracking dogs and helicopters,  
searched for the second suspect in Thursday night's shootings in 
this Maggie Valley tourist community, about 28 miles west of 
Asheville and 32 miles east of the Tennessee-North Carolina border. 
</P>
<P>
	The victims were identified as Phillips, 72; his wife, Cora, 71;  
their son Eddie, 40; their daughter-in-law, Mitzi, 44; and their 
granddaughter, Katie, 14. 
</P>
<P>
	The five were killed Thursday night after returning home from  
the Haywood County Fair. Four bodies were found inside their 
ranch-style house and a fifth outside. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities say the family apparently was targeted only because  
the suspects were trying to steal a vehicle. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can find no (other) connection between the suspects and the  
victims,'' Haywood County Sheriff Tom Alexander said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	One suspect was in custody. Charles Wesley Roache, 25, was  
caught by a neighbor of the victims and later charged with murder. 
The neighbor held him at gunpoint until police arrived, while the 
other suspect fled. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander refused to say if Roache had given a statement to  
police. The sheriff said he has a felony record, but did not have 
details. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators said the killers apparently stole the family's  
pickup but wrecked it at the bottom of the family's driveway, went 
back and took another car, which was discovered smashed into a 
guard rail on Interstate 40 two miles east of the murder scene. 
</P>
<P>
	A pickup stolen earlier in the week in Iredell County was driven  
off an embankment near the Phillipses' home. 
</P>
<P>
	``My personal opinion is that they came off to dump that vehicle  
and just decided, 'I bet those people got a vehicle,''' said David 
Barnes, an agent with the State Bureau of Investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	The elder Phillipses were retired. Eddie Phillips was a dump  
truck driver, and his wife worked at a textile plant and ran a 
beauty shop out of her home, relatives said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're good people, they were churchgoing people, they never  
harmed nobody,'' neighbor Rita Messer said. ``It's awful. You ain't 
safe in your own home, you're not safe in church. I don't know what 
this world is coming to.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
