<DOCNO> APW19991001.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 09:40:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Softens on Support-Check Delay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republicans were retreating today from  
their plan to delay income-support checks for poor workers after 
Republican GOP presidential front-runner George W. Bush said it was 
a bad idea. President Clinton, armed with a veto pen, declared, ``I 
believe I can stop it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Opposition to the idea is running strong among Senate  
Republicans and moderate GOP lawmakers in the House, where the 
party's narrow margin means that as few as five Republican 
defections can defeat one of the party's initiatives. Privately, 
many Republicans fear that the proposal has become a political 
distraction from the party's high-profile goal of protecting Social 
Security surpluses. 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference, House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill.,  
defended the idea, saying it would help needy families. But asked 
if Republicans were reconsidering their support, he said, ``We're 
always reassessing what's happening here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the headline today,'' House Majority Leader Dick Armey,  
R-Texas, told a reporter about the negative reaction by Bush and 
other Republicans. ``Obviously, that means you have to assess the 
situation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both Hastert and Armey said, ``I don't know,'' when asked if  
there were enough votes to push the plan through the House. 
</P>
<P>
	A pile of unfinished spending bills awaited lawmakers today on  
the first day of the new fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate was hoping to approve an enormous, $324 billion  
measure financing health, education and labor programs. It was 
among nine of the 13 annual spending bills yet to be passed, and 
one of five facing a veto threat, due to cuts Republicans would 
make in Clinton's plans to hire thousands of new teachers. 
</P>
<P>
	But with both sides sensing an issue that could echo in next  
year's elections, a driving force in the budget battle has become 
the GOP pledge to not use Social Security surpluses to pay for 
spending. Central to that is their plan, pushed through the House 
Appropriations Committee on Thursday, to save money by paying 
earned-income tax credits monthly instead of the usual lump sum. 
</P>
<P>
	``They don't lose a dime,'' the plan's sponsor, House Majority  
Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, said of the nearly 20 million working poor 
who receive the credit. 
</P>
<P>
	He added, ``Rather than getting one check, and who knows what  
they do with that one check once a year, they get a monthly 
income.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Armey said to replace some of the savings the plan would  
produce, Republicans were considering leaving the lump sum payments 
in place, but making monthly payments an option. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, DeLay, who introduced the plan, said Republicans  
had proposed it because, ``This is the one members will support.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Predictably, Democrats jumped all over the proposal.  
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, leaving the White House today for a trip to Nevada and  
California, said he was delighted that Texas Gov. Bush opposed the 
GOP plan and -- in language almost like the president's -- had said, 
``I don't think they ought to balance their budget on the backs of 
the poor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said the Republican proposal was ``unconscionable'' and  
threatened a veto. ``I intend to do everything I can to stop it,'' 
the president said. ``And I believe I can stop it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats say the GOP tactic would be unfair, because it would  
siphon money from working families who earn less than $30,000 a 
year. Bush agreed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm concerned for someone who is moving from near-poverty to  
middle class,'' said Bush, who is trying to build an election 
coalition by blending traditional conservative values with moderate 
rhetoric. Afterward, his spokeswoman Karen Hughes confirmed that 
Bush was criticizing the proposal to change the earned income tax 
credit distribution. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked later about Bush's remarks, DeLay said, ``It's obvious Mr.  
Bush needs a little education on how Congress works.'' He added, 
``I don't think he knew what he was talking about,'' suggesting 
Bush may not have realized that benefits would not be cut. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton signed legislation Thursday keeping the government  
financed through Oct. 21. That gives all sides three more weeks to 
work through dozens of disputes ranging from public housing to 
mining on federal lands. 
</P>
<P>
	One legislative deadlock was broken when House and Senate  
conferees finally agreed on a $8.7 billion farm relief package 
after dropping a provision that would have eased the embargo on 
trade with Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	The House Appropriations Committee approved its $316 billion  
version of the labor-health bill by a near party-line 33-26 vote. 
It did so after approving the delay in earned income payments by a 
party-line 32-27 tally. 
</P>
<P>
	That budgetary sleight-of-hand would produce $8.7 billion in  
savings in fiscal 2000. That is because with monthly payments, much 
of next year's funds would be paid out after Oct. 1, 2000 -- the 
start of fiscal 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	The 24-year-old tax credit program is designed to help 20  
million low-income people avoid becoming welfare recipients. The 
credit averages $1,890 annually for families with children, and 
should cost nearly $32 billion next year, the Treasury Department 
estimates. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton signed the fourth spending bill Thursday, a $21 billion  
measure financing energy and water projects. He has also signed 
measures financing the Treasury Department, Congress' own 
operations and military construction projects. 
</P>
<P>
	The nine unfinished bills cover 12 Cabinet departments including  
Defense, Health and Human Services, Interior and Justice, plus 
dozens of smaller agencies. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
