<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Manufacturing Sector Grew in Sept. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The nation's manufacturing sector grew in  
September for the eighth consecutive month, while prices of raw 
materials spurted to the highest level since May 1995, a business 
group reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The overall index for the industrial economy, as portrayed in  
the survey released today by the National Association of Purchasing 
Management, was much stronger than analysts had predicted, reaching 
its highest level in nearly five years. That was further evidence 
the economy grew strongly in the third quarter after a lackluster 
second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The purchasing managers' index for September was 57.8 percent  
compared with 54.2 percent in August -- the strongest reading since 
a 59.2 percent in November 1994, the association said. Analysts had 
projected a 54.2 percent index for September. A reading of more 
than 50 is a sign of an expanding industrial economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The purchasing managers' index is closely watched because it is  
the first national reading for September on U.S. manufacturing 
performance, a key sector of the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	``The manufacturing sector continued to grow in September and at  
a faster rate than it grew in August,'' Norbert J. Ore, chairman of 
the management group's business survey committee, said in a 
statement releasing the results. 
</P>
<P>
	``Both production and new orders accelerated during the month,  
while NAPM's price index jumped to its highest level since May 
1995, indicating that manufacturers continue to pay higher prices 
for their purchases.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The price index surged to 67.6 percent in September from 59.8  
percent in August. That was the highest since 70.5 percent in May 
1995, the association said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 42 percent of those surveyed in September said prices of  
input materials were higher, compared with 32 percent in August. Of 
the balance, 6 percent saw decreases and 52 percent said prices 
were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	``The price reading is extraordinarily high,'' said Mark Vitner,  
an economist at First Union Corp. in Charlotte, N.C. He described 
it as ``a very strong bounce-back'' from depressed levels during 
the Asian crisis that began in the summer of 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the rise in prices was more problematic for  
manufacturers than consumers. ``There's little evidence 
manufacturers will be able to pass on higher prices to consumers 
because of a lot of import competition,'' he said. As a result, 
manufacturers probably will have to find ways to absorb the added 
costs or increase productivity further. 
</P>
<P>
	Measures of future manufacturing strength -- new orders and the  
backlog of orders -- also showed healthy growth in September, the 
report showed. New orders increased to 64.4 percent in September 
from 56.6 percent the month before, while the backlog of orders 
went to 54.5 percent from 52.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Inventories declined, and employment weakened slightly.  
</P>
<P>
	The purchasing managers group represents executives who buy raw  
materials and supplies for industry. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
