<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Female Hall Inductee Reminisces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) -- First is an adjective that naturally  
tags along with Billie Moore's name: The first woman's coach to win 
national championships at two schools, Cal State-Fullerton and 
UCLA. The coach of the first U.S. Olympic women's basketball team. 
</P>
<P>
	But first there was a small town in Kansas in the 1950s and a  
father, who tripled as high school principal and coach of the boys 
and girls basketball teams. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was very fortunate. It was such a small town that I didn't  
know girls weren't supposed to compete,'' said Moore, recalling her 
path from Westmoreland, Kan., to Friday's induction into the 
Basketball Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	But when the family moved to Topeka there were no sports for  
girls in the high school. 
</P>
<P>
	``Girls were supposed to play for social purposes,'' the  
56-year-old Moore said. ``But, by that time the idea of playing to 
win was too ingrained in me for any of that to take.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She has done her share of winning.  
</P>
<P>
	In 24 seasons of coaching Moore compiled a 436-196 record. She  
led Cal State-Fullerton to the AIAW national title in 1970. And 
then won the 1978 title with a UCLA team that included Hall of 
Famers Ann Meyers and Denise Curry. 
</P>
<P>
	As a rookie college coach, she was already giving coaching  
clinics, because that was also the first year colleges abandoned 
the half-court women's game and Moore had grown up playing boy's 
rules. 
</P>
<P>
	``One woman actually asked me how you get the ball from one end  
of the court to the other,'' she said. ``It gave me a bit of an 
edge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While she revels in the growth of the game and the attention the  
WNBA has brought to it, Moore also has some cautions. 
</P>
<P>
	``The women's collegiate game has to be careful with all the  
recruiting and attention paid to the athletes that they do not end 
up spoiled and pampered,'' she said. ``Sometimes people think they 
are on third base when they are only on first.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Her own barometer of the growth of the game is the contrast  
between the millions of dollars and attention devoted to the 1996 
Olympic team, and her unheralded 1976 squad, which first turned the 
national television spotlight on women's basketball with its silver 
medal. 
</P>
<P>
	The team, including Meyers, fellow Hall of Famers Anne Donovan  
and Nancy Lieberman and Tennessee coach Pat Summitt, had six weeks 
to train, often playing high school boys teams. 
</P>
<P>
	And when the women left for Montreal, Moore had $500 in cash and  
the personal credit card of Bill Wall, the head of the organization 
running the national team, to cover the team's expenses. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991001.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 16:40:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NASA Craft Goes Down on Calif. Road </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BARSTOW, Calif. (AP) -- An unmanned experimental NASA aircraft  
being tested for environmental research crash landed in the Mojave 
Desert on Friday, sustaining moderate damage and partially blocking 
a highway. 
</P>
<P>
	No one was injured when the Perseus aircraft crash landed at  
8:45 a.m. crash 4 miles east of Barstow, said Leslie Mathews, a 
spokeswoman for the NASA's Dryden Flight Research Center at Edwards 
Air Force Base. 
</P>
<P>
	There were no immediate details on the damage. The aircraft,  
appearing intact but its nose resting on the ground, blocked the 
westbound side of Interstate 40 through the morning. 
</P>
<P>
	California Highway Patrol Officer Randy Lefebure said the craft  
came down like a helicopter and hit on its nose shortly before 9 
a.m. The Perseus is 25 feet long with a wingspan of 71 1/2 feet. It is 
designed to reach an altitude of 65,000 feet and stay aloft up to 
24 hours. 
</P>
<P>
	The single-engine aircraft had been in the air 2 1/4 hours under  
remote control by a pilot on the ground, Mathews said. 
</P>
<P>
	Perseus is part of NASA's Environmental Research Aircraft and  
Sensor Technology program to develop a variety of unmanned aircraft 
that can carry science packages for long duration and at very high 
altitudes. 
</P>
<P>
	Perseus aircraft are intended to be able to reach 82,000 feet  
with a 165-pound science payload. 
</P>
<P>
	The plane that went down Friday was Perseus B, a model expected  
to reach a maximum altitude of 65,000 feet and stay aloft for up to 
24 hours. 
</P>
<P>
	Perseus A was lost in a crash in November 1994, a little less  
than a year after the first Perseus flight. The aircraft were built 
by Aurora Flight Sciences Corp. of Manassas, Va. Development of 
each plane cost $1.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	According to NASA, Perseus' 9-foot-diameter propeller requires  
an unusual launch technique. With its engine running but the 
propeller locked in a horizontal position, the aircraft is towed 
into the air by a ground vehicle. At a certain altitude, the tow 
line separates and the propeller is engaged by remote control. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991001.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 09:10:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Democrats Back Test Ban Vote Delay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An offer by Senate Republican leaders to force  
a vote on a long-languishing nuclear test-ban treaty won 
conditional Democratic support today. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Democratic leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota told  
reporters he was attempting to negotiate a week's delay with 
Majority Leader Trent Lott and to buy more time for debate in an 
effort to win ratification. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration and Senate Democrats have made the  
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty a top priority and were caught by 
surprise Thursday by a Republican move to schedule a vote next 
week. Republicans say they have the votes to kill the 152-nation 
agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats have long pushed for action on the treaty, but until  
this week GOP leaders had blocked action, bottling it up in the 
Senate Foreign Relations Committee for two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott announced that he was prepared to call up the treaty Oct. 6  
and vote on it after 10 hours of debate, bypassing any hearings. 
</P>
<P>
	Daschle objected to the move Thursday and today made a  
counteroffer: a final vote Oct. 12, after 14 hours of debate. 
</P>
<P>
	Furthermore, Daschle suggested that hearings might be held by  
the Senate Armed Services and Intelligence committees, since 
Foreign Relations, chaired by Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., refuses to 
take it up. 
</P>
<P>
	Daschle said he still resented Lott's efforts to force a vote  
with no, or limited, hearings. But he said the treaty is so 
important that Democrats couldn't afford to turn their backs on the 
offer for a vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican aides said Lott is expected to go along with the  
week's delay, at the very least. 
</P>
<P>
	And Daschle hinted that Democrats want to see a vote on the  
treaty even if not entirely on their terms. As to whether he could 
marshal the 67 votes needed for ratification, Daschle said, ``I 
don't know at this point.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier today, a State Department official told reporters the  
administration needs ample time to make its case for the treaty. 
John Holum, the administration's top arms-control official, said he 
believes the votes could be mustered given enough time. 
</P>
<P>
	He spoke before the Democratic efforts to delay the vote for  
just one week were announced. 
</P>
<P>
	Holum said the treaty was of vital importance because, once it  
takes effect, it will be ``very difficult for new countries to 
develop nuclear weapons.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The prospect of a vote next week prompted Defense Secretary  
William Cohen to decide today to cut short by one day his Asian 
trip so he can return to Washington and take part in the 
discussions. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott's offer to bring up the long languishing treat divided  
Democratic ranks, with some treaty backers urging Daschle to accept 
the offer even if the administration lacked the apparent votes to 
prevail. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bring it up next week,'' said Sen. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., a  
leading test ban activist. He said the offer was ``all right with 
me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Daryl Kimball, director of the Coalition to Reduce Nuclear  
Dangers, a pro-treaty advocacy group, called Lott's offer 
disingenuous. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a rush to judgment,'' he said. ``The Senate needs to  
hold fair hearings, have thorough debate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Helms taunted apprehensive Democrats. ``The same people  
clamoring for action go running to the hills,'' he said. ``If it 
were not so pitiful, this behavior would be amusing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The treaty, which calls for an outright ban on nuclear testing,  
has been signed by 152 nations, including the United States. But it 
has only been ratified by 47 countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Bulgaria and South Korea ratified the treaty just this week.  
</P>
<P>
	If all 45 Democrats support the treaty, as is expected, 22  
Republicans must vote ``yes'' for it to be ratified. 
</P>
<P>
	Lack of support for the pact clearly figured into the GOP change  
of strategy. Republican opponents of the pact said they were 
confident they would prevail. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Joseph Biden of Delaware, senior Democrat on the Senate  
Foreign Relations Committee, said he was optimistic Daschle could 
negotiate more than 10 hours. 
</P>
<P>
	But if not, Biden suggested it was time to move ahead. ``I'm  
ready to roll the dice,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Biden said Democrats appear to be about 15 votes short. He  
suggested that 45 Democrats and seven Republicans currently support 
the treaty. But, he said, senators still ought to be forced to go 
on the record. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want people to pay a political price'' for voting against a  
treaty that has wide support around the world, Biden said. 
</P>
<P>
	Conservatives contend the pact -- which also has not been  
ratified yet by Russia or China -- could threaten the U.S. ability 
to modernize its arsenal if necessary. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters argue the United States already has a vast  
superiority in nuclear weapons, thanks to more than 1,000 nuclear 
tests during the Cold War, and the test ban treaty would lock in 
that advantage. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
