<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pistons Center Dele Might Retire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Detroit Pistons center Bison Dele has  
told the team that he might retire and will miss the start of 
training camp next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Dele is in Beirut and doesn't plan to return to the United  
States for a couple of weeks, the team said in a statement today. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's going through an epiphanal moment in his life,'' agent  
Dwight Manley said Thursday night. ``We'll sit down with the team 
when he gets back and we'll discuss everything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dele, 30, told the Pistons Wednesday of a possible desire to  
retire. In the past 48 hours, Pistons' executive vice presidents 
Rick Sund and Joe Dumars and coach Alvin Gentry have talked with 
Dele. 
</P>
<P>
	``He told me that he was tired and his heart was not in it,''  
Dumars, the Pistons director of player of personnel, said. ``He 
said he did not have the motivation to keep on playing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the statement, Sund emphasized the team's commitment to have  
Dele return. 
</P>
<P>
	Pistons players are to report to training camp Monday. The first  
practice is Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Dele, a 6-foot-11 center who formerly was known as Brian  
Williams, has played two seasons in Detroit. He stands to walk away 
from about $30 million, with five years left on a contract that 
called for him to receive $45 million for seven seasons. He was the 
team's highest-paid player. 
</P>
<P>
	Dele spent two seasons in Detroit after signing as a free agent,  
and his relationship with his teammates was known to be strained. 
Dele's name came up frequently in trade rumors during the summer. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had heard that he might not come back, and I have tried a  
couple of times to call him,'' Pistons star Grant Hill said. ``I 
don't want to comment on any of this because I don't know what is 
going on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shortly after joining the Pistons, Dele admitted his passion for  
basketball was not the greatest. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never had the kind of passion for basketball that my dad had  
for music,'' said Dele, whose father was a member of the Platters. 
``If I had the same kind of passion for basketball as my dad had 
for music, I probably would be a better player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dele averaged 10.5 points and 6.2 rebounds last season, 16.2  
points and 8.9 rebounds the previous season. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
