<DOCNO> APW19991001.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 15:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Apple Inspires Rainbow of Laptops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Major computer makers are giving their laptops a  
splash of color this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM plans to unveil a laptop computer that can be dressed in a  
$30 snap-on cover in different tones of blue, gray, green or red. 
Dell Computer, another longtime purveyor of plain-looking 
computers, introduced blue and gray laptops last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Emboldened by the initial success of Apple's new iBook portable  
computer, stodgier computer makers are splashing up their laptops 
to attract buyers whose taste for color extends well beyond basic 
black. 
</P>
<P>
	While the changes are merely cosmetic, the rise of colorful  
portables is the latest symbol of the industry's progression from 
targeting a single flavor of users to pursuing a rainbow of 
distinctive tastes and attitudes. 
</P>
<P>
	The two-decade-old market for home computers is undergoing a  
shift much like the automotive industry in the early 1900s, when 
the black-only Ford Model T was supplanted by colorful cars from 
General Motors. 
</P>
<P>
	Traditionally, computer makers differentiated their products by  
touting processing power and storage capacity. But a steady drop in 
prices has made powerful computers ubiquitous, leaving makers to 
scramble for new ways to distinguish their wares. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are in a very image-oriented society, and for computers to  
ignore that is kind of silly,'' said Matt Sargent, an analyst with 
the ZD InfoBeads research firm in La Jolla, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Apple Computer began tapping that image-mindedness last year  
when it introduced the futuristic-looking iMac personal computer, 
sold in five bright colors, and then again in early September with 
the new iBook laptop, sold in two fruity colors. 
</P>
<P>
	The iMac spurred several imitators to deviate from the boxy  
design of most desktop computers, and the iBook is apparently 
having the same impact the market for portable computers. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM's ``i'' series of ThinkPad laptop computers, starting at  
$1,500, will be offered next week. Customers who don't want a black 
model can buy a snap-on plastic cover that comes in metallic colors 
that look much like the finish on cars -- Mars Red, Terra Green, 
Eclipse Blue and Lunar Gray -- as well in non-metallic versions. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM boasts that the covers will enable consumers to change the  
color of their machines like a chameleon. A corporate executive, 
for example, might want to choose formal black when toting a laptap 
to a client's office, but switch back to Mars Red back at the home 
office. 
</P>
<P>
	But more importantly for IBM, the removable jacket helps the  
company avoid the costly inventory hurdles facing rivals who make 
computers in more than one color. 
</P>
<P>
	The electronics chain Best Buy, for instance, refused to sell  
Apple's iMacs early this year because Apple wanted it to feature 
all five colors, even though some are less popular than others. 
</P>
<P>
	The removable cover ``means we don't have to predict what will  
be hot in the marketplace,'' an IBM spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, the new crop of laptops strives to retain some of the  
formal look of the machines they seek to out-class. 
</P>
<P>
	Dell Computer introduced its Inspiron laptops in Tahoe Blue and  
Storm Gray last week. The machines are encased in colored plastic 
that surrounds the keyboard and computer screen. 
</P>
<P>
	If the new Dell colors appear more subdued than Apple's or even  
IBM's, there's a good reason, said Greg Nakagawa, director of 
Dell's Inspiron brand. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's was a little bit of a compromise,'' he said. ``We didn't  
want to be so wild.'' 
</P>
<P>
	People using a Dell laptop for a presentation to clients,  
Nakagawa explained, ``may want to show a demonstration on a 
platform that doesn't distract from the message they want to 
relay.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Starting at $1,800, the portables are key to a Dell push to  
expand sales to home and small business users. Consumers, seen as 
more likely to go for different colors, comprise just one-third of 
the market for portables, but demand is growing quickly, according 
to ZD Infobeads. 





  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
