<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 100 Sick From Fast Food in Wash. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ELLENSBURG, Wash. (AP) -- More than 100 people became sick with  
stomach and intestinal inflammation this week after eating at a 
Jack in the Box restaurant in this central Washington town, health 
officials said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The illnesses do not appear linked to hepatitis or the E. coli  
bacteria blamed for a 1993 outbreak that sickened hundreds of 
people and killed four. That was linked to tainted hamburger meat 
distributed to Jack in the Box outlets in Washington and other 
Western states. 
</P>
<P>
	About 50 new cases of mild to moderate viral gastroenteritis  
were reported Friday, three days after people began showing up at 
the emergency room at Kittitas Valley Community Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	The only person admitted to the hospital was released Thursday,  
and others with the illness reported their symptoms -- nausea, 
vomiting, stomach cramps and diarrhea -- were subsiding Friday, said 
John Wolpers of the Kittitas County Health Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Health officials believe an employee who reported to work Monday  
and then became ill during his shift is likely the source of the 
illnesses. The restaurant closed Wednesday, passed health 
inspections and was expected to reopen Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	San Diego-based Foodmaker Inc., the fast-food chain's corporate  
parent, said Friday it will pay the medical bills for patrons who 
became ill. 



</P>
</TEXT>
