<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  E.Timor Peacekeepers on the Move </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DILI, East Timor (AP) -- International peacekeepers ventured deep  
into hostile territory today near the border of West Timor, where 
thousands of militia fighters reportedly have assembled. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. and Australian defense officials say there are indications  
that 2,000 to 4,000 pro-Indonesian militias in West Timor may be 
preparing to begin guerrilla raids on the peacekeeping troops. 
</P>
<P>
	Peacekeepers from the U.N.-approved force known as Interfet were  
flown by helicopter to Balibo, the closest town in East Timor to 
the West Timorese city of Atambua, which has become headquarters 
for the militias who ravaged the territory after its people voted 
to break away from Indonesia on Aug. 30. 
</P>
<P>
	In Atambua, militia leader Joao da Silva Tavares said he planned  
to lead 12,000 fighters back into East Timor on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Interfet doesn't have any right to kick me out of the land  
where I was born,'' Tavares said. ``If the Interfet dares to 
threaten us, we will attack them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, a spokesman for the force, Lt. Col. Mark Kelly, said  
the peacekeepers had no intention of crossing the border with West 
Timor even if they encounter militia. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are conscious of our mandate. It stops in East Timor,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	His remarks seemed to differ with the position voiced Thursday  
by Australian Defense Minister John Moore, who said the 
multinational force had the right to cross into West Timor if it 
was engaged in battle, but that it had to withdraw as soon as any 
conflict ends. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesian Justice Minister Muladi called Moore's statement  
``very arrogant.'' He said that if Australian troops crossed into 
Indonesian territory, ``we have to review our diplomatic relations 
with Australia. We have to be tough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Defense Secretary William Cohen, meeting with officials in  
Thailand, also said today that peacekeepers should be able to 
venture into West Timor in case of cross-border attacks by 
militias. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the most important aspects of peacekeeping is that  
there should be adequate force protection,'' Cohen said. The 
Australian-led force has the right to be ``aggressive in reaction 
to any attacks,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Thai Deputy Foreign Minister Sukhumbhand Paribatra said  
Thailand did not agree. ``Indonesia's sovereignty must be 
respected,'' he told The Associated Press after meeting with Cohen. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, elite Nepalese Gurkha troops today disarmed five  
guerrillas of Falintil, the pro-independence group that led the 
resistance in East Timor after Indonesia invaded the former 
Portuguese colony in 1975. In Dili, Australian soldiers disarmed 
and detained two Falantil members. 
</P>
<P>
	Falintil has volunteered to work with the international force  
and even conduct joint patrols. But the force, under its 
U.N.-approved mandate, is instructed to seize weapons found outside 
the designated bases of any group. 
</P>
<P>
	In Dili, a newly formed National Commission of Human Rights in  
East Timor began its work today, urging the international community 
to speed up the investigation of atrocities in the province. 
</P>
<P>
	``This tragedy was not random. It was a well-planned and  
systematic operation,'' said Maria Domingus Fernades Albes, a 
member of the new body. 
</P>
<P>
	She accused Indonesia of running ``concentration camps'' in West  
Timor, where up to 200,000 East Timorese either fled or were 
forcibly taken after the vote for independence. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.N. refugee agency is preparing to airlift relief supplies  
to East Timorese living ``in appalling conditions'' in West Timor, 
spokesman Kris Janowski said today. The U.N. High Commissioner for 
Refugees also is drawing up plans to start flying refugees back to 
East Timor if they want to return, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Jose Alexandre ``Xanana'' Gusmao, the former  
guerrilla commander who is widely expected to become independent 
East Timor's first elected president, arrived in Portugal today in 
search of international help to rebuild his homeland. 
</P>
<P>
	The Portuguese government has donated more than $4 million in  
humanitarian assistance to its former colony since the ballot was 
held and East Timor plunged into anarchy. 
  	   	
</P>
