<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FDA Warns of Certain Dog Chews </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Dog owners should wash their hands after  
giving their pets certain dog chews, particularly those made of pig 
ears, because the popular pet treats may be contaminated with 
salmonella, the government warned Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 30 people in Canada are suffering infection with  
Salmonella infantis linked to dog chews made from pork- or 
beef-derived materials, including pig ears, beef jerky and pigskin, 
health authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	Salmonella is not considered a risk for the dogs, but people can  
become infected easily if they touch something that carries the 
bacterium and then touch their mouths or their own food. In healthy 
people, Salmonella causes flulike symptoms, including vomiting, 
abdominal pain and diarrhea, but it can cause life-threatening 
illness in people with weak immune systems. 
</P>
<P>
	No Americans are known to be sick, but there is no way to know  
if contaminated dog chews already were imported. 
</P>
<P>
	So the U.S. Food and Drug Administration urged American pet  
owners to handle dog chews very carefully. 
</P>
<P>
	Anyone who touches one should wash their hands with hot water  
and soap and watch children to ensure they do not put the pet treat 
into their mouths. Elderly people, young children and people with 
weakened immune systems are particularly at risk from salmonella 
and should avoid any contact with these chews, the FDA said. 
</P>
<P>
	The FDA said Friday it will detain imports of pig ears to test  
for salmonella, and will examine U.S. manufacturing of dog chews. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
