<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> PGA Head Doesn't Regret Celebration  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PALM BEACH GARDENS, Fla. (AP) -- The head of the PGA of America  
is not faulting American team members for their much-maligned burst 
of enthusiasm on the 17th green of last weekend's Ryder Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, he says the players and wives who mobbed Justin Leonard  
after he sank a 45-foot putt were simply showing the kind of 
emotion so lacking in the sport. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've come to expect our players to walk around likhey're  
carrying a briefcase,'' Jim Awtrey, CEO of the PGA of America, 
which runs the international competition, said Thursday. ``We saw 
they're human and they get excited. We had 12 Sergios (Garcia) out 
there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Awtrey said, though, that he did regret the celebration took  
place before Spaniard Jose Maria Olabal had a chance at a 25-foot 
putt that could have kept his match with Leona alive. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a shame the celebration on 17 didn't occur after Jose's  
putt,'' Awtrey said. ``But I don't think -- and I was there -- it had 
anything to do with the outcome of the match. To let something as 
small as that overshadow what the Ryder Cup is all about, I don't 
think it's right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, Awtrey agreed that American fans need to be stopped  
from heckling players. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will have low tolerance with fans who cross the ne. People  
were taken out of the stands, I don't knw how many, but that's 
pbably what we'll have to do more of.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
