<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Commerce Department Closed By Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A fire Friday at the Commerce Department sent  
48 people, including 16 firefighters and emergency medical 
technicians, to the hospital to be treated for possible exposure to 
PCBs. 
</P>
<P>
	A transformer that used PCBs as a coolant caught fire about 6  
a.m., filling sections of Commerce building with smoke and PCB 
levels above the acceptable 50 parts per million, said D.C. Fire 
Chief Don Edwards. 
</P>
<P>
	Commerce Secretary William Daley said the sprawling building a  
block from the White House would remain closed through the weekend 
``while experts analyze the level of contamination in the material 
that was removed from the building.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At least two people, both Commerce Department workers, were  
directly contaminated with PCBs, said Dr. Anthony MacIntyre, an 
emergency room physician at George Washington University Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	One was sprayed with liquid from the transformer and the other  
took in heavy smoke from the fire. Everyone was released within two 
hours, except the man exposed to smoke. He was being kept for 
observation after complaining of dizziness, Daley said. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton said he was ``relieved'' that the fire was  
``extinguished quickly and apparently without any serious 
injuries.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Symptoms of PCB exposure include skin irritation, swollen eyes  
and upper respiratory problems. Long-term effects can include liver 
damage and other problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``It could be five years, 10 years from now,'' said firefighter  
Rudolph Blyther said, one of those taken to the hospital. When 
asked if he's concerned, he said, ``You know I am.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There is no direct test to determine PCB contamination but  
results from blood tests should determine others who inhaled lots 
of smoke, which could indicate PCB contamination, MacIntyre said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The exposure, if any, was minimal,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The trouble began as workers in the basement of the Commerce  
Department building heard a crash in an adjacent room, said Stephen 
Reid, a battalion chief with the District of Columbia Fire 
Department. 
</P>
<P>
	They discovered the fire and doused most of the blaze with  
extinguishers by the time firefighters arrived, Reid said. 
Approximately 400 employees were evacuated. 
</P>
<P>
	All 48 people, including 32 Commerce Department employees or  
contractors, considered at risk of exposure were ``decontaminated'' 
-- given showers and clean, yellow suits in a courtyard in the 
center of the Commerce building. 
</P>
<P>
	At the hospital, they bathed with soap and water in special  
decontamination showers and were tested for symptoms, a hospital 
spokeswoman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Widespread use of PCBs, or polychlorinated biphenyls, in  
transformers was phased out in the 1980s. In December, the 
Environmental Protection Agency began requiring that all facilities 
still using PCB transformers be registered. 
</P>
<P>
	Daley defended as ``absolutely necessary'' the decision to close  
the building, along with the National Aquarium inside it, all day 
Friday and through the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	If the fire had occurred later in the day, some 3,700 people  
would have been in the building, Daley said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991001.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 10:56:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Thompson, McHale Get to Hoops Hall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) -- Little ever came easy for John  
Thompson. 
</P>
<P>
	His outspoken views on minority access challenged the basketball  
world. His unrelenting high standards sometimes frustrated his 
friends. He even repeated sixth grade. 
</P>
<P>
	So it was perhaps no shock that it took the retired Georgetown  
coach three tries to make the Basketball Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't mind saying what I don't want and what I don't like,''  
Thompson said today at a news conference. ``And I don't mind saying 
what I want and what I like.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson said he was pleased to be entering the Hall of Fame  
tonight with Boston Celtics star Kevin McHale, Cleveland Cavaliers 
executive Wayne Embry, women's college coach Billie Moore, and the 
late NBA pioneer and owner Fred Zollner. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hear all these things: Hard guy, tough guy,'' McHale said,  
gesturing toward Thompson. ``Not the guy I know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I never thought that he was arrogant. I never thought that he  
was difficult. He challenged you,'' said Georgetown coach Craig 
Esherick, who played for Thompson and later served as his 
assistant. Then he added, ``There were some days I left the court 
as a player not thinking good thoughts about him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A big man with a husky voice and booming laugh, Thompson turned  
into a national fixture in his 27 seasons at Georgetown. Stalking 
courtside with a towel habitually draped over his shoulder, he 
watched his teams make 24 straight postseason appearances and three 
NCAA Final Fours. When his team won the national championship in 
1984, he became the first black coach with that title. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet colleagues say Thompson always demanded that his players be  
their best both on court and in class. ``He was a tremendously 
demanding educator,'' said Bill Shapland, a 15-year staffer. ``He 
was not interested in giving you a lot of excuses or wiggle room 
for not being the best you can be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson also made demands of the basketball world, pushing for  
more and better chances for minorities. He endured racial taunts 
when he first fielded a predominantly black team at Georgetown. He 
later boycotted two games in 1989 to protest NCAA Proposition 42, 
saying its financial limits hurt minority athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	McHale, who formed a formidable frontcourt with Larry Bird and  
Robert Parish, also set high standards, but mainly for himself. In 
the 1987 NBA Finals against the Los Angeles Lakers, McHale's right 
foot was so badly hurt that he was said to use a patio chair as a 
walker when he was off court. 
</P>
<P>
	``With all that pain, we don't want you to play,'' his coach,  
K.C. Jones, recalls telling him. ``He said, `I'm doing this!' '' 
</P>
<P>
	The Celtics lost in six games anyway, and McHale underwent  
surgery. He was hobbled by foot and ankle injuries until retiring 
in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	But during 13 seasons with Boston, McHale played on championship  
teams in 1981, 1984 and 1986. ``He was a winner. We both had the 
same desire to win,'' said Bird, who now coaches the Indiana 
Pacers. 
</P>
<P>
	A Minnesota boy with an easygoing exterior, McHale grew to a  
long-limbed 6-foot-10. He came to Boston in 1980 as the sixth man. 
</P>
<P>
	``McHale was a big, gangly kid who looked like a stand-in for  
the Frankenstein monster when he first showed up. But he had this 
indomitable will to win,'' said Tom Heinsohn, a former Celtics 
player and coach. 
</P>
<P>
	McHale added a jump hook and fadeaway jumper to his expanding  
offensive repertoire. ``Those two shots were almost unstoppable,'' 
Parish said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	McHale eventually transformed himself into one of the league's  
most feared offensive threats, averaging 55 percent from the floor 
during his career. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991001.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 12:30:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McCartney Inspired by Ga. Pharmacy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- When Paul McCartney visited Atlanta earlier this  
year, he discovered a pharmacy filled with bath salts, incense, 
candles -- and the title song for his new album. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was looking in the shop window and I saw this bottle of bath  
salts called `Run Devil Run,''' McCartney said in a statement 
accompanying the album. ``I thought it was a good title for a song. 
So when I was on holiday after that, I started thinking of words 
for it and it came quite easily.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCartney was in Atlanta in January to see daughter Heather  
unveil her line of household creations at a trade show. He spotted 
Miller's Rexall Drugs store while he and son James, 21, walked 
around downtown. James had said he wanted to visit the ``funky'' 
side of downtown, McCartney said. 
</P>
<P>
	The album hits stores Tuesday. The store is pictured on the  
album cover, but the name ``Miller's'' on the sign has been changed 
to ``Earl's.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991001.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 10:56:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Thompson, McHale Get to Hoops Hall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) -- Little ever came easy for John  
Thompson. 
</P>
<P>
	His outspoken views on minority access challenged the basketball  
world. His unrelenting high standards sometimes frustrated his 
friends. He even repeated sixth grade. 
</P>
<P>
	So it was perhaps no shock that it took the retired Georgetown  
coach three tries to make the Basketball Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't mind saying what I don't want and what I don't like,''  
Thompson said today at a news conference. ``And I don't mind saying 
what I want and what I like.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson said he was pleased to be entering the Hall of Fame  
tonight with Boston Celtics star Kevin McHale, Cleveland Cavaliers 
executive Wayne Embry, women's college coach Billie Moore, and the 
late NBA pioneer and owner Fred Zollner. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hear all these things: Hard guy, tough guy,'' McHale said,  
gesturing toward Thompson. ``Not the guy I know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I never thought that he was arrogant. I never thought that he  
was difficult. He challenged you,'' said Georgetown coach Craig 
Esherick, who played for Thompson and later served as his 
assistant. Then he added, ``There were some days I left the court 
as a player not thinking good thoughts about him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A big man with a husky voice and booming laugh, Thompson turned  
into a national fixture in his 27 seasons at Georgetown. Stalking 
courtside with a towel habitually draped over his shoulder, he 
watched his teams make 24 straight postseason appearances and three 
NCAA Final Fours. When his team won the national championship in 
1984, he became the first black coach with that title. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet colleagues say Thompson always demanded that his players be  
their best both on court and in class. ``He was a tremendously 
demanding educator,'' said Bill Shapland, a 15-year staffer. ``He 
was not interested in giving you a lot of excuses or wiggle room 
for not being the best you can be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson also made demands of the basketball world, pushing for  
more and better chances for minorities. He endured racial taunts 
when he first fielded a predominantly black team at Georgetown. He 
later boycotted two games in 1989 to protest NCAA Proposition 42, 
saying its financial limits hurt minority athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	McHale, who formed a formidable frontcourt with Larry Bird and  
Robert Parish, also set high standards, but mainly for himself. In 
the 1987 NBA Finals against the Los Angeles Lakers, McHale's right 
foot was so badly hurt that he was said to use a patio chair as a 
walker when he was off court. 
</P>
<P>
	``With all that pain, we don't want you to play,'' his coach,  
K.C. Jones, recalls telling him. ``He said, `I'm doing this!' '' 
</P>
<P>
	The Celtics lost in six games anyway, and McHale underwent  
surgery. He was hobbled by foot and ankle injuries until retiring 
in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	But during 13 seasons with Boston, McHale played on championship  
teams in 1981, 1984 and 1986. ``He was a winner. We both had the 
same desire to win,'' said Bird, who now coaches the Indiana 
Pacers. 
</P>
<P>
	A Minnesota boy with an easygoing exterior, McHale grew to a  
long-limbed 6-foot-10. He came to Boston in 1980 as the sixth man. 
</P>
<P>
	``McHale was a big, gangly kid who looked like a stand-in for  
the Frankenstein monster when he first showed up. But he had this 
indomitable will to win,'' said Tom Heinsohn, a former Celtics 
player and coach. 
</P>
<P>
	McHale added a jump hook and fadeaway jumper to his expanding  
offensive repertoire. ``Those two shots were almost unstoppable,'' 
Parish said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	McHale eventually transformed himself into one of the league's  
most feared offensive threats, averaging 55 percent from the floor 
during his career. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
