<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7:30 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Oct. 1, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Thailand Negotiates With Hostage-Takers  
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Thai authorities continued to negotiate  
Friday night with a dozen armed Myanmar dissidents who took over 
their country's embassy in Bangkok at gunpoint and seized about 30 
hostages. One hostage-taker, who claims to be a student, said early 
Saturday morning that he and the others distrusted the Thai 
government, and if a helicopter was not provided, they would ``have 
to do something,'' which could include killing hostages. He did not 
say there was an explicit threat to kill Myanmar hostages every 
half-hour if the aircraft didn't come, as some of his comrades had 
been quoted saying. The dissidents demanded the release of 
political prisoners and the convening of an elected parliament. 

</P>
<P>
	GOP Backs Off Benefits Slowdown  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republican leaders backed away today  
from their plan to slow income-support payments to working poor 
people. Though not yet jettisoning the proposal, lawmakers and 
aides acknowledged they were looking for other ways to raise the 
$8.7 billion that they had expected the plan to save in the budget 
for fiscal 2000, which began today. Sen. John McCain joined George 
W. Bush as the second Republican presidential contender criticizing 
the idea. And House GOP moderates and Senate Republicans predicted 
the plan's demise. 

</P>
<P>
	HUD Awards Vouchers to Working Poor  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Putting dollars behind the effort to guide  
welfare recipients to employment, the government awarded $280 
million in vouchers designed to help about 50,000 families across 
the country. This initial distribution of the welfare-to-work 
vouchers by the Department of Housing and Urban Development will 
subsidize rents of low-income families receiving welfare or 
recently off welfare to enable them to rent apartments near 
available jobs, child care and transportation. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia Renounces Chechen Parliament  
</P>
<P>
	GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- The Russian government announced Friday  
that it no longer recognizes the democratically elected parliament 
of Chechnya. The military said its forces would establish a 
security zone in the breakaway republic, as jets continued to bomb 
targets across Chechnya, sending more than 88,000 civilians fleeing 
to neighboring regions. The statement underlined Russia's 
increasingly tough stance on Chechnya, clouding prospects for talks 
on preventing the conflict from escalating into an all-out war. 

</P>
<P>
	March Toward Milosevic Home Halted  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Entering their third night of a  
showdown with Serbian authorities Friday, protesters were prevented 
from heading toward the home of President Slobodan Milosevic as 
riot police sealed off part of the capital. The leaders of street 
protests said they would increase pressure on Milosevic despite 
police beatings and arrests of opposition activists. The opposition 
blames Milosevic for a decade of economic misery, aggravated by his 
defiance of NATO that led to prolonged bombing and the de facto 
loss of the Serbian province of Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Medicare To Pay for Low-Fat Diet  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Medicare will pay for up to 1,800 elderly  
Americans with severe heart disease to try Dr. Dean Ornish's famous 
but radical ultra low-fat diet, to see if it could be an 
alternative to heart surgery. Under the pilot project, Medicare 
patients who have been told they will soon need bypass surgery or 
an angioplasty to clear clogged heart arteries can instead try the 
intensive diet-and-lifestyle program. 

</P>
<P>
	Big Tuna Stirring Dangerous Hunts  
</P>
<P>
	CHATHAM, Mass. (AP) -- Big tuna are so plentiful off Cape Cod  
this year that inexperienced, weekend fishermen are taking to the 
seas -- and getting in over their heads. At least three vessels have 
capsized in the past week, two of them because the fish were too 
big for the boats. Fisheries officials are not sure exactly why 
there is an abundance of tuna this year. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Slips 63.95 to 10,273  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks resumed their slide today after new  
reports showed that the economy's surging growth has not slowed in 
recent months. The data renewed concerns that the Federal Reserve 
will raise interest rates next week. The Dow industrials closed 
down 63.95 at 10,273.00 and the Nasdaq composite index fell 9.31 to 
2,736.85. 

</P>
<P>
	Oilers and NHL To Honor No. 99  
</P>
<P>
	EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) -- Edmonton will officially welcome home  
its favorite adopted son, Wayne Gretzky, tonight by lifting his No. 
99 jersey to the ceiling of the rink where he helped the Oilers win 
four Stanley Cups. The rink already has a bronze statue of him in 
front. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRAD FOSS  
  	   	
</P>
