<DOCNO> APW19991001.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 02:50:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Share Prices Rise / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The release of data showing a falling unemployment  
rate boosted Tokyo share prices today. The dollar gained against 
the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average climbed 107.10  
points, or 0.61 percent, to close the day at 17,712.56. On 
Thursday, the average climbed 323.18 points, or 1.87 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 105.94 yen, up 0.28 yen from late Thursday in  
Tokyo but below its late New York level of 106.77 yen overnight. 
The dollar ranged between 105.30 yen and 106.37 yen in today's 
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices jumped following news Japan's  
unemployment rate for August improved from the previous month. The 
better-than-expected data spurred further optimism over the 
country's nascent economic recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	The jobless rate fell to 4.7 percent from July's record high 4.9  
percent as more men found jobs, the government announced. 
</P>
<P>
	The jobless rate for men stood at 4.7 percent in August, down  
from the previous month's record-high 5.1 percent. The rate for 
women was unchanged in August at 4.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Lingering worries by traders over an accident at a nuclear plant  
north of Tokyo on Thursday had little impact on the overall market, 
traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	An accidental nuclear reaction at a uranium processing plant was  
contained early today, nearly a full day after a leak of 
radioactive gas seriously injured three workers and possibly 
contaminated 46 others. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials described the accident as the most serious ever at a  
nuclear facility in Japan but said that by today radiation levels 
outside the plant had returned to normal. They added they did not 
believe there was a serious threat to local residents. 
</P>
<P>
	The facility where the accident occurred is about 70 miles  
northeast of Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Sumitomo Metal Mining, owner of the company that  
operates the facility, fell sharply. It closed down 94 cents, or 19 
percent, at $4.03. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York on Wednesday, the Dow Jones industrial average rose  
123.47 points, or 1.2 percent, to 10,336.95. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 543 million shares changed hands on the first  
section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange, down from 559.7 million shares 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Decliners outnumbered advancers 654 to 585, while 101 issues  
remained unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 8.25 points, or 0.55 percent, to 1,515.08. The 
TOPIX closed up 91 points, or 2.39 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, traders were largely focused on the Bank  
of Japan's quarterly survey of business sentiment, due out Monday. 
Traders also watched the central bank for further signs of a change 
in its monetary policy amid the yen's recent strength. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 113.44 yen, up from  
112.24 yen late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell  
to 1.6700 percent from Thursday's finish of 1.7100 percent. Its 
price rose 0.35 points to 100.26. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
