<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chilean Journalist To Get Asylum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Immigration officials have recommended political  
asylum for a Chilean journalist who fled to Miami after her book on 
corruption in Chile's highest court was banned there. 
</P>
<P>
	Alejandra Matus, 33, author of ``The Black Book of Chilean  
Justice,'' will qualify for asylum after passing a background 
check. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a shame for the Chilean government that this happened,''  
Ms. Matus said after being notified of the INS decision Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Matus' 340-page book describes abuse of power,  
influence-peddling and nepotism by members of Chile's Supreme 
Court. Many of its members were appointed during Gen. Augusto 
Pinochet's military regime from 1973-90. 
</P>
<P>
	A Chilean judge banned Ms. Matus' book and ordered her arrested  
last April under a 1950s law that makes it a crime to slander the 
South American country's president, cabinet ministers, legislators 
or judges. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics say the law has been used principally to silence  
journalists and politicians, about 26 of whom have been jailed 
since 1990, according to freedom-of-the-press organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	John D. Hopkins, chairman of the International Journalism  
Committee of the Society of Professional Journalists, called the 
asylum recommendation ``good news for journalists throughout the 
Americas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a sad reminder, though,'' he said, ``that there still  
are parts of the world where the cost to speak, publish or read the 
truth can be the loss of someone's beloved homeland.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
