<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Probe Eyes Mental Hospital Deaths </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- At least 24 people died and 1,000 were injured  
or abused after being restrained or put into seclusion at mental 
health facilities in 1998, congressional investigators said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The actual number of avoidable deaths and injuries probably is  
much higher, said the General Accounting Office, Congress's 
investigative arm. Only 15 states have reporting systems, it said, 
and most facilities are not required to report. 
</P>
<P>
	``The random use of restraints cited by the GAO suggests bad  
luck, more than medical science, determines which patients end up 
restrained, secluded or even dead,'' said Sen. Joseph Lieberman, 
D-Conn. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers in the House and the Senate, following Hartford  
Courant investigative articles in Lieberman's home state, have 
introduced bills that would require better reporting, better 
training of mental health care workers and a doctor's authorization 
before a patient is restrained. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate will hold hearings on the issue before Congress  
adjourns for the year, said Sen. William Roth, the Delaware 
Republican who chairs the Finance Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't have to tell you that hospitals should be places of  
safety and healing,'' Roth said. The GAO report and the articles 
suggest an urgent need to ``rededicate ourselves to continued 
improvement,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mental health experts generally agree that a patient must be  
restrained or put into seclusion on an emergency basis when he is a 
danger to himself or to others, the GAO said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Far less agreement exists about the use of restraint and  
seclusion in any other situation,'' such as punishment or staff 
convenience, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	The GAO said 240,000 people require either inpatient treatment  
in mental hospitals or residential treatment in centers or group 
homes each year. About 120,000 people with mental retardation lived 
in intermediate care facilities and 240,000 others lived in smaller 
residential settings in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	No federal regulations governed the use of restraint and  
seclusion in those facilities until July 1999, when the Health Care 
Financing Administration put new restrictions on hospitals that 
received federal Medicare money. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although this is a positive step, people in residential  
treatment centers and group homes participating in the Medicaid 
Home and Community-Based Waiver program have limited federal 
protection,'' the GAO report said. ``While some states have 
regulations in place governing the use of restraint and seclusion, 
often these regulations do not apply to privately operated 
facilities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This is about protecting our loved ones from deadly  
restraint,'' said Rep. Rosa DeLauro, D-Conn. ``They should not fear 
for their lives -- and their families should not fear for their 
lives -- when they check into a hospital.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991001.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 09:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alaska Subsistence Fishing Mediated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) -- The federal government today took control  
of subsistence fishing on most Alaska waters after state 
legislators failed to agree on a constitutional amendment that 
would bring state law in line with federal law. 
</P>
<P>
	A contingent of opponents in the Senate defeated a proposed  
amendment that, if then passed by voters, would have allowed 
priority for rural fishermen. That would discriminate against 
people who live in urban areas who depend on fish and game for 
food, opponents said. 
</P>
<P>
	The bitter debate struck on historical fears that stem from  
Alaska's territorial days before it became a state in 1959. Before 
then, federal fish management practices created many problems. 
Supporters said the failure to act jeopardized the freedom from 
federal control that Alaska won with statehood. 
</P>
<P>
	``We could have prevented the offensive intrusion of federal  
management of Alaska's fish and game resources -- a right that was 
at the root of our battle for statehood,'' said Gov. Tony Knowles, 
who called the special session in an effort to pass the amendment. 
</P>
<P>
	``The feds are here and certainly its a sad day,'' said House  
Speaker Brian Porter, R-Anchorage, after Thursday night's 
adjournment. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal managers already oversee subsistence hunting on federal  
land. This step expands the control to fishing on most lakes, 
rivers and streams. 
</P>
<P>
	Subsistence priorities free those who depend on wildlife for  
food -- often, but not exclusively, Indians, Eskimos and other 
native groups -- from many regular hunting and fishing regulations. 
It also allows federal wildlife managers to restrict the amount of 
wildlife taken by other hunters and fishermen to protect the 
subsistence users. 
</P>
<P>
	The immediate impact of the takeover will likely be negligible  
because the summer fishing season is nearly over. But the Federal 
Subsistence Board could begin restricting commercial fishing as 
early as next spring to protect subsistence users, and the impact 
of federal management decisions on commercial, sport and 
personal-use fishing is expected to grow over time. 
</P>
<P>
	The House passed the constitutional amendment, but the measure  
fell short in the Senate. The House then adjourned to block a 
Senate plan to try to pass a drastically revised version. 
</P>
<P>
	The conflict originated when a federal law enacted in 1980, the  
Alaska National Interest Lands Conservation Act, provided that 
rural residents would have priority for subsistence hunting and 
fishing. 
</P>
<P>
	The state Supreme Court ruled in 1989 that the federal law  
violated the state Constitution, which guarantees equal access to 
fish and game. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents of the amendment, which would have revised the  
Constitution to allow for the rural priority and bring the state 
into compliance with federal law, instead want the federal law 
challenged in court. 
</P>
<P>
	``The senators protected the interests of all Alaskans and their  
civil rights by not compromising,'' said Dick Bishop, the vice 
president of the Alaska Outdoor Council. 
</P>
<P>
	But Julie Kitka, president of the Alaska Federation of Natives,  
expressed disappointment, saying, ``For over 10 years we've waited 
and urged the state to do what's right for its Native citizens -- 
what is morally right and what is right by federal law.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
