<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 01:00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Giants End Run at Windswept Park </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- The San Francisco Giants didn't leave their  
heart at Candlestick Park. They took it with them. 
</P>
<P>
	On a brilliant Thursday that belied the park's reputation for  
swirling winds, fog and cold, the Giants played the Los Angeles 
Dodgers in the last baseball game at Candlestick and then 
celebrated the end of their 40-year-stay at the park. 
</P>
<P>
	They didn't leave without a relic, digging out home plate,  
putting the old park's heart on a helicopter and flying it uptown, 
where it was planted into the team's new stadium near downtown 
that's opening next season. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not a sad day for the Giants,'' Peter Magowan, the  
club's managing general partner, said during postgame ceremonies. 
``Yes, we are leaving our home, but we are going to a new one, and 
I promise you it will be the best ballpark in this country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In many ways, Candlestick Park might have been the worst, its  
predominantly chilly, windy environment producing the zany and the 
weird, and posing a survival test for fans and players alike. 
</P>
<P>
	But Candlestick was also the scene of some of baseball's great  
moments and the venue for some of the game's best players, 
including Hall of Famers Willie Mays, Willie McCovey and Juan 
Marichal. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was very special,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said.  
``Fans were really into it today, but they weren't too bad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And it was in that spirit that the curtain came down on baseball  
at the 'Stick. 
</P>
<P>
	Marichal tossed out the ceremonial first pitch, signaling the  
beginning of the end, and after the Dodgers beat the Giants 9-4, 
Mays came on to throw the symbolic final pitch to his godson, 
Giants star Barry Bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess all you can say is, `Tell it goodbye,' '' longtime  
Giants broadcaster Lon Simmons said during postgame ceremonies that 
ended with the blowing out of a candle. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot of good memories, a lot of bad memories here,''  
Mays said. ``I'm happy. I don't understand why when you leave a 
good thing and you go to another thing that's going to be good for 
the fans that you've got to be sad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The last day for baseball was unlike any other at Candlestick in  
other ways. 
</P>
<P>
	The park's famous winds were quiet, the familiar shroud of cold  
and fog nowhere to be seen or felt. Even so, the elements loomed in 
everyone's thoughts. 
</P>
<P>
	``The wind and the cold made it miserable. Night games were  
terrible,'' recalled Mike Ivie, who was among some 60 former Giants 
players on hand to take a final bow before a crowd of 61,389, the 
most ever to attend a regular-season game here. 
</P>
<P>
	``It took a little bit to put on the insulated underwear and go  
play nine innings, but just being here and seeing all the old 
coaches players and made it enjoyable for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There were rousing cheers for the oldtimers and current players  
and plenty of boos for the Dodgers. 
</P>
<P>
	Many in the crowd wore old jerseys and hats and some made their  
feelings known in signs dotting the stands. 
</P>
<P>
	``Adios Candlestick,'' one sign read. ``We'll miss the thrills  
and chills,'' read another. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was great to be out here today, seeing all those players  
who gave me sleepless nights,'' said Tommy Lasorda, who managed the 
Dodgers for 20 years and now is a team vice president. ``I love 
this place, but the new park is going to be great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maligned for its bitter weather and isolation, Candlestick was  
also remembered for withstanding the October 1989 earthquake that 
ravaged the Bay area and interrupted the World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	The All-Star game was played at the 'Stick in 1961, when the  
winds blew pitcher Stu Miller off the mound. 
</P>
<P>
	Dedicated the year before by Vice President Richard Nixon as  
``the finest ballpark in America,'' Candlestick also was the scene 
of the 16-inning scoreless duel between Marichal and the Braves' 
Warren Spahn (Mays won it with a homer); McCovey's 500-foot 
upper-deck homer in a 1966 loss to the Mets and lefty Dave 
Dravecky's August 1989 miracle comeback from cancer, in which he 
beat the Reds. 
</P>
<P>
	A 1964 game was delayed after a visiting Dodgers outfielder lost  
a fly ball in the fog, though the final game was played under a 
brilliant sun. The temperature at gametime was 82 degrees. 
</P>
<P>
	And with the sun out and the stands and dugout warmed by  
nostalgia, even the bad, cold days didn't seem so windy or so cold. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never really minded it,'' said San Francisco manager Dusty  
Baker, a native of Sacramento who got his first hit here in 1968 as 
a rookie with the Atlanta Braves. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whenever I'm here, I've had all my friends and family here, so  
it was always like a homecoming for me. I had to have my best games 
here in front of my home boys.'' 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* In his last game of the season, Bonds went 0-for-4. He  
faced season-ending arthroscopic surgery on his right knee today. 
... Raul Mondesi hit the last homer at Candlestick, a three-run 
shot in the sixth. ... San Francisco's Marvin Benard homered to 
lead off the game. ... The Giants went 49-32 at home this season. 
... Eric Karros had two singles for Los Angeles, extending his 
hitting streak to 10 games. ... Shawn Estes (11-11) was the loser 
and Jeff Williams (2-0) got the win. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
