<DOCNO> APW19991001.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 15:20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 4 Tenn. Players Cleared To Play </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Four Tennessee players suspended as part  
of the school's academic fraud investigation have been cleared to 
play in Saturday's game against Auburn, school president J. Wade 
Gilley said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Gilley said investigators ``found nothing'' indicating any  
wrongdoing by the players, so the Southeastern Conference will 
allow them to play. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no cloud over the players,'' Gilley said.  
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the four seldom-used redshirt freshmen, starting  
center Spencer Riley was cleared of any wrongdoing, Gilley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Riley had not been suspended, but school officials decided to  
look again into a 1995 allegation that an athletic department 
employee had co-written a paper with the player. Riley was cleared 
in 1995, and investigators found no new evidence to change that 
finding. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee is continuing its investigation of allegations that  
athletic department tutors did schoolwork for athletes, a possible 
violation of school honor codes and NCAA rules. 
</P>
<P>
	ESPN reported this week that internal memos show high-level  
administrators in Tennessee's athletic department were told four 
tutors might have done schoolwork for Riley and four unidentified 
football players, a baseball player and a female athlete. Three of 
the football players have transferred. 
</P>
<P>
	Apparently, none of the information was passed on to campus  
authorities charged with investigating possible rules infractions, 
university officials say. 
</P>
<P>
	Gilley said the allegations were ``rumor and speculation'' by  
people at the school ``who had an ax to grind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The four redshirt freshmen -- kick returner Leonard Scott, tight  
end Reggie Ridley, linebacker Keyon Whiteside and defensive tackle 
Ryan Rowe -- were held out of the seventh-ranked Volunteers' 17-16 
victory over Memphis last Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee athletic director Doug Dickey and two of the school's  
investigators drove to Birmingham, Ala., on Thursday and told SEC 
commissioner Roy Kramer of the university's findings. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC issued its decision about the players late Thursday,  
though no statement from the league was released, Gilley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dickey said a written report will be prepared and submitted to  
the SEC and NCAA as quickly as possible, but that ``since no 
players were ruled ineligible, we don't have a lack of 
institutional control charge and (the NCAA has) no infraction to 
react to us about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other issues raised in the investigation that deal with tutors,  
writing laboratories, coordination and oversight of the programs 
will be looked by the Faculty Senate and the Athletics Board, 
Dickey said. 
</P>
<P>
	The NCAA could get involved in that aspect of the investigation.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
