<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Fall; Dow Down 106.38 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks resumed their downward trek today after  
new reports showed the economy's surging growth has not slowed in 
recent months. The data again raised concerns that the Federal 
Reserve will further boost interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	In afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial  
average was down 106.38 at 10,230.57. The blue-chip index was off 
as much as 135 points in earlier trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's  
500 index was down 9.11 at 1,273.60, and the Nasdaq composite index 
fell 34.02 to 2,712.14. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks fell after the Commerce Department reported that personal  
income -- which includes wages, interest and government benefits -- 
rose 0.5 percent in August, the eighth straight monthly increase. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, consumer spending rose 0.9 percent in August  
and the personal savings rate matched a record low of negative 1.5 
percent. While robust consumer spending has powered the growth of 
the U.S. economy, many economists fear that if spending continues 
unchecked, inflation will begin escalating. 
</P>
<P>
	Also today, the National Association of Purchasing Management  
reported that the nation's manufacturing sector grew at a 
stronger-than expected rate in September. It was the eight 
consecutive month of gains. 
</P>
<P>
	The NAPM also reported that prices of raw materials spurted to  
the highest level since May 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	``First, the personal income and consumer spending report  
knocked the market down,'' said Alfred E. Goldman, director of 
market analysis at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc. in St. Louis. ``Then 
the NAPM really was the bullet. The market really didn't like the 
rise in prices paid.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed has tried to stave off inflation by raising interest  
rates twice so far this year. Fears of a third increase have kept 
stocks off balance for the past month, and while many analysts 
expect the Fed to leave rates unchanged when it meets next Tuesday, 
today's reports injected a last-minute note of uncertainty. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists say interest rate increases take several months to  
produce a measurable effect on the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Worries about rising interest rates also led to a slump in bond  
prices, which pushed up the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond to 
6.16 percent this afternoon from 6.04 percent late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hewlett Packard fell 3 13/16 to 86 15/16, contributing to the  
Dow's decline. The computer maker warned that its fiscal 
fourth-quarter revenue could fall short of Wall Street expectations 
because of component shortages caused by last week's earthquake in 
Taiwan. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM fell 5 to 116, the steepest decliner in the Dow.  
</P>
<P>
	Revlon shares also slumped, falling 5 3/4 to 12 1/2 after the  
cosmetics giant said it expected a loss in the third quarter. The 
New York-based company has not been able to find a buyer, so it now 
is looking to sell off its salon-based business and some Latin 
American brands. 
</P>
<P>
	Eli Lilly rose 3 to 67 3/16. The U.S. Food and Drug  
Administration granted the company approval to sell an estrogen 
substitute used to prevent brittle bones in women who are past 
menopause as a treatment for osteoporosis. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 12-to-7 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 686.34 million 
shares, compared with 743.00 million shares on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index fell 5.22 to 422.08.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
