<DOCNO> APW19991001.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 13:30:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Promotes Health Care Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore countered the ambitious  
health care plan unveiled by rival Bill Bradley with a visit Friday 
to a local hospital to meet with doctors and nurses and push his 
own plan to provide health insurance to all children. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore also urged Congress to swiftly pass legislation that would  
increase patients' rights in dealing with managed health care 
systems. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope the partisanship that has delayed passage of this  
measure will subside and that Republicans will join Democrats in 
passing this,'' he said. ``I hope they'll go further and see it's 
time to expand access to health insurance for every child in this 
country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The vice president also took a jab at Texas Gov. George W. Bush,  
the GOP presidential front-runner who on Thursday criticized GOP 
spending proposals, saying they would allow Congress to ``balance 
their budget on the backs of the poor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore said Bush needs to break from the Republican majority on  
other issues, such as the so-called patient's bill of rights and a 
proposed increase in the minimum wage. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore did not provide any new details on his insurance plan, nor  
did he refer to the one offered by Bradley, the former U.S. senator 
who wants universal access to affordable health care. When asked 
about the differences between the two proposals, Gore only promised 
there would be ``plenty of time'' to make point-by-point 
comparisons. 
</P>
<P>
	``Stay tuned,'' he said. ``There will be plenty of opportunity  
for that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore also urged Congress to extend health coverage to uninsured  
adults by ``fixing Medicare and adding prescription drug benefits 
for seniors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If the members of Congress opposing these measures could  
listen to the EMTs, the nurses and the emergency room nurses and 
the doctors and hear what they have to say about the choices that 
their patients are having to make, they'd make different 
decisions,'' Gore said. 
</P>
<P>
	They also would act differently toward the proposed budget, he  
added. 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP budget plan slashes funding for critical health  
programs, Gore said. About 170,000 fewer children would be 
immunized and services for 100,000 mentally ill patients would be 
reduced. The plan also would deny substance abuse assistance to 
31,000 people. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard to resist the conclusion that they are truly headed  
in the wrong direction,'' Gore said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
