<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stars Sign Matvichuk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Hours before opening their Stanley Cup defense  
Friday night, the Dallas Stars signed defenseman Richard Matvichuk 
to a four-year contract and announced they'd given goaltender Ed 
Belfour a two-year extension. 
</P>
<P>
	Matvichuk, who starts alongside captain Derian Hatcher, had been  
holding out for a five-year deal. Dallas refused to go longer than 
three years. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of the holdout, the Stars weren't sure whether to  
include Matvichuk in pregame ceremonies honoring last year's 
champions. They decided to invite him and his acceptance became the 
opening needed to reach an agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hammered out the deal and it's good for both sides,''  
Matvichuk said. ``I'm happy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Matvichuk, 26, stayed in shape while waiting out training camp  
and the exhibition season, but Dallas general manager Bob Gainey 
said he won't play until next week at the soonest. 
</P>
<P>
	Gainey wasn't happy about giving up the fifth year because it  
means Matvichuk and Hatcher will both be free agents after the 
2002-03 season. 
</P>
<P>
	But Gainey said the compromise was worth keeping up the  
excitement surrounding the season opener against Pittsburgh and the 
team's momentum towards repeating. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems the timing was right,'' Gainey said. ``Our wish is to  
keep our players thinking about being a championship team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Belfour has led the Stars to the NHL's best regular-season  
record in his first two years in Dallas. But until last summer he 
had a reputation for not being able to come through when it 
mattered most. 
</P>
<P>
	The Eagle erased that by going 16-7 with three shutouts in the  
playoffs. He won two triple-overtime games, including the 
title-clincher against Buffalo. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars offered the extension before training camp to let him  
know they wanted to keep him off the free-agent market after this 
season. Belfour was glad to stay and he's now locked up through 
2002, when he'll be 38. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel he is physically capable of playing at the same level  
at that age, and we feel we can continue to put a quality team 
around him for the term of his contract,'' Gainey said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gainey said the team also offered a two-year extension to  
Stanley Cup MVP Joe Nieuwendyk, but after several counteroffers by 
both sides everyone agreed to wait until the summer. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
