<HEADLINE> N.D. Governor Not To Run Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) -- Republican Gov. Ed Schafer stunned his  
supporters Friday by announcing he will not run for a third term 
next year, saying it will be time ``to turn the reins over to a new 
leader.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The decision made the Democratic attorney general, Heidi  
Heitkamp, the front-runner for the job. 
</P>
<P>
	``The easy decision would have been to run again,'' Schafer said  
during an emotional news conference at the state Republican 
headquarters. ``The accomplishments are many. The support is 
tremendous. ... However, we feel it is time, a year from now, to 
turn the reins over to a new leader.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schaefer, 53, said it was ``quite possible'' he would return to  
politics -- even the governor's office. 
</P>
<P>
	Schafer's decision boosted the campaign of Ms. Heitkamp, the  
only declared Democratic candidate. She praised Schafer, saying he 
brought ``a great deal of class to the office of governor, whether 
you believed in his programs or not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	North Dakota's economy expanded on Schafer's watch -- helped, he  
said, by his insistence on holding down taxes. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
