<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kellogg To Buy Worthington Foods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Less than a week after unloading its frozen bagel division,  
Kellogg Co. on Friday got into the vegetarian burger business, with 
hopes of broadening its appeal to health conscious consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Battle Creek, Mich.-based cereal maker, which has suffered  
in recent years with sagging sales and profits, agreed to acquire 
Worthington Foods for $307 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Worthington Foods specializes in manufacturing and marketing  
products including veggie burgers and meatless sausage, chicken, 
and hot dog products. Its brand names include Morningstar Farms, 
Natural Touch, Worthington, and Loma Linda. 
</P>
<P>
	Worthington stock surged 60 percent, rising $8.68 3/4 to $23.06 1/4 a  
share in trading Friday on the Nasdaq Stock Market. Kellogg slipped 
31 1/4 cents to $37.12 1/2 a share on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement comes five days after the cereal maker  
announced it was selling its struggling Lender's Bagel business to 
Aurora Foods Inc. for $275 million, 41 percent below the 1996 
purchase price of $466 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their past management bought Lender's, which was yesterday's  
product,'' Prudential Securities analysts John McMillin said. 
``Kellogg's new management is trying to buy tomorrow's products, 
which they believe will be healthier foods.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since he took the helm of the company in April, Kellogg chief  
executive Carlos Gutierrez has stressed the need for the company to 
expand its product line, especially since fewer Americans are 
eating cereal for breakfast. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, he told analysts that Kellogg has the marketing  
expertise to increase the sales of Worthington's existing product 
lines, and perhaps develop new ones. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their research department has a lot of experience working with  
soy ... and we are looking at different products with soy,'' 
Gutierrez said. ``This will give us a bigger head start once soy 
takes off, which we believe is the next big hot food product.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A Worthington representative did not immediately return phone  
calls Friday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Nomi Ghez of Goldman Sachs said this appears to be a competitive  
acquisition, which is an important part of a company's growth. 
</P>
<P>
	``Worthington is in a very strong growth category and one which  
has very low consumer penetration, about 15 percent. It clearly ... 
has strong growth prospects,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Worthington Foods is expected to have sales in excess of $170  
million this year, more than 20 percent above its sales in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Kellogg will pay $24 for each of Worthington's approximately  
12.8 million shares outstanding or approximately $307 million. 
Kellogg expects to complete the transaction by the end of the year, 
and said the purchase should have little effect on its earnings for 
the next year. 
</P>
<P>
	In an attempt to cut costs and turnaround its business, Kellogg  
has gone through significant restructuring recently, including 
slashing jobs and closing its historic Battle Creek cereal plant. 
</P>
<P>
	Worthington employs 650 hourly and salaried people at its  
Worthington, Ohio, headquarters and two plants. The company's 
management team, including its CEO, is expected to stay on at least 
through the transition. 
</P>
<P>
	A Kellogg spokesman said no immediate job cuts are planned.  


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
