<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Approves Farm Aid Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP -- The House today approved an $8.7 billion  
package of farm relief despite complaints that it wasn't enough 
money and didn't deal with disputes over dairy policy and the Cuban 
trade embargo. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill, approved 240-175, offers $7.5 billion for growers hurt  
by a second year of low market prices, including $5.5 billion that 
would be paid to farmers who have ``market transition'' contracts 
with the government. 
</P>
<P>
	The Agriculture Department said those checks could be sent to  
farmers within two weeks after the bill is signed into law by 
President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate is expected to take up the bill next week.  
</P>
<P>
	Also included is $1.2 billion for farmers who lost crops to  
drought and floods. Moving separately through Congress is $500 
million for hurricane-related farm losses in North Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	``Farmers can't wait. They need assistance now,'' said Rep. Joe  
Skeen, R-N.M., chairman of the House Appropriations agricultural 
subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Marcy Kaptur, D-Ohio, tried unsuccessfully to get the House  
to order the bill rewritten. She said much of the money would go to 
well-off farmers and landowners who don't need the help. ``Some of 
these people aren't the ones who are truly hurting in this 
economy,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The farm aid is included in a $69 billion appropriations bill  
for operations of USDA, with its myriad of agriculture and 
nutrition programs, and the Food and Drug Administration. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican leaders forced the measure out of a House-Senate  
conference committee Thursday without provisions that would allow 
sales of food and medicine to Cuba and block the Agriculture 
Department from implementing new dairy-pricing rules. 
</P>
<P>
	The conference committee stopped work on the bill last week  
after GOP leaders refused to let them consider the Cuba provision. 
The leadership then coaxed a majority of the panel's members to 
endorse the bill individually, securing the last two signatures 
Thursday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the committee's approval was a variety of special  
provisions for the lawmakers' home-state farmers: $125 million in 
subsidies for dairy producers, a requirement that meatpackers start 
reporting the prices they pay for cattle and hogs and a guarantee 
that livestock producers would get $200 million in drought aid. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Jack Kingston, R-Ga., said he agreed to the compromise to  
keep Republican leaders from having to make additional concessions 
to Democrats. ``They were all over me to get this out of the 
station,'' he said, referring to the leadership. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is expected to meet some opposition in Senate as well  
as the House. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have people who are upset about what's not in the bill and  
you have people who are upset about what's in,'' said Sen. Pat 
Roberts, R-Kan. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Democrats and Republicans were angry that GOP leaders  
prevented the committee from meeting and voting on the Cuba 
measure, which had passed the Senate, 70-28. 
</P>
<P>
	``The process was manipulated,'' complained Sen. John Ashcroft,  
R-Mo., the amendment's sponsor. 
</P>
<P>
	``Certain elements of the House are more concerned with  
continuing the Cold War than with helping our nation's farmers,'' 
said Jim Dornan, a spokesman for Rep. George Nethercutt, R-Wash. 
``But we will be back to fight this another day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some lawmakers from dairy states in the South and East wanted to  
use the must-pass spending bill to overturn a new nationwide 
milk-pricing system that was scheduled to take effect today. A 
federal judge on Tuesday postponed implementation of the plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Midwestern lawmakers, who support the new pricing system,  
persuaded GOP leaders to keep it out of the legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	The House Appropriations Committee may have eliminated some  
opposition to the bill by agreeing Thursday to put in another 
spending measure $508 million for crop and livestock losses in 
North Carolina due to Hurricane Floyd. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is just a down payment, but it will go a long way to  
meeting the staggering losses our farm families have suffered in 
the flood,'' said Rep. David Price, D-N.C. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
