<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kid Grounded After Sneaking on Plane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) -- A 12-year-old Alexandria boy was grounded  
at home after taking an unauthorized and unticketed flight to St. 
Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	Renee Peregory told WUSA-TV her son, Christopher, was trying to  
see what he could get away with when he sneaked onto a TWA airliner 
at Reagan National Airport Wednesday. He had skipped school and 
taken a Metro train to the airport. 
</P>
<P>
	Eventually, he got as far as St. Louis, then panicked and called  
his mother. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously a 12-year-old child was able to get onto a plane and  
ride off -- without anybody noticing him whatsoever,'' the mother 
said. ``And then getting to the destination and nobody checking to 
see if he's at the right stop.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But TWA spokesman Jim Brown said, ``He did something wrong, he  
did something that was a violation of several statutes, and that 
should be the focus of what occurred here and the ramifications 
afterwards.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The spokesman said the boy hid from the gate agent by walking in  
the shadow of an adult. Then he found an empty seat in the back of 
the plane. 
</P>
<P>
	Christopher spent Wednesday night in a St. Louis juvenile  
detention facility, and was escorted on a return flight Thursday by 
a TWA employee. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Aviation Administration is investigating how he  
could have gotten onto the plane without a ticket or a boarding 
pass. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's been extremely quiet because he's just waiting for the  
other shoe to fall,'' Christopher's mother said. Asked if he was 
ground from flying in the future, she replied, ``He's grounded from 
lots of things actually.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
