<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Consumers To Get Medicine Advice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Can I drink alcohol while taking an  
antidepressant? Can I swallow my heart medicine with grapefruit 
juice? Does my daughter really need to finish this antibiotic when 
it's obvious she's feeling better? 
</P>
<P>
	Taking medication can be complicated.  
</P>
<P>
	First you must know when and how to take prescription and  
over-the-counter drugs. That means more than how many pills a day -- 
it also means knowing what other medicines, foods, even herbs are 
safe with the drugs, what to do about missed doses and how long to 
take them. 
</P>
<P>
	Then you must know what to do if you're among the millions of  
Americans who suffer a drug-caused side effect each year. When is 
it serious enough to seek help? 
</P>
<P>
	For women, dealing with medicine can be even more complex. Women  
typically take more prescription drugs than men. And studies 
suggest moms make more of a family's health decisions, from when to 
call a pediatrician to ensuring a forgetful grandparent doesn't 
miss a dose. 
</P>
<P>
	Citing those studies, the Food and Drug Administration is  
targeting American women with a campaign on using medicine more 
wisely -- hoping to distribute 5 million brochures in October that 
offer what can be lifesaving tips. 
</P>
<P>
	Popping a few prescription pills or teaspoons of a cold remedy  
may not seem risky, but all drugs, even nonprescription ones, cause 
some side effects. 
</P>
<P>
	``Using medicines wisely will help to reduce that risk,'' said  
FDA Commissioner Jane Henney. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 2 million Americans are hospitalized annually from  
drug side effects, and 100,000 die. The vast majority of those 
cases are believed preventable, and the FDA says those illnesses 
cost some $76 billion in health care. 
</P>
<P>
	Some problems are caused when the wrong drug or dose is provided  
to a patient. But consumers bear responsibility, too: About 30 
percent to 50 percent of patients fail to follow instructions from 
their doctor or the drug's label, the FDA says. 
</P>
<P>
	That's where the women's education campaign, co-sponsored by the  
National Association of Chain Drug Stores, comes in. 
</P>
<P>
	The advice, in a free ``My Medicines'' brochure, is pretty  
simple: 
</P>
<P>
	--Read the drug's label. If you or a family member are allergic  
to any ingredients, request a different drug. Read the warnings, 
check the expiration date and don't use expired medicine -- it might 
not work. 
</P>
<P>
	--Keep a record of all your medicines -- prescription,  
over-the-counter, even dietary supplements. 
</P>
<P>
	Why? Many people see numerous doctors. Without a list of what  
each advises taking, patients may be given prescriptions that 
interact dangerously with each other, or accidentally get double 
drugs for the same illness. 
</P>
<P>
	Prescriptions aren't the only worry, said pharmacist Mary Ann  
Wagner of the drugstore association. The herb ginkgo, touted as a 
memory booster, can thin blood, potentially dangerous for people on 
Coumadin or other blood thinners, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	--Ask questions. If you forgot to query the doctor, call back or  
ask the pharmacist, who should be willing to engage in a private 
conversation about a drug's safe use, Wagner said. 
</P>
<P>
	Questions can be vital. A warning that grapefruit juice can  
interact dangerously with certain drugs, or that it's wise to avoid 
alcohol with some others, might be hidden in the label's fine 
print, Wagner said. So ask when to take a drug and with what foods. 
</P>
<P>
	Ask how long to take medicine. People on antibiotics, for  
instance, are supposed to finish them even if they feel better. 
</P>
<P>
	Ask what side effects to expect, and what to do. Patients on  
painkillers, for instance, should know the symptoms of stomach 
ulcers so they can quit the drugs and call a doctor. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even though these are very simple messages, their importance  
cannot be minimized,'' Henney said. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, interviews with women who received the brochures in a  
pilot program last year suggested more had begun keeping medication 
lists, a big step in avoiding drug interactions, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Over 20,000 chain drugstores will distribute the free brochures  
beginning today. They also can be ordered by calling 
1-888-8-PUEBLO, or via the Internet at 
http://www.fda.gov/womens/tttc.html. They will be offered in 
English, Spanish and several other languages. 
</P>
<P>
	----------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Lauran Neergaard covers health and medical  
issues for The Associated Press in Washington. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991001.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 14:01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Candidates Woo Christian Coalition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As Republican presidential candidates showed  
off their conservative credentials Friday, Christian Coalition 
founder Pat Robertson deemed Gary Bauer a ``lost cause,'' Elizabeth 
Dole ``a Southern belle'' and George W. Bush ``worthy of support.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Pat Buchanan, Robertson gave a stern warning that Christian  
conservatives will desert him if he ditches the GOP for a 
third-party presidential run with the Reform Party. 
</P>
<P>
	Reform supporters are ``180 degrees out in terms of social  
issues. They don't share any of the views that Pat Buchanan claimed 
to espouse so vociferously,'' Robertson told a news conference at 
the coalition's annual ``Road to Victory'' conference. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't see him taking many Christian conservatives with him --  
not to the Reform Party,'' Robertson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The two-day conference drew 3,500 of the coalition's 2.1 million  
members and six of the eight Republicans running for president. 
</P>
<P>
	It was Bush, the Texas governor and front-runner for the GOP  
nomination, who filled all the seats -- and lined the perimeter's 
standing room -- in a cavernous hotel ballroom. ``Every child born 
and unborn must be protected by law and welcomed to life,'' he 
declared. 
</P>
<P>
	He advocated parental-notification laws on abortion, saying  
``Parents should be the first to help, not the last to know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robertson, the religious broadcaster who commands the  
grass-roots army of Christian activists that helped sweep 
Republicans into control of Congress in the 1994 elections, said he 
will not endorse any presidential candidate during the primary 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	But his preferences were clear.  
</P>
<P>
	In an interview, Robertson all but dismissed Bauer, whose  
teen-aged supporters in campaign T-shirts worked Friday's 
convention in droves. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's not going to win,'' Robertson told The New York Times.  
``You don't win with 1 or 2 percent. Most people are not terribly 
keen on riding a lost cause.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer, who once ran the Family Research Council and prides  
himself on his Christian conservative appeal, appeared taken aback 
when informed of Robertson's remark. He said he was disappointed 
Robertson was not taking a straw poll of members at this year's 
convention. ``Then we wouldn't have to sit around and speculate on 
where the leaders are,'' Bauer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Robertson said some of what he's heard from Bush's ``centrist''  
campaign ``so far would cause me to believe he would be worthy of 
support of the coalition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Robertson added he is eager to see a series of debates  
force Bush to ``crystallize his positions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his speech, Bauer promised that, unlike Bush, he would make a  
judge's opposition to abortion rights a prerequisite for 
appointment to any federal bench. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, Bauer shouted, ``My judges are going to understand that  
marriage is between a man and a woman -- not two men.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dole took the stage to the rolling crescendos of the music from  
``Gone With the Wind'' and talked of her religious upbringing. She 
called her grandmother's tattered Bible her dearest treasure. 
</P>
<P>
	``My commitment is to strive to lean on the lord with my whole  
heart, reading his word daily and earnestly seeking his will in my 
life,'' Dole said. ``I learned from the best -- President Reagan -- 
that you have to lead with the convictions of your heart, not with 
the latest polling data.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robertson said later that she gave a ``wonderful speech'' and  
enjoys ``real support'' from his members. Asked to explain the 
music organizers chose for her entrance, Robertson boyishly 
shrugged. ``She's the Southern belle, right?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch promised to be a ``conservative president  
with guts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barbara Penberth of Bethlehem, Penn., remained undecided.  
``These 20-minute speeches don't get you anywhere. It's just 
rah-rah,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona Sen. John McCain declined an invitation to speak. And  
though Buchanan appeared on Saturday's program, he canceled earlier 
this week, his campaign said. Alan Keyes was addressing the Friday 
evening session. Steve Forbes issued an open invitation to picnic 
by the pool after his Saturday morning speech. 
</P>
<P>
	From atop a massive, political-convention-styled dais and  
accompanied by the ``Rocky'' fight song, Robertson opened the 
conference with an eye on the 2000 elections and appeal to his 
followers. ``If we aren't in the field in this coming election, 
Republicans will lose,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton was Robertson's primary target. ``As we  
prepare for a new millennium, I want to start with cleansing the 
highest office of the land from the sleaze and the equivocation and 
the moral rot which has embarrassed us all,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Aside from Clinton, the villain in abstentia here was Minnesota  
Gov. Jesse Ventura, who, in a Playboy magazine interview this week, 
called organized religion ``a sham and a crutch for weak-minded 
people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robertson said Ventura was ``off his rocker.'' Bauer suggested  
the former pro-wrestler change his name to ``Jesse 'the Bigot' 
Ventura.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991001.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 14:01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
