grass-roots army of Christian activists that helped sweep 
Republicans into control of Congress in the 1994 elections, said he 
will not endorse any presidential candidate during the primary 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	But his preferences were clear.  
</P>
<P>
	In an interview, Robertson all but dismissed Bauer, whose  
teen-aged supporters in campaign T-shirts worked Friday's 
convention in droves. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's not going to win,'' Robertson told The New York Times.  
``You don't win with 1 or 2 percent. Most people are not terribly 
keen on riding a lost cause.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer, who once ran the Family Research Council and prides  
himself on his Christian conservative appeal, appeared taken aback 
when informed of Robertson's remark. He said he was disappointed 
Robertson was not taking a straw poll of members at this year's 
convention. ``Then we wouldn't have to sit around and speculate on 
where the leaders are,'' Bauer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Robertson said some of what he's heard from Bush's ``centrist''  
campaign ``so far would cause me to believe he would be worthy of 
support of the coalition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Robertson added he is eager to see a series of debates  
force Bush to ``crystallize his positions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his speech, Bauer promised that, unlike Bush, he would make a  
judge's opposition to abortion rights a prerequisite for 
appointment to any federal bench. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, Bauer shouted, ``My judges are going to understand that  
marriage is between a man and a woman -- not two men.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dole took the stage to the rolling crescendos of the music from  
``Gone With the Wind'' and talked of her religious upbringing. She 
called her grandmother's tattered Bible her dearest treasure. 
</P>
<P>
	``My commitment is to strive to lean on the lord with my whole  
heart, reading his word daily and earnestly seeking his will in my 
life,'' Dole said. ``I learned from the best -- President Reagan -- 
that you have to lead with the convictions of your heart, not with 
the latest polling data.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robertson said later that she gave a ``wonderful speech'' and  
enjoys ``real support'' from his members. Asked to explain the 
music organizers chose for her entrance, Robertson boyishly 
shrugged. ``She's the Southern belle, right?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch promised to be a ``conservative president  
with guts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barbara Penberth of Bethlehem, Penn., remained undecided.  
``These 20-minute speeches don't get you anywhere. It's just 
rah-rah,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona Sen. John McCain declined an invitation to speak. And  
though Buchanan appeared on Saturday's program, he canceled earlier 
this week, his campaign said. Alan Keyes was addressing the Friday 
evening session. Steve Forbes issued an open invitation to picnic 
by the pool after his Saturday morning speech. 
</P>
<P>
	From atop a massive, political-convention-styled dais and  
accompanied by the ``Rocky'' fight song, Robertson opened the 
conference with an eye on the 2000 elections and appeal to his 
followers. ``If we aren't in the field in this coming election, 
Republicans will lose,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton was Robertson's primary target. ``As we  
prepare for a new millennium, I want to start with cleansing the 
highest office of the land from the sleaze and the equivocation and 
the moral rot which has embarrassed us all,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Aside from Clinton, the villain in abstentia here was Minnesota  
Gov. Jesse Ventura, who, in a Playboy magazine interview this week, 
called organized religion ``a sham and a crutch for weak-minded 
people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robertson said Ventura was ``off his rocker.'' Bauer suggested  
the former pro-wrestler change his name to ``Jesse 'the Bigot' 
Ventura.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
