<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar Lower; gold Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar fell against most other major  
currencies in European trading today. Gold prices rose. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0705 in late European trading, up from  
$1.0648 Thursday. Later, in midday trading in New York, the euro 
traded at $1.0706. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday,  
included 105.02 Japanese yen, down from 106.44; 1.4898 Swiss 
francs, down from 1.5008; 1.4690 Canadian dollars, unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.6558, up from $1.6462.  
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth 1.8270 German marks, down from 1.8368; 
6.1293 French francs, down from 6.1621; 2.0593 Dutch guilders, down 
from 2.0702; 1,805.92 Italian lire, down from 1,818.95. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $303.00 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$300.50 on Thursday. In Zurich the bid price was $305.00, up from 
$298.20. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial markets in Hong Kong were closed Friday due to a  
public holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.60 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$5.58. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
