<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Oct. 1, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Ventura Urged To Leave Reform Party  
</P>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- Reform Party chairman Russell Verney  
demanded today that Gov. Jesse Ventura resign from the party, 
saying the former wrestler ``brought shame'' to himself with a 
bombastic interview in Playboy magazine. Verney's letter to the 
Minnesota governor reflects rising bitterness inside the Reform 
Party as its fractious members seek a 2000 presidential nominee. 
The governor, whose frank talk got him elected in a November upset, 
told Playboy that organized religion ``is a sham,'' the Navy 
Tailhook scandal was ``much ado about nothing'' and fat people 
``can't push away from the table.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Lifts Nuclear Plant Advisory  
</P>
<P>
	TOKAIMURA, Japan (AP) -- Recovering from its worst nuclear  
accident ever, the Japanese government on Friday lifted an advisory 
that had urged residents near a hobbled uranium reprocessing plant 
to stay home and shut their windows. But even as officials at the 
plant northeast of Tokyo said danger from radiation released 
Thursday was subsiding, fears persisted that people near the 
Tokaimura facility may suffer long-term effects from the accident. 
Police began investigating whether criminal negligence was 
involved. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia Renounces Chechen Parliament  
</P>
<P>
	GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- The Russian government announced Friday it  
no longer recognizes the democratically elected parliament of 
Chechnya, a sign that Moscow is seeking allies to possibly reassert 
power in the breakaway republic. Meantime, Russian jets continued 
to bomb targets across Chechnya, raids that have sent more than 
88,000 civilians fleeing to neighboring regions that have little 
capacity to care for them. It was not clear if the advance of 
Russian troops inside Chechnya was a limited move or the precursor 
to a full invasion. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Unveils Computer Center  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Ending a long-standing conflict over the illegal  
sale of high-performance IBM computers to Russia, visiting U.S. 
Energy Secretary Bill Richardson on Friday inaugurated a civilian 
computer center that would use them. The computer center is 
intended to help Russian researchers find civilian jobs as Sarov, a 
city that is home to a major nuclear research laboratory and 
nuclear weapons production center, converts from weapons research 
to peaceful work. 

</P>
<P>
	Thailand Negotiates With Hostage-Takers  
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- A self-described 29-year-old student  
said he and the other armed Myanmar dissidents who took over their 
country's embassy would ``have to do something'' -- which could 
include killing hostages -- if a helicopter was not provided for 
them. Thai authorities continued to negotiate with the dissidents, 
who seized about 30 hostages, including some foreigners. The 
dissidents seek the release of political prisoners, a dialogue 
between Myanmar's pro-democracy leader Aung San Suu Kyi and the 
military, and the convening of an elected parliament. 

</P>
<P>
	HUD Awards Vouchers to Working Poor  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Putting dollars behind the effort to guide  
welfare recipients to employment, the government awarded $280 
million in vouchers designed to help about 50,000 families across 
the country. This initial distribution of the welfare-to-work 
vouchers by the Department of Housing and Urban Development will 
subsidize rents of low-income families receiving welfare or 
recently off welfare to enable them to rent apartments near 
available jobs, child care and transportation. 

</P>
<P>
	Fishing War Brews in Canada  
</P>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- A Canadian Supreme Court court ruling giving  
Indians the right to unlicensed fishing year-around has drawn 
protests from some commercial fishermen, who claim the decision 
puts their jobs at risk. Atlantic lobstermen say they can now stand 
on shore and watch Micmac Indians harvest tons of lobster two 
months before the legal season starts. Some natives have reported 
being shot at, but so far there has been no outbreak of major 
violence. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Slips 63.95 to 10,273  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks resumed their slide today after new  
reports showed that the economy's surging growth has not slowed in 
recent months. The data renewed concerns that the Federal Reserve 
will raise interest rates next week. The Dow industrials closed 
down 63.95 at 10,273.00 and the Nasdaq composite index fell 9.31 to 
2,736.85. 

</P>
<P>
	Rockets To Trade Pippen to Portland  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In a six-for-one deal, Scottie Pippen will be  
traded tomorrow from the Houston Rockets to the Portland Trail 
Blazers, The Associated Press has learned. The deal will send the 
disgruntled Pippen to Portland for Kelvin Cato, Stacey Augmon, Walt 
Williams, Ed Gray, Brian Shaw and Carlos Rogers. It's a mixed 
blessing for Pippen, who wanted out of Houston but would have 
preferred to go to the Lakers so he could be reunited with Phil 
Jackson, his coach in Chicago when Pippen and the Bulls won six 
championships. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRAD FOSS  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
