<HEADLINE> Brush Fire Threatens Calif. Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CORONA, Calif. (AP) -- Firefighters scrambled to contain a  
fast-moving brush fire that swept across 250 acres and forced 
authorities to order 200 families out of their homes. 
</P>
<P>
	One home was destroyed Thursday as the blaze scorched brush and  
citrus groves within a half-mile of Corona. At least two other 
homes were damaged in the area 40 miles east of Los Angeles, 
Riverside County spokeswoman Becky Luther said. 
</P>
<P>
	Evacuation centers were opened at Corona High School and Raine  
Intermediate School. As the blaze raced down hillsides from the 
Cleveland National Forest and into back yards, residents watched 
helplessly. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's scary when you're in the bedroom and you're looking out  
the window and all you see are flames,'' said Peter Fischetti. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the scariest feeling in my life,'' added Elizabeth  
Arroyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Air tankers and helicopters were dropping fire retardant and  
water, but officials couldn't say when the fire might be contained. 
</P>
<P>
	Two brush fires also burned in San Diego County, and the  
region's largest blaze, just south of the Mexico border, forced 
about 70 families to evacuate a remote area near Tecate. 
</P>
<P>
	Calmer winds and cooler temperatures gave firefighters an edge  
against blazes in Northern California, but the stable air also made 
it difficult for them to breathe since the smoke wasn't dissipating 
quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	A fire in the Sierra foothills doubled in size to 31,300 acres  
Thursday, forcing the evacuation of about 50 homes scattered in the 
canyons, said Karen Terrill, spokeswoman for the California 
Department of Forestry and Fire Protection. 
</P>
<P>
	Lightning-sparked fires also burned in the Trinity Alps  
Wilderness and the Los Padres National Forest near Big Sur. 
Firefighters near Big Sur used mules to bring in supplies in the 
steep terrain. 
</P>
<P>
	In Oregon, firefighters were battling at least five wildfires,  
including a controlled burn in a farm field that blew into a 
5,000-acre wildfire on the Warm Springs Indian Reservation. 
</P>
<P>
	Fires also burned on the slopes of Mount Emily in Oregon's  
Siskiyou National Forest and along the Oregon Coast Range. 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of wildfires have scorched more than 115,000 acres in  
California and Oregon in the past month. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
