<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Revlon Stock Plunges on Makeover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Plans for a relatively minor makeover at Revlon  
Inc. were anything but attractive to investors Friday and the 
company's stock lost more than a third of its value. 
</P>
<P>
	Revlon, one of the best-known names in makeup and consumer  
products, disclosed it is getting out of the business of selling 
products through beauty salons and shedding some Latin American 
brands after billionaire Ronald O. Perelman failed to find a buyer 
for the company. 
</P>
<P>
	Revlon also surprised Wall Street with word that it would post a  
loss for this year, and have to restructure its $1.8 billion debt. 
</P>
<P>
	Disappointed investors sent Revlon's shares tumbling 34 percent,  
or by $6.25, to $12 on the New York Stock Exchange. Revlon's shares 
had traded as high as $30.25 in June. 
</P>
<P>
	Revlon, which makes Revlon and Almay makeup, Flex shampoo and  
Charlie perfume, has been struggling to pay its debts while sales 
of its lipsticks and eyeshadows are facing new competition. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you get by this short-term bitter pill -- and it's a big one  
-- this really speaks to a strong 2000,'' said George Fellows, 
Revlon's president and chief executive. 
</P>
<P>
	Perelman put Revlon on the auction block in April, and peddled  
the company to several rivals, including the Dutch fragrance 
company Coty Inc., but couldn't get the price he wanted. 
</P>
<P>
	``The conversations we had with a number of people didn't get to  
values we thought were appropriate,'' Fellows said. 
</P>
<P>
	New York-based Revlon is currently negotiating to sell its salon  
products business, which includes the American Crew and Creative 
Nails brands. Revlon also will sell some of its Latin American hair 
care brands, including the Colorama, Juvena, and Plusbelle names. 
</P>
<P>
	Together, the two businesses account for 20 percent of Revlon's  
$2.2 billion in annual sales. 
</P>
<P>
	The market for salon products ``is consolidating quickly and  
they really don't belong in it anymore. It isn't integral to their 
company, and the dollars are better spent elsewhere,'' said Allan 
Mottus, editor of The Informationist, an industry trade 
publication. 
</P>
<P>
	Revlon expects to sell the businesses for a total of $500  
million, and use the money to pay down debt, much of it borrowed 
when Perelman bought the company in 1985 for $1.83 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Revlon, which uses model Cindy Crawford to promote its new  
shades, is fighting to protect its market from Johnson &AMP; Johnson's 
new Neutrogena line of makeup and Procter &AMP; Gamble's new Oil of 
Olay makeup. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, companies like Gap and Victoria's Secrets have  
started selling their own makeup and body care lines. 
</P>
<P>
	Revlon tried to pump up sales by flooding drugstore shelves with  
promotional products. But retailers got stuck with inventories of 
older products, and didn't put new items in the cosmetics counters 
fast enough, so they often missed the advertising campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	To solve this problem, Revlon said it will cut product shipments  
$280 million through December. 
</P>
<P>
	The inventory problem has been ``an albatross we've been  
carrying around for a year now,'' said Fellows, adding he wished he 
had done this earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the cut in shipments coupled with worsening economic  
conditions in Brazil, South Africa and other overseas markets will 
lead to an operating loss of $70 million to $80 million for the 
year before additional charges for its restructuring. 
</P>
<P>
	In the third quarter alone, Revlon expects a net loss before  
restructuring charges of $3.10 to $3.20 a share. Wall Street had 
expected the New York-based company to earn 45 cents a share in the 
third quarter and 72 cents for the full year. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
