<HEADLINE> US Airways Has Quieter Shuttle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- People who live near LaGuardia and Reagan  
National airports had their first chance Friday to hear a new 
airplane that will replace noisier US Airways jets shuttling 
between New York and Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	The 9 a.m. shuttle between Washington and New York, as well as  
the 11 a.m. return trip, were flown on one of US Airways' new 
Airbus A-320s. 
</P>
<P>
	Thanks to their high-bypass jet engines, the twin-engine planes  
leave noise footprints 10 times smaller than the route's current 
Boeing 727s at National and 17 times smaller on approaches or 
takeoffs at LaGuardia. 
</P>
<P>
	In each location, residents have long complained about aircraft  
noise. The switch for US Airways is particularly important because 
the airline makes hourly flights back and forth between the 
airports. 
</P>
<P>
	US Airways also operates hourly shuttle service between  
LaGuardia and Boston's Logan International Airport. That route will 
begin receiving A-320s on Nov. 1, and Airbus airplanes will account 
for about three-quarters of the shuttle fleet by the end of the 
year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
