<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Magazine Names Best Destinations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Some are popular vacation spots, some can be  
reached only through a long and costly trek. One has been visited 
by only a few people and one can be enjoyed without leaving the 
desk. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years in the making, National Geographic Traveler magazine  
has selected the 50 ``places of a lifetime -- the must-see spots for 
the complete traveler.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We are celebrating these places as the century turns, the  
places you should visit in your lifetime if you are a real 
traveler,'' said Keith Bellows, editor of the travel magazine 
published by the National Geographic Society. 
</P>
<P>
	These places, Bellows said, ``capture the spirit and diversity  
of our world ... each of them marks you indelibly when you 
experience it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 50 winners -- plus one bonus destination -- were picked from  
more than 500 nominations by National Geographic writers and 
editors along with outside advisers. 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps the easiest to reach spot on the list, placed in the  
``world wonders'' category, is ``cyberspace ... a destination 
unlike any visited by humans before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Directions of how to get there and what to do once you arrive  
change with each person you ask. Attempting to map cyberspace is 
impossible because it is an unchartable land that exists in the 
ether, that halfway point between your computer and my computer,'' 
Traveler reports. 
</P>
<P>
	At the other end of the most-visited scale is the 51st, or bonus  
location, space. 
</P>
<P>
	``My pockets filled with a picnic lunch, I float more than 150  
miles above the Earth and I look out of the spacecraft's windows; 
they are filled with Earth, heavenly Earth. She beckons and I 
follow,'' recalled astronaut Story Musgrave, one of the few to have 
ventured to this destination. 
</P>
<P>
	Each of the 51 special locations is described in an essay by a  
guest writer, including former U. N. Secretary General Boutros 
Boutros-Ghali, Virgin Airlines founder Richard Branson, Sen. Edward 
Kennedy, actor Hugh Grant, Playboy founder Hugh Hefner, singer 
Eartha Kitt and actor-comedian Robin Williams, among others. 
</P>
<P>
	Probably the best-known and most widely visited locations on the  
list are found in the category Urban Spaces -- the cities that offer 
visitors history, entertainment and culture. Included are 
Barcelona, Hong Kong, Istanbul, Jerusalem, London, New York, Paris, 
Rio de Janeiro, San Francisco and Venice. 
</P>
<P>
	Wild places, the ``last bastions of Eden,'' involve more exotic  
travel but also attract many visitors. They include Africa's 
Serengeti plain, ``a vast natural ecosystem where great herds of 
wildlife have annual migrations.'' Others in this category include 
the coral reefs of Papua New Guinea, Australia's vast outback and 
Antarctica. 
</P>
<P>
	Also exotic but less wild is the category Paradise Found -- the  
lovely islands of the Pacific Ocean, the Boundary Waters along 
Minnesota's border with Canada and the Torres del Paine National 
Park in southern Chile, among others. 
</P>
<P>
	The great outdoors in the Country Unbound category includes such  
spots as England's Lake District, California's Big Sur, the Alps 
and Coastal Norway. 
</P>
<P>
	And World Wonders features such grand locations as The Great  
Wall of China, the Taj Mahal, the Pyramids, Vatican City and 
cyberspace. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991001.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 03:20:17 </DATE_TIME>
