<HEADLINE> Illnesses Said Linked to Restaurant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ELLENSBURG, Wash. (AP) -- More than 40 people became sick this  
week after eating at a Jack in the Box restaurant in this central 
Washington community, health officials said. One woman was 
hospitalized. 
</P>
<P>
	The illnesses did not appear to be linked to hepatitis or a  
strain of E. coli bacteria blamed for a 1993 outbreak that sickened 
hundreds of people and killed four, said Dr. James Gale, the 
Kittitas County health officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Health officials said they believe an employee who became ill  
during his shift on Monday may be the source of the illnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Since Tuesday, 45 cases of people with mild to moderate  
gastroenteritis have been confirmed, said Dr. Kiet Ly, an assistant 
county health officer. All but two had eaten at the restaurant 
Monday, Ly said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The only person admitted to the hospital was an elderly woman  
with pre-existing health problems who became dehydrated after 
suffering diarrhea, Ly said. Her illness was not considered 
life-threatening. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1993, an outbreak of E. coli O157:H7 was linked to tainted  
hamburger meat distributed to Jack in the Box outlets in Washington 
and other Western states. 
</P>
<P>
	Kathleen Finn, a spokeswoman for San Diego-based Foodmaker Inc.,  
Jack in the Box's corporate owner, said the Ellensburg restaurant 
would remain closed until an investigation is complete. 
</P>
<P>
	An inspection of the restaurant turned up no violations of  
health regulations, Ly said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
