<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Democrats Back Test Ban Vote Delay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An offer by Senate Republican leaders to force  
a vote on a long-languishing nuclear test-ban treaty won 
conditional Democratic support today. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Democratic leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota told  
reporters he was attempting to negotiate a week's delay with 
Majority Leader Trent Lott and to buy more time for debate in an 
effort to win ratification. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration and Senate Democrats have made the  
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty a top priority and were caught by 
surprise Thursday by a Republican move to schedule a vote next 
week. Republicans say they have the votes to kill the 152-nation 
agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats have long pushed for action on the treaty, but until  
this week GOP leaders had blocked action, bottling it up in the 
Senate Foreign Relations Committee for two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott announced that he was prepared to call up the treaty Oct. 6  
and vote on it after 10 hours of debate, bypassing any hearings. 
</P>
<P>
	Daschle objected to the move Thursday and today made a  
counteroffer: a final vote Oct. 12, after 14 hours of debate. 
</P>
<P>
	Furthermore, Daschle suggested that hearings might be held by  
the Senate Armed Services and Intelligence committees, since 
Foreign Relations, chaired by Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., refuses to 
take it up. 
</P>
<P>
	Daschle said he still resented Lott's efforts to force a vote  
with no, or limited, hearings. But he said the treaty is so 
important that Democrats couldn't afford to turn their backs on the 
offer for a vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican aides said Lott is expected to go along with the  
week's delay, at the very least. 
</P>
<P>
	And Daschle hinted that Democrats want to see a vote on the  
treaty even if not entirely on their terms. As to whether he could 
marshal the 67 votes needed for ratification, Daschle said, ``I 
don't know at this point.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier today, a State Department official told reporters the  
administration needs ample time to make its case for the treaty. 
John Holum, the administration's top arms-control official, said he 
believes the votes could be mustered given enough time. 
</P>
<P>
	He spoke before the Democratic efforts to delay the vote for  
just one week were announced. 
</P>
<P>
	Holum said the treaty was of vital importance because, once it  
takes effect, it will be ``very difficult for new countries to 
develop nuclear weapons.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The prospect of a vote next week prompted Defense Secretary  
William Cohen to decide today to cut short by one day his Asian 
trip so he can return to Washington and take part in the 
discussions. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott's offer to bring up the long languishing treat divided  
Democratic ranks, with some treaty backers urging Daschle to accept 
the offer even if the administration lacked the apparent votes to 
prevail. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bring it up next week,'' said Sen. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., a  
leading test ban activist. He said the offer was ``all right with 
me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Daryl Kimball, director of the Coalition to Reduce Nuclear  
Dangers, a pro-treaty advocacy group, called Lott's offer 
disingenuous. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a rush to judgment,'' he said. ``The Senate needs to  
hold fair hearings, have thorough debate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Helms taunted apprehensive Democrats. ``The same people  
clamoring for action go running to the hills,'' he said. ``If it 
were not so pitiful, this behavior would be amusing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The treaty, which calls for an outright ban on nuclear testing,  
has been signed by 152 nations, including the United States. But it 
has only been ratified by 47 countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Bulgaria and South Korea ratified the treaty just this week.  
</P>
<P>
	If all 45 Democrats support the treaty, as is expected, 22  
Republicans must vote ``yes'' for it to be ratified. 
</P>
<P>
	Lack of support for the pact clearly figured into the GOP change  
of strategy. Republican opponents of the pact said they were 
confident they would prevail. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Joseph Biden of Delaware, senior Democrat on the Senate  
Foreign Relations Committee, said he was optimistic Daschle could 
negotiate more than 10 hours. 
</P>
<P>
	But if not, Biden suggested it was time to move ahead. ``I'm  
ready to roll the dice,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Biden said Democrats appear to be about 15 votes short. He  
suggested that 45 Democrats and seven Republicans currently support 
the treaty. But, he said, senators still ought to be forced to go 
on the record. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want people to pay a political price'' for voting against a  
treaty that has wide support around the world, Biden said. 
</P>
<P>
	Conservatives contend the pact -- which also has not been  
ratified yet by Russia or China -- could threaten the U.S. ability 
to modernize its arsenal if necessary. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters argue the United States already has a vast  
superiority in nuclear weapons, thanks to more than 1,000 nuclear 
tests during the Cold War, and the test ban treaty would lock in 
that advantage. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
