<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Spending Rising Faster Than Income </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans' personal income rose in August but  
their spending climbed much faster, leaving the nation's savings 
rate matching a record low. 
</P>
<P>
	Personal income -- which includes wages, interest and government  
benefits -- rose 0.5 percent in August, the eighth straight monthly 
increase, the Commerce Department said today. The increase was a 
little faster than the 0.4 percent gain forecast by many analysts 
and followed a 0.2 percent increase in July. 
</P>
<P>
	But spending went up 0.9 percent in August, more than many  
analysts had expected. That was the biggest increase since 
February, when spending grew by the same amount. Many analysts were 
forecasting a 0.7 percent increase in August. It rose 0.4 percent 
in July. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate, closely watched report today, the National  
Association of Purchasing Management said the nation's 
manufacturing sector grew in September for the eighth consecutive 
month, while prices of raw materials spurted to the highest level 
since May 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	The stronger-than-expected manufacturing performance was viewed  
as additional evidence of strong third-quarter economic growth 
after a lackluster second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	In another report, the Commerce Department said today that  
construction spending fell an unexpected 0.4 percent in August to a 
seasonally adjusted annual rate of $692 billion, a sign that one of 
the economy's strongest sectors is beginning to slow. In July, 
construction spending declined 0.6 percent. Many analysts were 
forecasting a 0.6 percent rise in August. 
</P>
<P>
	Spending on all private construction projects was down 1.1  
percent with decreases reported for single-family homes, hotels and 
motels and industrial projects, although spending on office 
buildings was up. Spending on big government projects, however, 
rose 2.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Reserve, seeking to slow the economy and keep  
inflation at bay, bumped up interest rates twice this summer, 
making borrowing more expensive. Fed policy-makers meet again on 
Tuesday and many economists doubt another rate increase is in the 
offing, although some say it is a close call. 
</P>
<P>
	Continued uncertainty about interest rates apparently was  
hurting stocks today. The Dow Jones average of 30 blue-chip 
industrial stocks lost more than 100 points in early trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Because consumer spending has repeatedly outpaced incomes, the  
nation's savings rate -- savings as a percentage of after-tax income 
-- has set a string of record lows this year. 
</P>
<P>
	And in August, the savings rates was minus 1.5 percent, matching  
the record low set in May. 
</P>
<P>
	A major reason for the negative savings rate, economists say, is  
that the stock market is boosting Americans' net worth and making 
them more comfortable about dipping into savings to pay for their 
spending sprees. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's personal income and spending report also said wages rose  
0.6 percent in August, following a 0.7 percent gain in July. But 
farm proprietors' income fell 8.8 percent in August, reflecting the 
pattern of disaster relief subsidy payments to farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	In June, a big increase in those subsidy payments caused farm  
proprietors' income to surge, boosting overall personal income. In 
July, those payments decrease, causing farm proprietors' income to 
fall sharply and slow overall income growth. 
</P>
<P>
	Spending on durable goods -- big-ticket manufactured items  
expected to last at least three years, such as washing machines and 
cars -- rose 2.6 percent in August, compared with a decline of 0.7 
percent in July. 
</P>
<P>
	For nondurable goods, such as food and fuel, spending went up by  
0.8 percent, more than the 0.3 percent gain the month before. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, the government reported that the nation's economic  
growth slowed to an annual rate of 1.6 percent in the second 
quarter, the smallest gain in four years. However, many private 
economists believe that was only a temporary lull and are expecting 
growth in the existing third quarter to be considerably higher. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer spending in the second quarter rose at an annual rate  
of 4.8 percent. That was brisker than previously estimated but 
slower than the torrid 6.7 percent rate of spending in the first 
quarter. Consumer spending accounts for two-thirds of total 
economic activity. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
