<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Plane Anti-Collision System Delayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A new system designed to prevent runway  
collisions has been delayed two more years because of problems, 
according to a published report. 
</P>
<P>
	The Airport Movement Area Safety System, a $90 million project  
being designed by Northrop Grumman Corp., originally was to have 
been put into the field in the mid-1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	A revised schedule specified deployment next August. Now the  
Federal Aviation Administration says ``human factors and software 
development problems'' will delay launch until September 2002 at a 
yet-to-be-determined cost, according to a report in next Monday's 
Aviation Week &AMP; Space Technology. 
</P>
<P>
	A runway collision led to the single deadliest airline accident,  
the 1977 collision of two Boeing 747s in the Canary Islands that 
killed 538 people. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, there 292 so-called runway incursions, when an aircraft  
comes too close to a vehicle or object on the ground. The FAA's 
goal has been to reduce them 15 percent per year. Instead, 
incursions rose in 1998 by 11.3 percent to 325. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
