<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Backs Off Benefit Slowdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republican leaders backed away Friday  
from their plan to slow income-support payments to working poor 
people as a backlash to the idea grew within their own party. 
</P>
<P>
	Though not yet jettisoning the proposal, lawmakers and aides  
acknowledged they were looking for other ways to raise the $8.7 
billion that they had expected the plan to save in the budget for 
fiscal 2000, which began Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. John McCain joined George W. Bush as the second Republican  
presidential contender criticizing the idea. And House GOP 
moderates and Senate Republicans predicted the plan's demise. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to knee-jerk anything right now,'' House Speaker  
Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., said after a meeting with rank-and-file 
lawmakers. ``We need to assess, to see where we're at.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both Hastert and House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas,  
said, ``I don't know,'' when asked if there were enough votes to 
push the plan through the House. The GOP's margin in the chamber is 
so slight that five defecting Republicans can kill one of the 
party's initiatives. 
</P>
<P>
	For many Republicans, the worry was that the proposal had become  
a political distraction from the party's high-profile goal of 
protecting Social Security surpluses and would be used against them 
by Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	``It positions us in a way that is not desirable, that will be  
used to portray the party as insensitive and uncaring,'' said Rep. 
Sherwood Boehlert, R-N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	The decisive blow seemed to have been dealt Thursday by Bush,  
the party's leading presidential contender, when he said 
Republicans shouldn't ``balance their budget on the backs of the 
poor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Unless he says, 'I had this all wrong,' then I think it's dead  
on arrival,'' said Rep. James Greenwood, R-Pa. 
</P>
<P>
	Hastert said that the plan had been described to the campaigns  
of Bush and other GOP candidates before it was introduced, and that 
congressional Republicans got no response. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would hope that we'd have a future dialogue on these kind of  
issues,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal, approved Thursday by the House Appropriations  
Committee, would convert into 12 monthly payments the lump-sum 
payment almost all 20 million recipients of the earned-income tax 
credit now get. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters said each beneficiary would receive the same amount  
of money as now. Opponents said the change would deny recipients 
the big cash infusion many now use to buy expensive items. 
</P>
<P>
	``What they propose to do is unconscionable,'' Clinton said  
Friday, reiterating his promise to kill the plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Some lawmakers and aides said the proposal might gain public  
acceptance -- and House votes -- if they did a better job of selling 
it. They said they had to emphasize that benefits from Social 
Security and many other income-support programs are already paid 
monthly. 
</P>
<P>
	Emerging from his meeting with Republicans, Hastert said, ``You  
just can't duck your head and run every time there's a shot 
fired.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Underlining the GOP's disarray, House Majority Whip Tom DeLay,  
R-Texas, the plan's sponsor, said of Republicans at the same 
meeting, ``I didn't think they understood it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the Senate, where Republicans have been critical of the idea  
since it first surfaced last month, Majority Leader Trent Lott said 
he viewed the proposal as temporary in the House GOP's search for 
savings to pay for spending bills. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the end, I think the House and Senate will find other ways  
to proceed with the problem, and we'll decide not to do that,'' 
Lott, R-Miss., told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, McCain, R-Ariz., told The Associated Press that  
Republicans should instead cut ``pork and wasteful spending'' from 
bills. 
</P>
<P>
	``If our goal is to have lower-income Americans lifted up into  
the middle class, this is the wrong way to do it,'' said McCain. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers and aides said other savings options Republicans were  
exploring included making their plan to switch from lump-sum to 
monthly payments optional, and cutting spending bills across the 
board. 
</P>
<P>
	Currently, most of the money under the $30 billion  
income-support program is paid early in the year, when 
beneficiaries file income-tax returns. Under the plan, the payments 
would be spread out so that $8.7 billion would be paid after Sept. 
30, 2000 -- spilling into fiscal 2001, and out of the books for 
2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The 24-year-old program is designed to supplement the earnings  
of workers who earn between $10,000 and $31,000 and owe little or 
no income taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile Friday, the House approved two more compromise  
spending bills for the new fiscal year, readying them for Senate 
action and Clinton's expected signature. 
</P>
<P>
	A $69 billion agriculture bill was passed 240-175, and a $51  
billion transportation measure was approved 304-91. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
