<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Soccer League Bans Cheering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- No parents cheering. No coaches barking orders.  
</P>
<P>
	The soccer fields of the Northern Ohio Girls Soccer League will  
sound like a monastic retreat. 
</P>
<P>
	Fed up with screaming, know-it-all coaches and parents, the  
league has banned cheering for this weekend's games, a plan dubbed 
``Silent Sunday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We want kids to be able to learn and to be able to think and  
play without the constant yelling,'' league president Al Soper 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials with the league for 3,800 girls ages 8 to 14 had  
previously discussed a possible noise ban. But Soper decided to 
silence the crowds after refereeing a boys' soccer tournament 
earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted earplugs,'' he said. ``The crowd was so loud, kids  
couldn't hear the whistle, talk to each other, develop combinations 
or anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some national organizations have adopted guidelines and programs  
to restrain bad parental behavior at athletic events, but Fred 
Engh, president of the National Alliance for Youth Sports, said the 
cheering ban was the first of its kind that he was aware of in any 
sport. 
</P>
<P>
	Engh's organization recently created the Parents Association for  
Youth Sports, a training program with a code of ethics that 
instructs parents to ``remember that the game is for youth -- not 
for adults.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Engh thinks a silent Sunday is a great idea.  
</P>
<P>
	``Parents have lost perspective of what youth sports are all  
about,'' he said. ``This is a wake-up call, a giant timeout for 
adults.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As recently as Monday the father of a high school soccer player  
was charged with punching one of his son's opponents during a high 
school game in suburban Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	Soper said that after his league announced the plan for silence  
earlier this month, several smaller leagues tested the concept at 
some of their games with success -- measured in subdued crowds and 
happy players. 
</P>
<P>
	Although parents and coaches in the Northern Ohio Girls League  
won't be given a red card for cheering, Soper hopes the stands will 
be completely silent when players take the field. 
</P>
<P>
	One of those players is 13-year-old Joceyln Predina, who said  
the quiet crowds will be a nice change. She said she doesn't like 
it when abuse is hurled at referees. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it will be better on Sunday,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	Joceyln isn't too worried about losing out on accolades if she  
makes a big play. 
</P>
<P>
	``It might be weird if people aren't saying anything,'' she  
said. ``It's nice to hear cheering. But sometimes the crowd just 
takes it too far.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Carl Pavlovich, a coach, referee and member of the league's  
board of directors, said some coaches and parents were skeptical 
when the league first announced the ban. 
</P>
<P>
	``But every single player I've talked to is thrilled with the  
idea,'' Pavlovich said. 
</P>
<P>
	Going noise-free for an entire season is unlikely, officials  
say. But if Sunday goes according to plan, the league will consider 
having another silent day in spring. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is for the kids,'' Soper said. ``If the parents and  
coaches weren't there, and we threw a ball onto the field, the kids 
would still want to play.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
