<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls, Gold Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar fell today against most other  
major currencies in European trading. Gold prices rose. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0734, up from $1.0648 Thursday.  
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates compared with late Thursday included 105.81  
Japanese yen, down from 106.44; 1.4885 Swiss francs, down from 
1.5008, and 1.4650 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4690. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.6486, up from $1.6462.  
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth 1.8221 German marks, down from 1.8368; 
6.1110 French francs, down from 6.1621; 2.0530 Dutch guilders, down 
from 2.0702, and 1,803.87 Italian lire, down from 1,818.95. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold dealers in London fixed a recommended price of $303.00 per  
troy ounce at midmorning, up from $300.50 on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Zurich the bid price was $302.50, up from $298.20.  
</P>
<P>
	Financial markets in Hong Kong were closed due to a public  
holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver opened in London at $5.61 per troy ounce, up from $5.58.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
