<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Named to U.S. Hockey Hall of Fame </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Former NHL defensemen Rod Langway and Gordie  
Roberts and former college coach Sid Watson are the 1999 inductees 
for the U.S. Hockey Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	Langway, who played four years with the Montreal Canadiens and  
11 years with the Washington Capitals, won the Norris Trophy as the 
NHL's most outstanding defenseman in the 1982-83 and 1983-84 
seasons. He was a member of the 1978-79 Stanley Cup champion 
Canadiens. Langway was chosen to the NHL All-Star First Team in 
1983 and 1984 and captained Team USA at the 1981, 1984 and 1987 
Canada Cup tournaments. 
</P>
<P>
	Roberts played 15 years in the NHL. He was the first U.S.-born  
player to play 1,000 games, scoring 420 points during his career. 
Roberts played on Stanley Cup champion teams with Pittsburgh in 
1991 and 1992. He appeared in 153 playoff games and scored 57 
postseason points. 
</P>
<P>
	Watson coached Bowdoin College for more than two decades,  
winning four Eastern Collegiate Athletic Conference championships. 
His teams compiled a record of 326-210-11. He was the national 
small college coach of the year in 1970, 1971 and 1978. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
