<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Oct. 1, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Russia Steps Up Chechnya Bombing  
</P>
<P>
	GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- Russia pressed ahead today with a bombing  
campaign against Chechnya, and an official warned the exodus of 
refugees from the breakaway southern territory could soon reach 
100,000. The military situation around Chechnya's volatile borders 
remained murky. Russian political leaders said yesterday that 
government troops had taken strategic heights several miles inside 
Chechnya, but the military has declined to give any details on 
troop movements. More than 88,000 refugees have fled Chechnya for 
neighboring Ingushetia to the west, straining the resources of the 
impoverished territory. 

</P>
<P>
	GOP Nears Farm Aid Bill Approval  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House neared final approval today of an  
$8.7 billion package of farm relief despite complaints that it 
wasn't enough money and didn't deal with disputes over dairy policy 
and the Cuban trade embargo. ``If you want to help family farms 
vote for this bill,'' said Rep. Ray LaHood, R-Ill. But Rep. Marcy 
Kaptur, D-Ohio, said much of the money would go to well-off farmers 
and landowners who don't need the help. Republican leaders forced 
the measure out of a House-Senate conference committee without 
provisions that would allow sales of food and medicine to Cuba. 

</P>
<P>
	Pat Robertson Chides GOP Congress  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Christian Coalition founder Pat Robertson  
accused congressional Republicans today of betraying -- by inaction 
and timidity -- the Christian conservatives who helped the GOP take 
control of Congress. ``We want leaders who are motivated by love of 
country, not fear of the next opinion poll,'' Robertson said. 
Addressing the coalition's annual ``Road to Victory'' conference, 
the broadcaster said his primary target is President Clinton. ``As 
we prepare for a new millennium, I want to start with cleansing the 
highest office of the land from the sleaze and the equivocation and 
the moral rot which has embarrassed us all,'' he said. 

</P>
<P>
	Starr Spent $7M During Impeachment  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr spent $7.2  
million on his investigation during the six-month period that 
included the impeachment proceedings against President Clinton. The 
figures included in the audit released today bring the total cost 
of Starr's five-year investigation of President and Mrs. Clinton 
and their associates to $47 million, edging it closer to being the 
most expensive independent counsel probe ever. Independent Counsel 
Lawrence Walsh spent $48.5 million on a six-year probe into whether 
the Reagan administration attempted arms-for-hostages deals with 
Iran and its secret war against the communist-led government of 
Nicaragua. 

</P>
<P>
	Man Arrested in University Bombings  
</P>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- A 41-year-old white man was arrested on  
federal charges in two recent bombings at predominantly black 
Florida A&AMP;M University, the FBI said today. Lawrence Michael 
Lombardi, an unemployed father of two from Tallahassee, was 
arrested about 4:30 a.m. after agents searched his home. He was 
charged with a single count of manufacturing a bomb pending formal 
charges later. Two small explosions have gone off at the campus 
since Aug. 31. No one was injured, but racist phone calls 
accompanied each incident and warned of futher attacks, spreading 
fear on the 12,000-student campus. 

</P>
<P>
	China Marks 50 Years of Communism  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Fighter jets screamed and crisp-uniformed  
soldiers paraded through Tiananmen Square today as China marked 50 
years of communist rule. President Jiang Zemin and other Communist 
Party leaders viewed the parade of a half-million soldiers and 
civilians from atop the Gate of Heavenly Peace. The party's $36 
million celebration is showcasing the nation's growing military 
might and its rapid economic progress since Mao Tse-tung stood atop 
the gate on Oct. 1, 1949, and declared the founding of the People's 
Republic. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 97.83; Nasdaq Down 21.09  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 1 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
down 97.83 points at 10,239.12. Decliners on the New York Stock 
Exchange led advancers 1,788-1,084. The Nasdaq composite index was 
down 21.09 at 2,725.07. 

</P>
<P>
	Venus Williams Ousts Martina Hingis  
</P>
<P>
	MUNICH, Germany (AP) -- Defending champion Venus Williams rallied  
in the third set and beat top-ranked Martina Hingis 6-2, 6-7 (6-8), 
9-7 today to reach the final of the $6.7 million Grand Slam Cup. In 
winning, Williams avenged a semifinal loss to Hingis at the U.S. 
Open three weeks ago. In Sunday's final, worth $800,000 to the 
winner, Williams could face her younger sister Serena, the U.S. 
Open champion. Serena Williams played Lindsay Davenport in the 
second women's semifinal today -- in another repeat of the U.S. 
Open. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
