<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Automakers Post Strong Sept. Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Several major automakers Friday reported vigorous  
U.S. sales in September, with no signs of fatigue from buyers 
enjoying a good economy and low prices. 
</P>
<P>
	General Motors Corp. said it sales were up 8.5 percent, to  
424,184 vehicles, with a 30 percent gain in light truck sales 
offsetting a 7 percent decline in passenger cars. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are good times,'' said Roy Roberts, GM group vice  
president of North America vehicle sales, service and marketing. 
``Vehicles are probably more affordable now than they've been in 
seven, eight or nine years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For only the second month in at least 20 years, GM sold more  
trucks than it did cars. The company has recently put more 
attention on its high-profit trucks, delaying some small-car 
development plans. 
</P>
<P>
	Roberts said it was the best month for GM's full-size trucks  
since March 1979, with strong sales of the company's Suburban sport 
utility vehicle and new Silverado pickups. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a real change for us, and one that we're proud of. The  
trucks have really served us well,'' Roberts said. 
</P>
<P>
	He defended GM's car performance, saying the sluggish sales were  
due to lower demand for passenger cars and a few hiccups. Saturn 
sales were down 11 percent due to start-up problems with 2000 
models; Cadillac sales were off 9 percent as GM phases in the new 
DeVille. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't have any one reason why cars are down,'' Roberts said.  
``In the aggregate, I feel pretty good about where we are.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But other companies reported increases in passenger cars,  
especially European and Asian makes. One analyst said imports 
appeared to be taking a larger share of the market. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are some very large year-to-year increases in new  
foreign makes,'' said David Healy, an analyst with Burnham 
Securities. ``Other competitive cars may be eating GM's lunch in 
the passenger car department.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler AG said sales at its Chrysler division were up 7  
percent, with a 5 percent gain in cars and an 8.5 percent gain in 
trucks. The truck increase was powered by the company's SUVs -- the 
Dodge Durango and the Jeep Grand Cherokee. 
</P>
<P>
	Toyota said its sales were up 10 percent, setting a record for  
the month, with trucks up almost 21 percent. The Camry sedan was up 
16 percent, while sales of the Lexus luxury SUVs were up 32 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Nissan, Mitsubishi and Subaru also reported double-digit sales  
increases, with Mitsubishi up 36 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	European nameplates also did well in September. Volkswagen said  
its sales were up 52 percent. The New Beetle nearly doubled its 
sales, and the company's Jetta and Passat cars also did well. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mercedes-Benz side of DaimlerChrysler posted a 9 percent  
gain, all on the strength of its M-Class SUV. Volvo, Audi and Saab 
also announced large increases in sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford Motor Co. will report its sales Monday.  


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
