<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Car Rental Cos. Petition Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Car rental executives asked Congress to exempt  
them from state laws that require them to pay millions of dollars a 
year to compensate victims of accidents caused by their customers. 
</P>
<P>
	Twelve states have ``vicarious liability'' laws that allow  
accident victims to sue and collect damages from car rental and car 
leasing companies even if they were not at fault. But car renters 
from all states pay higher rates because of those judgments, 
Enterprise Rent-A-Car Vice President Ray Wagner told a Senate 
subcommittee Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is not fair to impose multimillion-dollar judgments on any  
entity, whether an individual or a corporation, when they have done 
nothing wrong,'' Wagner told the Senate Commerce Committee panel on 
consumer affairs, foreign commerce and tourism. 
</P>
<P>
	Wagner, who also is a municipal court judge in St. Louis County,  
said rental companies spend about $100 million every year on 
vicarious liability cases, not including insurance costs and legal 
fees. 
</P>
<P>
	Sharon Faulkner, a regional manager for Premier Car Rental Co.  
in Albany, N.Y., told senators she closed her own small independent 
car rental company in upstate New York in 1997 because of a 
vicarious liability case. 
</P>
<P>
	In that case, the renter agreed that she would be the only  
driver of the car. But she lent the car to her son, who drove it to 
New York City without her knowledge and hit a pedestrian in a 
crosswalk. 
</P>
<P>
	The injured person sued the renter's son, claiming negligence,  
Faulkner said, and her company was named as a co-defendant. 
</P>
<P>
	``You might wonder how it is that my company was sued for this  
accident,'' she said. ``We rented to a licensed driver. ... It was 
the unauthorized driver -- a person neither I or any of my employees 
had ever met -- that caused the accident that injured this 
pedestrian.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A former president of the Association of Trial Lawyers of  
America argued against the bill, saying the federal government had 
no business telling states how they should regulate insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	Vicarious liability laws, which apply to other types of  
businesses, also encourage rental companies to maintain adequate 
insurance, said Larry Stewart, a Miami attorney. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no reason to single out one industry,'' Stewart said.  
``Every special interest would like to have immunity from lawsuits. 
But there's no need here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Car rental and car leasing businesses have pulled in billions of  
dollars in revenue in recent years, he said. ``Surely they do not 
need this legislation in order to flourish. They are merely trying 
to limit their financial liability so they may reap additional 
profits.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is S. 1130.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
