<DOCNO> APW19991001.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 15:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Early Sales Strong for Reagan Book </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Read by few, criticized by many, ``Dutch: A  
Memoir of Ronald Reagan'' finally went on sale Thursday. The book 
had already reached No. 4 on Amazon.com's best-seller list, 
trailing only three ``Harry Potter'' children's stories. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's obviously a very strong debut,'' said Tim Appelo, a  
senior editor for the Internet superstore's best-seller page. 
</P>
<P>
	Author Edmund Morris, granted extensive access to Reagan when he  
was president, took more than a decade to complete the book and has 
been attacked for inserting himself into the story as a fictional 
character. But ``Dutch'' received some strong reviews Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Times' Christopher Lehmann-Haupt praised the  
``force and fascination of Mr. Morris' narrative.'' Deirdre Donahue 
of USA Today called Morris ``a gifted writer'' and said the book 
offers ``penetrating insights and original observations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The author received a reported $3 million from Random House for  
the book, which has a first printing of more than 300,000. 
</P>
<P>
	At a Borders bookstore in Washington, D.C., customers crowded  
the table where ``Dutch'' was displayed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Who wouldn't buy a book about the man who ended the Cold  
War?'' said Steven Scott, a private investigator from Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	At a Barnes &AMP; Noble in nearby Georgetown, department manager  
Noelle Sharbaugh said the biography was selling extremely well. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every other customer this morning is buying the book,'' she  
said. ``We may have to order new copies from the publisher today.'' 
Barnes and Noble does not release any sales figures, but there were 
400 copies in stock at the Georgetown store. 
</P>
<P>
	While some copies leaked early to stores and the press, not many  
people have gotten to see ``Dutch.'' Historian Arthur Schlesinger 
Jr., who has not yet read the book, said Morris should not be 
expected to offer a definitive account. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no ultimate biography,'' said Schlesinger, a former  
Kennedy aide who has written books on the Kennedy and Jackson 
administrations. ``If someone has access to the president and it 
enriches the evidence, I'm all for it. What Edmund Morris has done 
will be of great benefit to future historians.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although his book runs nearly 900 pages, Morris devotes less  
than 300 to Reagan's two terms as president and less than 50 to his 
two terms as governor of California. More space is given to 
Reagan's first wife, actress Jane Wyman, than to his vice 
president, George Bush, or to such longtime political aides as 
Michael Deaver and Edwin Meese. 
</P>
<P>
	Morris, winner of the Pulitzer Prize for his biography of  
Theodore Roosevelt, has said he found Reagan a highly difficult man 
to figure out and that making himself a fictional character was the 
best way to approach the book. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview Wednesday, Morris said he voted for Reagan in  
the 1980 and 1984 presidential elections but that he was 
``emphatically not a political writer.'' He added that he had 
always wanted ``to make literature out of Ronald Reagan.'' 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
