<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former Dolphin Spikes Pleads Guilty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BILOXI, Miss. (AP) -- Former Miami Dolphins running back Irving  
Spikes has pleaded guilty to federal drug and firearms charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Spikes entered his plea Thursday in U.S. District Court in  
Biloxi in the presence of a judge, attorneys and his parents. 
</P>
<P>
	Spikes faces at least five years in federal prison when he is  
sentenced Jan. 12. 
</P>
<P>
	In exchange for his plea, federal prosecutors recommended that  
the court dismiss a charge that Spikes helped others run a cocaine 
business in Alabama and Mississippi. 
</P>
<P>
	Spikes also faces two federal cocaine trafficking charges in  
Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Spikes admitted that on March 15 he and two friends tried to  
sell a piece of sheetrock disguised as a kilogram of cocaine to 
Gulfport drug dealer Derek Joiner, who has pleaded guilty in a 
related case. 
</P>
<P>
	At Joiner's apartment, one of Spikes' cohorts used Spikes' 9-mm  
pistol to rob Joiner of $17,000. After the robbery, Joiner grabbed 
his gun and traded fire with Spikes' group. 
</P>
<P>
	Police arrested Spikes and his friends on U.S. 49 a short time  
later and he has since been in the Harrison County Jail. 
</P>
<P>
	Spikes played four seasons with the Dolphins before being  
released in April 1998. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
