<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> What Can Bush's $56 Million Buy? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush, no doubt, has been advised not  
to spend it all in one place. 
</P>
<P>
	But if he did, the $56 million the Texas governor has raised to  
run for president could buy a small ``Vote Bush'' sign for the yard 
of every single-family house in America or treat everyone of voting 
age to a 25-cent gumball. 
</P>
<P>
	It's enough to buy a single F-15 fighter jet, which might appeal  
to Bush since he flew in the National Guard during Vietnam. Or how 
about 802 Mercedes Benz E55 sedans? 
</P>
<P>
	The only limit to how much Bush can spend to seek the Republican  
nomination is the number of Americans willing to contribute up to 
$1,000 apiece. 
</P>
<P>
	Already, Bush's primary campaign has raised more money than any  
candidate before him ever spent seeking a presidential nomination. 
Predicting just how high he can go has become a political parlor 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	``The cap is about $70 million to $75 million that can be  
raised, just because there aren't that many more folks out there to 
give,'' said Scott Reed, who was 1996 Republican nominee Bob Dole's 
campaign manager. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've heard estimates of up to $100 million,'' said Herbert  
Alexander, professor emeritus of political science at the 
University of Southern California. 
</P>
<P>
	For now, at least, $56 million is the jaw-dropping number. So  
just how much is that? 
</P>
<P>
	--More than was earned last year by singers Celine Dion ($55.5  
million) or Garth Brooks ($54 million), according to Forbes 
magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	--Enough to stockpile 13 million daily food rations for worldwide  
disaster victims. 
</P>
<P>
	--More than the hit movie ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged  
Me,'' drew during its opening weekend ($54.7 million). 
</P>
<P>
	--Enough to finance 24 weeklong search-and-rescue missions like  
the one carried out by a 90-member U.S. team after the Taiwan 
earthquake. 
</P>
<P>
	--The cost of running 5 1/2 minutes of prime time, major network TV  
advertising every night for one month. 
</P>
<P>
	--A brightly colored gumball for each of the 202.7 million people  
of voting age in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	--Enough to purchase 62.1 million campaign yard signs -- one for  
the yard of every single-family detached home in America -- or 466 
million ``Bush for President'' balloons or 622 million combs from A 
Advertising &AMP; Supply of Omaha, Neb., which prints candidates' names 
on novelty items. 
</P>
<P>
	``He could buy a heckuva lot of wooden nickels for that,''  
suggested company president Kirby Ralston. ``As corny as they are, 
they're still a pretty good seller.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One more bit of advice, Gov. Bush: Don't take the wooden  
nickels. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991001.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 00:30:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.C. Residents Survey Ruined Homes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PRINCEVILLE, N.C. (AP) -- Alice Bell lacked the nerve to peek  
inside her flood-ravaged home, yet she vowed to return to the 
parcel of land where her grandparents established roots more than 
50 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm staying,'' she said, unwilling to go inside the brown  
trailer with a water stain from Hurricane Floyd some 8 feet above 
the door sill. ``This is my home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Bell and others surveyed their wrecked homes Thursday for  
the first time since floodwaters swallowed the community of 1,900 
founded by ex-slaves. 
</P>
<P>
	Along the banks of the Tar River, Princeville saw the worst of  
the flooding from Floyd, which dumped up 20 inches of rain two 
weeks ago. But more rain -- 8 inches or more fell this week across 
eastern North Carolina -- delayed recovery efforts and kept the Tar 
and Neuse rivers well above flood stage. They won't fall below 
flood stage until next week. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 47 deaths have been blamed on Floyd, which is expected  
to surpass Hurricane Fran's $6 billion cost in 1996 as the state's 
costliest natural disaster. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials have released new housing damage figures of $250  
million. The storm destroyed 3,680 homes, severely damaged 4,282 
others and caused minor damage to 7,890 more. 
</P>
<P>
	About 1,250 people remained in 14 American Red Cross shelters.  
</P>
<P>
	Emergency funds totaling $20.3 million will help families in  
low-income areas rebuild. The federal government now will cover 90 
percent of initial Floyd disaster aid, and a House committee 
approved $508 million in direct assistance to farmers who lost 
crops and livestock. 
</P>
<P>
	James Lee Witt, director of the Federal Emergency Management  
Agency, and Environmental Protection Agency administrator Carol 
Browner toured flooded Kinston on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	When asked to name the most important environmental lesson  
learned from Floyd, Browner said, ``Stay out of floodplains.'' 
</P>
<P>
	State figures show 14 sewage treatment plants and 50 animal  
waste lagoons remain under water following Floyd. Authorities have 
scrambled to recover dozens of caskets unearthed by floodwaters. 
</P>
<P>
	Maxie Harrison, 37, had to break a bathroom window to get into  
his Princeville home on Thursday: high water had pushed furniture 
and appliances up against the doors. White mold sprouted from door 
frames, a television was upside down in a bedroom, and slippery, 
brown mud covered the floor. In the yard, two roosters lay dead in 
a cage. The stench was horrific. 
</P>
<P>
	Oscar, a green parrot that belonged to Harrison's 18-year-old  
son, gave out a screech, still alive after two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Well, at least we got something. I got Oscar; he's one bad  
bird,'' said Harrison, who is unlikely to return to his house. 
</P>
<P>
	It may be next year before Princeville residents can move back,  
since floodwaters have wiped out the town water system and other 
infrastructure. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert and Callie Suggs won't be back in the green-and-white  
home they built 34 years ago, the place where they raised their six 
children. There is an inch-wide crack in the foundation. 
</P>
<P>
	``All my life this was a gathering place for the family,'' Mrs.  
Suggs said. ``I would cook something every Sunday, and we would 
come here after church and pray together and eat together. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm really going to miss that. I guess someday it'll be the  
same, but I don't know where.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991001.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 15:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
