<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 10:30:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> San Francisco Race Isn't Pretty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- The stylish Mayor Willie Brown appears  
headed for re-election, but it won't be pretty. 
</P>
<P>
	The 14-way campaign has been so bitter that at one debate,  
audience members left in disgust after an hour of chaos and 
shouting that ended in the arrest of one candidate and 11 
supporters. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you like mud, it's been an interesting campaign so far,''  
said Bruce Cain, director of the Institute of Governmental Studies 
at the University of California at Berkeley. 
</P>
<P>
	``Normally in the first phase, the candidates present themselves  
to the public in glowing terms. They kiss babies, bring out their 
wives. We've skipped that phase entirely. They've gone for the 
jugular right from the start.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's not only the candidates who don't like each other. The  
voters don't seem to care for them either. A poll of 621 voters 
last week for the San Francisco Examiner and Oakland TV station 
KTVU found that the three main candidates' unfavorable ratings were 
about as high as or even higher than their favorable ones. 
</P>
<P>
	Only two of the 13 hopefuls challenging Brown are given a real  
shot at success come Nov. 2 -- former Mayor Frank Jordan, who lost 
to Brown in 1995, and political consultant Clint Reilly, who ran 
Jordan's campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	The charismatic, 65-year-old Brown, who is known for his  
expensive suits and an imperious style, is haunted by his 
4-year-old unfulfilled campaign promise to fix the city's transit 
system. Critics also complain he has added millions of wasted 
dollars to the budget. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the FBI is investigating the awarding of contracts  
to minority companies. Agents have called on several city 
departments in a year-long probe, Brown cronies have been targeted, 
and his opponents have said it is inconceivable he wasn't in the 
know. 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan, 64, spent his working life in the police department,  
including five years as chief, before his term in City Hall. But 
the image many people see when they think of him is ... a shower. 
In the waning days of the 1995 campaign, he appeared on a radio 
show in a shower with two disc jockeys. A photographer snapped a 
picture, with Jordan appearing to be naked. He opened himself up to 
national ridicule and lost the election. 
</P>
<P>
	Reilly, 51, spent nine years in a seminary before taking up  
politics in the 1970s. In addition to Jordan, he worked for Sens. 
Barbara Boxer and Dianne Feinstein and Los Angeles Mayor Richard 
Riordan. 
</P>
<P>
	He is dogged by a nasty temper -- he broke an ankle in a tussle  
with San Francisco Examiner executive editor Phil Bronstein -- a 
domestic violence incident 20 years ago involving a former 
girlfriend, and a drunken driving arrest. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown is running ``Jeopardy!''-style TV commercials: ``For $300,  
please!'' -- ``Who has been called famously misogynistic in a 
national magazine and sued for sexual harassment?'' -- ``Who is 
Clint Reilly?'' -- ``Yes!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reilly has run TV ads admitting past indiscretions and ripping  
Brown for bringing them up. ``I made mistakes I deeply regret,'' he 
says. ``I took responsibility for my actions and I haven't had a 
drink since 1981.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan is running the most low-key campaign and hasn't run any  
TV ads. 
</P>
<P>
	At one debate, disgusted audience members left after an hour of  
chaotic shouting. Candidate Lucrecia Bermudez was arrested, along 
with 11 supporters. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a real clothespin election'' -- one in which voters will  
have to hold their noses and vote, said Richard DeLeon, chairman of 
the political science department at San Francisco State University. 
``How disgusted are the voters? My guess is Brown can win without a 
runoff. But I could be wrong.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
