<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Might Call Off U.S. Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- The International Olympic Committee  
insists the Salt Lake City scandal has no bearing on its plans to 
possibly postpone a high-level meeting in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC still intends to hold its executive board meeting, set  
for Feb. 21-23 in Colorado Springs, Colo., and Feb. 25 in Salt Lake 
City. 
</P>
<P>
	But the organization says a ``scheduling conflict'' could force  
a switch. There has been speculation for weeks the meetings would 
be called off. 
</P>
<P>
	Some IOC members are reluctant to travel to the United States  
because they could be stopped for questioning by FBI agents 
investigating the Salt Lake bribery scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, a congressman has threatened to subpoena IOC  
president Juan Antonio Samaranch to testify at a hearing into the 
excesses surrounding Atlanta's winning bid for the 1996 Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``Officially, the executive board meeting is still scheduled,''  
IOC spokesman Franklin Servan-Schreiber said Friday. ``There has 
been no decision to move the meeting in time or place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, the spokesman said officials retained the option of  
canceling or postponing the meetings because of a possible 
scheduling conflict. He cited the Feb. 10-13 meeting in Sydney, 
Australia, of the IOC coordination commission, the panel overseeing 
preparations for the 2000 Summer Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Servan-Schreiber denied any correlation between a possible  
switch in the meetings and the U.S. investigations into the bid 
scandals. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course, people can make a link between the two,'' he said.  
``It looks bad, but there is no link.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Olympic Committee said earlier Friday that it had  
received a letter from the IOC indicating that the meetings were 
being postponed. 
</P>
<P>
	But later in the day, the USOC said it had based its statement  
on a ``miscommunication,'' citing a ``poorly written'' letter from 
the IOC that had been ``misinterpreted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sydney meetings had originally been scheduled for January.  
But they were moved to February to coincide with a meeting of 
national Olympic committees in Sydney. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC said a final decision whether to go ahead with the U.S.  
meetings would be made before the next executive board session in 
December in Lausanne, Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	Servan-Schreiber said it would be possible, if necessary, for  
the meetings to be moved to Sydney or Lausanne. 
</P>
<P>
	But Michael Knight, head of the organizing committee of the  
Sydney Games, said he didn't see any scheduling conflict and was 
unaware the IOC might move the board meeting to Sydney. 
</P>
<P>
	The executive board, which opened four days of meetings in  
Athens on Friday, reached no decision on whether Samaranch should 
appear at the Oct. 14 House hearings into the Atlanta bid. 
</P>
<P>
	``They need more time for a full discussion,'' Servan-Schreiber  
said. ``It's a complex issue. A decision will be made this 
weekend.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A report submitted to Congress last month detailed gifts, travel  
and offers of college scholarships, job assistance and other perks 
to IOC members and their families by Atlanta bid officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch declined to testify at Senate hearings last April into  
the vote-buying scandal stemming from Salt Lake's winning bid for 
the 2002 Winter Games. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
