<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arab Groups Want Disney Exhibit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. (AP) -- After threatening Disney with a  
boycott over an Israel exhibit they hadn't seen, some Arab and 
Muslim groups toured the display today and decided they wanted an 
exhibit for Palestinians. 
</P>
<P>
	Six members of the delegation said they planned to meet with  
Disney officials and demand that such an exhibit be allowed. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Warren, Disney spokesman, responded: ``I'm not going to  
prejudge a decision we haven't had a chance to evaluate. Any day 
we're open to hearing from potential sponsors or exhibitors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The delegation was escorted by Disney officials through the  
Israel exhibit at Epcot, which is part of Walt Disney World's 
15-month millennium celebration. The Millennium Village, which 
opened to the public today, covers 24 countries, with the exhibits 
partially paid for by the countries themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	Some members of the delegation said the exhibit was fair in  
presenting material on Islam and Christianity as well as Judaism. 
But others objected to what they said is the impression that 
Jerusalem is a unified city. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an excellent piece of propaganda,'' said Hussein Ibish,  
spokesman for the Washington-based American-Arab 
Anti-Discrimination Committee. ``I expect nothing less from the 
Israeli foreign ministry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For its part, a Jewish group was unhappy the exhibit makes no  
reference to Jerusalem as the Israeli capital. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were disappointed to see that, according to Disney,  
Jerusalem is the capital of the Millennium, rather than the capital 
of the state of Israel,'' said Abraham Foxman, national director of 
the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith. 
</P>
<P>
	Ibish has said the mention of the capital was deleted because of  
Arab and Muslim criticism. Disney would not say whether the 
reference was deleted or had been left out from the start. 
</P>
<P>
	Israel captured east Jerusalem in the 1967 Mideast War, annexed  
it and claimed the entire city as its capital. The Palestinians 
want the eastern part of the city to be the capital of their future 
state. The United States has never recognized Jerusalem as Israel's 
capital. 
</P>
<P>
	Arab foreign ministers had considered boycotting Disney over the  
exhibit but ultimately decided against it last week. Walt Disney 
World President Al Weiss met with Arab and Muslim leaders in 
Washington several weeks ago to discuss their concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	Two Arab countries are represented at the Millennium Village --  
Morocco and Saudi Arabia. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we're trying to do here is showcase cultures,'' said  
Linda Warren, Walt Disney World's senior vice president of 
marketing and brand management. ``We're completely trying to stay 
out of politics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another group, American Muslims for Jerusalem, didn't take part  
in today's tour but planned to protest and distribute pamphlets 
later today just outside Walt Disney World. 
</P>
<P>
	``These signs will tell visitors what the Israel exhibit fails  
to explain,'' said Khalid Turaani, executive director of the 
Washington-based group. He contended the exhibit depicts east 
Jerusalem as part of Israel and marginalizes the roles of Muslims 
and Christians in Jerusalem. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991001.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 11:10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yanks' AL East Crown Thrills Torre </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The tears in Joe Torre's eyes said it all. No matter how many  
times the New York Yankees spray each other with champagne and beer 
to mark another milestone, none of them take winning for granted. 
</P>
<P>
	Especially Torre.  
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees' manager wiped moisture from his eyes as New York  
clinched its second straight AL East title Thursday night with a 
12-5 victory over the Orioles in Baltimore. He has already 
accumulated two World Series rings and three division crowns in New 
York, yet he isn't that far removed from a time when such success 
was only a dream. 
</P>
<P>
	When the Yankees hired him in November 1995, Torre was five  
months removed from his job as manager of the St. Louis Cardinals. 
He owned a very unspectacular 894-1,003 lifetime record and one 
first-place finish over 14 seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	So even though the Yankees haven't come close to matching last  
year's 114-48 record, and although the season won't be considered a 
success unless New York successfully defends its World Series 
title, Torre took great delight in donning the hat that proclaimed 
his team 1999 AL East champions. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're talking to a 59-year-old guy who was fired at age 55  
and had a little daughter born at the end of that year. Now all of 
a sudden it's the greatest time of my professional life. It 
continues to amaze me,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	During a season in which he missed two months after undergoing  
surgery for prostate cancer, Torre wasn't about to downplay this 
division crown just because New York didn't once again run away 
from the persistent Boston Red Sox. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's still the same result. I get emotional because I know how  
much hard work goes into this thing,'' he said. ``It's not easy 
when you play 162 games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shortstop Derek Jeter, who has led the team at the plate and in  
the field, tipped his champagne-soaked hat to Torre when asked if 
this division crown was different than the other two. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have been through a lot, but Joe was through the most. He  
is the leader of this team,'' Jeter said. ``I can't imagine playing 
for a better manager. He is an inspiration. What he went through, I 
don't think anybody can relate to it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Paul O'Neill, whose three-run double broke open the clincher,  
said, ``Joe's illness was a shock to everybody. We were stunned. 
But here we are, back again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The fact that New York had to work hard to win the division  
might have made this one more satisfying. By the end of May last 
year, the Yankees knew that the AL East crown was almost assuredly 
theirs. This season, the Red Sox just wouldn't go away. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't pretty, but it doesn't always have to be like last  
year when we pretty much won all the games we played,'' Torre said. 
``This year, we had to fight through some things, a tough little 
slump. ... But the guys seemed to pick each other up and I think 
that's the greatest tribute I can pay them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees will open the postseason Tuesday against either  
Texas or Cleveland, but still had something to play for as they 
entered a three-game series against the Tampa Bay Devil Rays on 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	New York started the day trailing Cleveland by one game in the  
battle for best record in the AL, a distinction that enables the 
bearer to enjoy homefield advantage through the league championship 
series. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is only the beginning,'' said Orlando Hernandez, the  
winning pitcher Thursday night. ``We have a long way to go, some 
important games to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's the way Torre's Yankees operate: Savor every precious  
victory and celebrate the important ones, but never take your eye 
off the next objective. 
</P>
<P>
	``This feels great,'' a drenched Tino Martinez said. ``We had a  
great team coming out of spring training, but there's nothing 
given. We had to play all year to get where we're at. It's tough, 
but we did it. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've accomplished our first goal. Now we've got to do the  
rest.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991001.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 19:20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Phillies' Giles To Scale Back Job </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Bill Giles, chairman of the Philadelphia  
Phillies and the team's president until 27 months ago, will 
reportedly give up his day-to-day responsibilities with the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``Retirement isn't quite the right word,'' Giles, 65, told The  
Philadelphia Inquirer for Friday editions. ``I've just decided to 
stop working so hard.'' Team officials refused comment on the 
report and said Giles would have no comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Giles, the son of former NL president Warren Giles, said he will  
remain chairman, a title he assumed in June 1997 when he was 
replaced as president by David Montgomery. He said he will keep his 
15 percent ownership of the team ``as long as I'm alive.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991001.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 17:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Notre Dame Finally Showing Emotion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) -- Notre Dame fullback Joey Goodspeed is  
angry. Left tackle Jordan Black is offended. 
</P>
<P>
	Notre Dame finally is showing some emotion after opening the  
season 1-3, and coach Bob Davie hopes it means the Irish will 
finally play with passion when No. 23 Oklahoma comes to town 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Davie has gone public in pointing out his team's problems the  
last few weeks, and it looks like his words found their target. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am glad they took that personally. I am glad they have  
enough pulse to see that,'' Davie said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rather than being inspired, his players are fighting among  
themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	Black said the offensive line knows quarterback Jarious Jackson  
has lost faith in them after allowing him to be sacked nine times 
in four games. Rather than rally around the fifth-year senior and 
lone captain, Black said the offense has been rallying around 
coordinator Kevin Rogers. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson isn't the only senior riding his underclass teammates  
hard, either. 
</P>
<P>
	Black, a sophomore, said the seniors aren't exactly using  
positive reinforcement as a motivating tool in practice. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now it's kind of more of a, `We're back against the wall,  
we're angry, we're ready to fight' kind of attitude,'' Black said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sooners are in a much different situation. Beating the Irish  
would add legitimacy to their ranking and 3-0 record, both firsts 
since 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	They still have some questions to answer about how good they  
really are after beating up on the likes of Louisville, Baylor and 
Division I-AA Indiana State in establishing the top-ranked offense 
in the country and a defense that ranks 16th overall. 
</P>
<P>
	They also could use another confidence booster before heading  
into a rough stretch of their schedule that includes the likes of 
Texas, Texas A&AMP;M, Colorado and Missouri. 
</P>
<P>
	What would it mean to beat a team that has lost three of four?  
</P>
<P>
	A lot, says first-year Sooners coach Bob Stoops, who called  
Notre Dame the best 1-3 team in the country. 
</P>
<P>
	``The teams they've lost to are excellent football teams,  
undefeated, and they've been to the wire with every one of them,'' 
Stoops said. ``So they're a strong football team, no question, with 
a great deal of pride.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Irish, however, haven't established a consistent running  
game, despite rushing for 363 yards against Kansas in the season 
opener. Also, Jackson has already matched his interception total 
(six) from last season. 
</P>
<P>
	Davie is so desperate for a running game that he's been working  
leading rusher Tony Fisher at the fullback position, in part to 
give promising freshman Julius Jones a shot at tailback to spark 
something -- anything -- in the offense. 
</P>
<P>
	That's irked Goodspeed, who's handled most of the snaps at  
fullback so far. He was also upset that Davie doesn't appear to 
have any confidence in the Irish running game. Davie elected to 
throw on third-and-1 in a critical situation against Michigan State 
and then punted on fourth-and-1 with time running out in the 23-13 
loss. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to be nervous on third-and-1 handing the football  
off or fourth-and-1 punting the football,'' Davie replied. ``I 
think our football team has taken all of this personally. That is 
why I think we have got a chance to get it solved.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even if the Irish are finally showing signs of life, it never  
should have come to this, Black insisted. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a bad sign because Notre Dame is never supposed to be  
1-3, in my opinion,'' he said. ``It irritates me. I can't even tell 
you how mad it makes me when Notre Dame loses a game. But that's 
the fact. We are against the wall and we have to deal with it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
