<DOCNO> APW19991001.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 17:51:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Would Veto Nuclear Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- President Clinton assured Nevada's two senators  
Friday that he will oppose a Republican attempt at compromise over 
disposal of nuclear waste in their state. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton told the two senators aboard Air Force One en route to  
Las Vegas that he will veto a Senate nuclear waste bill -- should it 
pass Congress -- because it would relax safeguards against radiation 
exposure at a permanent disposal site being considered in Nevada. 
</P>
<P>
	The assurances echoed a statement issued in Washington by the  
White House. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yesterday's nuclear accident in Japan is a tragic reminder  
that we must do everything in our power to ensure safe, responsible 
handling of radioactive material,'' Clinton said in the statement. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he reviewed the bill in its current form and  
``determined that it would not adequately ensure the protection of 
public health and safety. If this bill is presented to me in its 
current form, I will veto it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bill was crafted by Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, last  
July in an attempt to break a five-year deadlock over what to do 
with thousands of tons of used reactor fuel now kept at power 
plants around the country. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would keep waste at the reactor sites temporarily,  
although the government would take title pending a decision on a 
permanent waste repository at Yucca Mountain in Nevada. 
</P>
<P>
	In remarks to reporters before leaving Washington, Clinton  
brought up the proposed waste site and said he would ``bend over 
backwards'' to assure that the site will be a safe repository for 
used reactor fuel that will be highly radioactive for more than 
10,000 years. 
</P>
<P>
	He acknowledged that ``the majority of members of Congress''  
favor the Senate bill, which is expected to be considered by the 
full Senate in the coming weeks. No House action has been 
scheduled. 
</P>
<P>
	Aboard Air Force One en route to Las Vegas, Clinton discussed  
the legislation with Nevada Sens. Harry Reid and Richard Bryan. The 
two Democrats have vowed to use any parliamentary tactic to block 
its passage. 
</P>
<P>
	In a telephone interview, Murkowski said the legislation  
represents a compromise because it agrees to Clinton administration 
demands that the waste temporarily be kept at reactor sites. Many 
in the nuclear industry want a temporary storage facility to be 
built in Nevada until Yucca Mountain is available. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's threatening to veto a bill that hasn't even come to the  
Senate yet,'' Murkowski said. ``What's his proposal to address the 
issue of nuclear waste when 20 percent of our power in this country 
comes from nuclear energy?'' 
</P>
<P>
	By law the government must assume responsibility for the waste,  
and several utilities have filed lawsuits claiming breach of 
contract. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Murkowski bill also would require that responsibility  
for determining maximum radiation exposure levels at the future 
Yucca Mountain site be shifted from the Environmental Protection 
Agency to the Nuclear Regulatory Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration, and most environmentalists as well as  
Nevada's senators, strongly object to such a change, contending 
that it would reduce radiation protection. The EPA indicates it 
wants a much more stringent radiation standard than that acceptable 
to the NRC. 
</P>
<P>
	The Energy Department is proceeding with the scientific  
evaluation of the Yucca site for eventual waste burial with a final 
decision on its suitability expected within two years. The 
repository could be completed by 2010. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevada officials have complained for years that the waste site  
was pushed on the state by Congress in 1987. Potential sites in 
Texas and Washington state were eliminated from consideration, the 
Nevadans say, because other lawmakers wanted to make sure it wasn't 
built in their state. 
</P>
<P>
	About the Yucca site, Clinton said Friday: ``My feeling (is)  
that at the time it was selected there was some science in there, 
but perhaps some politics too, since Nevada was a small state.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I have wanted not to see this issue politicized, but to bend  
over backwards to do everything we can to deal with the nuclear 
safety issue before we adopt this course.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991001.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 17:51:01 </DATE_TIME>
