<P>
	Earlier, as he addressing the 3,500 members gathered at a  
downtown Washington hotel picketed by pro-abortion-rights 
supporters, Robertson made a veiled plea to Buchanan. 
</P>
<P>
	``The time will come when we have to choose between two  
candidates for president of the United States,'' Robertson said. 
``Hopefully it's not going to be three.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Political analysts believe Buchanan, as a third-party candidate,  
would weaken the eventual GOP nominee by drawing some Republican 
and independent support. 
</P>
<P>
	But in fired-up remarks to his followers, which were accompanied  
by the ``Rocky'' fight song, Robertson said his primary target was 
President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ladies and gentleman, I don't know about you but I am filled  
with Clinton fatigue,'' Robertson said with a hint of Southern 
drawl. 
</P>
<P>
	``As we prepare for a new millennium, I want to start with  
cleansing the highest office of the land from the sleaze and the 
equivocation and the moral rot which has embarrassed us all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robertson had little good to say about his own party, either.  
``In terms of the Congress, we ask exactly what's been done?'' 
</P>
<P>
	He accused Republican leaders of ``deep ideological problems as  
they have wrestled with the fight against the president who they do 
not care about very much.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To applause, Robertson continued: ``I speak now to our  
Republican friends in Congress. We helped you to be elected. Now we 
ask for principled leadership. We ask for courage. We ask you to 
remember it is better to lose fighting a noble cause than to live 
in peace as a coward. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the words of Ronald Reagan, we would say, 'Paint in vivid  
hues, not in pale pastels.''' 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate interview, Robertson singled out a $215 billion  
highway bill as evidence that congressional Republicans were ``at 
the trough'' as much as Democrats. ``I want them to know we're not 
going to just slavishly do what they want,'' Robertson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, taking his turn in a  
speakers' lineup heavy with GOP presidential candidates, spoke 
generally about the Republican agenda for tax cuts, education and a 
ban on the so-called ``partial birth'' abortion procedure. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Republicans' record of accomplishment, Lott, R-Miss.,  
joked in his folksy manner: ``In the Senate, it's like trying to 
herd cats. They won't herd.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Using the refrain, ``It's in your hands,'' Lott asked the  
coalition to help mobilize Republican voters behind conservative 
candidates. ``I've got to have some help,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the eight Republicans running for president in 2000, seven --  
Elizabeth Dole, Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, 
Steve Forbes, Buchanan, Gary Bauer and Alan Keyes -- were on the 
Christian Coalition program. But Buchanan's staff said today he 
would not speak at the conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona Sen. John McCain also was absent.  
</P>
<P>
	Dole followed Robertson to the massive,  
political-convention-styled lectern erected on stage at the 
Washington Hilton. She did not speak to his criticisms of the GOP 
Congress, where her husband, Bob Dole, was Senate majority leader 
until he resigned in 1996 to run for president. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, Mrs. Dole stuck with a stump speech on education and  
national defense, but heavily laced with talk of her own religious 
upbringing. ``My commitment is to strive to lean on the lord with 
my whole heart, reading his word daily and earnestly seeking his 
will in my life,'' Dole said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I learned from the best -- President Reagan -- that you have to  
lead with the convictions of your heart, not with the latest 
polling data,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	More on the Reform Party, Robertson disparaged its most  
prominent elected official, Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura. ``He's an 
ex-Navy SEAL and I hope he doesn't come after me. He's a big tough 
wrestler, but I think he's off his rocker,'' Robertson said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
