<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coca-Cola Denies Shredding Evidence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Coca-Cola officials did not shred potential  
evidence in a discrimination lawsuit, though they did consider 
putting a shredder in a room containing documents in the case, 
attorneys for the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	Allegations of document-shredding were raised two weeks ago by  
lawyers for four black current or former employees who maintain the 
company racially discriminates within its ranks. Coca-Cola denies 
the charge. 
</P>
<P>
	In their U.S. District Court motion, the plaintiffs' attorneys  
said they had ``substantial evidence'' that the so-called ``war 
room'' where Coca-Cola was working on the suit contained shredders 
that destroyed information. The plaintiffs asked U.S. District 
Judge Richard Story to order additional depositions and to punish 
Coke for any misconduct. 
</P>
<P>
	In a response filed yesterday, attorneys for Coke said company  
officials once discussed the possibility of putting shredders in a 
data collection room but the idea was ``immediately vetoed'' and 
never acted upon. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the meeting, the group discussed using a shredder or the  
confidential refuse system to dispose of any miscopies and extra 
copies of confidential information,'' the company's attorneys said. 
However, company officials decided that placing the shredder in the 
room would give ``the wrong impression,'' the documents said. 
</P>
<P>
	Coca-Cola's attorneys said the plaintiffs' lawyers are  
``apparently unrestrained by any obligation even to attempt to 
verify'' facts and suggested they be sanctioned. 
</P>
<P>
	``Plaintiffs' latest motion is at best reckless and  
disingenuous, and at worst a deliberate attempt to mislead the 
court and manipulate public opinion through demonstrably false and 
inflammatory allegations,'' Coca-Cola said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cyrus Mehri, a plaintiffs' attorney, discounted the company's  
response. 
</P>
<P>
	``This defense is the equivalent of `I smoked pot but didn't  
inhale,''' Mehri said. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
