<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Funeral Co. Lowers Earnings Outlook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Stock in the world's largest funeral company  
plunged 25 percent Friday after Service Corp. International 
announced that it would report disappointing third-quarter 
earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	The Houston-based company blamed everything from ``weakened''  
death rates, bad weather in the Southeast and difficult labor 
negotiations in France for the earnings shortfall. 
</P>
<P>
	SCI said its earnings would be about $27 million to $37 million,  
or 10 cents to 13 cents a share, for the three months ended Sept. 
30. Wall Street analysts surveyed by First Call had expected 
earnings of 22 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	A year ago, SCI reported net income of $83 million, 32 cents per  
diluted share. The company said it expects to release earnings the 
last week of October. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's stock plunged $2.68 3/4 to close at $7.82 1/2 in trading  
Friday on the New York Stock Exchange. Less than a year ago, the 
stock traded for more than $40 a share. 
</P>
<P>
	SCI and other big funeral companies, including Louisiana-based  
Stewart Enterprises Inc., have reported disappointing earnings 
lately. Canada's Loewen Group Inc. filed for bankruptcy in June. 
</P>
<P>
	The problems have been attributed to the frenetic consolidation  
in the funeral industry, with the major companies buying many 
locally owned, independent homes and cemeteries. 
</P>
<P>
	``The whole group is experiencing problems because companies  
have been paying what appears to be too much for a long time,'' 
said Kevin Silverman, an analyst with ABN-Amro. 
</P>
<P>
	Silverman said that companies are now reducing their offers to  
acquisition targets. 
</P>
<P>
	``Consolidation has basically stopped because nobody wants to  
sell at what has become today's lower prices,'' Silverman said. 
</P>
<P>
	SCI said it is looking at ways to improve cash flow, including  
cutting the number of acquisitions, ``significantly'' reducing 
capital expenditures and disposing of some businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief executive R.L. Waltrip said in a statement that the  
company is still focused on its core funeral and cemetery 
operations and aims to increase market share. 
</P>
<P>
	The company did not respond to requests for further comment.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
