<HEADLINE> Beckford, Playgirl Settle Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Playgirl has settled a dispute with model Tyson  
Beckford over the magazine's unauthorized use of his photograph on 
the cover of its September issue. 
</P>
<P>
	Terms of the settlement were not disclosed. Beckford's lawyer,  
Edward Hayes, said the preliminary agreement bars Playgirl and the 
photographer, Timothy White, from using the photo again. 
</P>
<P>
	In court papers filed Wednesday, Beckford said he was ``shocked  
and extremely upset'' with the cover shot. He says the photo -- a 
waist-up shot of a shirtless Beckford glaring at the camera -- was 
cropped to make him appear nude. 
</P>
<P>
	Bethann Hardison, Beckford's manager, had rejected Playgirl's  
offer in February to put him on its cover because she feared any 
association with the magazine would endanger his contract with 
Polo/Ralph Lauren. 
</P>
<P>
	Playgirl's lawyer, Caroline Landau, said the magazine did  
nothing wrong. She said Playgirl bought the photo from a reputable 
photographic ``stock house'' and paid for its use. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
