<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ventura Draws Interview Criticism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- Jesse Ventura's interview with Playboy  
magazine has outraged and disgraced the Reform Party, and the 
Minnesota governor should resign, the outgoing party chairman says. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter Friday to Ventura, Russ Verney criticized the  
ex-wrestler for his comments about religion, sexual assault, fat 
people, drugs, prostitution and women's undergarments, among other 
things. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have brought shame to yourself and disgrace to the members  
of the Reform Party,'' Verney wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Verney, a longtime ally of Reform Party founder Ross Perot, said  
Ventura had severely damaged the credibility and integrity of the 
party. 
</P>
<P>
	But Ventura, who is not in the Perot camp, dismissed Verney's  
attack. In taped comments for NBC's ``Meet the Press'' to be aired 
Sunday, the governor said the national party did ``virtually 
nothing'' to help him in his upset victory last November. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura, who is the highest official in the Reform Party, also  
supported Jack Gargan's successful bid to replace Verney as party 
chairman. Gargan takes over in January. 
</P>
<P>
	Verney said he has been deluged with calls about the interview,  
especially the governor's comments about organized religion and 
Tailhook. Ventura called organized religion a ``sham,'' then said 
later he was referring to extremists. He also said he understood 
the circumstances that led to the Navy's Tailhook scandal, female 
Navy officers were groped and fondled by aviators at a Las Vegas 
hotel; however, he has said repeatedly since that he doesn't 
condone it. 
</P>
<P>
	Verney said he was shocked by newspaper reports about the  
Playboy interview, but thought the actual interview in the magazine 
was ``even worse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If somebody wants to be a leader, they should set the highest  
standard for ethics,'' he said. ``This doesn't stack up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some took particular offense to Ventura's comments on religion,  
which he called a ``a crutch for weak-minded people who need 
strength in numbers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Christian Coalition founder Pat Robertson said Ventura was ``off  
his rocker.'' Others, including Republican presidential hopeful 
Gary Bauer and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, called Ventura a 
bigot. 
</P>
<P>
	Said Lott: ``Can you believe a governor of a state in America  
would say such an insensitive, bigoted thing?'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
