<DOCNO> APW19991001.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 08:30:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC May Cancel U.S. Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- The International Olympic Committee said  
today it might call off a scheduled high-level meeting in the 
United States but denied the possible shift was linked to FBI and 
Congressional investigations of bidding scandals. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC said that, for now, it still was planning to hold  
executive board meetings at Colorado Springs, Colo., and Salt Lake 
City from Feb. 21-25. But it said the meetings could be postponed 
or canceled because of ``scheduling conflicts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	IOC spokesman Franklin Servan-Schreiber denied a report in the  
Salt Lake Tribune that the meeting already had been postponed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Officially, the executive board meeting is still scheduled,''  
he said. ``There will be no discussion on that matter for the time 
being.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the U.S. Olympic Committee said it understood the IOC had  
decided to reschedule the meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have received a letter from the International Olympic  
Committee which would seem to indicate the meeting would be 
postponed,'' USOC spokesman Darryl Seibel said by telephone from 
Colorado Springs. 
</P>
<P>
	Seibel said the letter, dated Sept. 24, was sent by IOC  
secretary general Francoise Zweifel, who is in charge of logistal 
arrangements for the international committee. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's fair to interpret the letter to mean the meeting would  
need to be rescheduled,'' Seibel said. ``My understanding is it 
will be rescheduled.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC cited a possible conflict with a Feb. 10-13 meeting in  
Sydney, Australia, of the IOC panel overseeing preparations for the 
2000 Summer Games. 
</P>
<P>
	USOC president Bill Hybl approached the IOC in mid-September and  
said the USOC was willing to have the meeting changed, according to 
the IOC spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a scheduling problem with Sydney,'' Servan-Schreiber  
said. ``The USOC brought this to our attention and said, `We don't 
need you to be in Salt Lake City at that time. We are ready to 
postpone it if you need to.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	Seibel said he was unaware that Hybl had raised the matter with  
the IOC. 
</P>
<P>
	Servan-Schreiber said it would be possible, if necessary, for  
the executive board to meet at Sydney or Lausanne, Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have scheduling issues all the time,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The spokesman said a final decision whether to go ahead with the  
meetings would be made before the next IOC board meeting in 
December at Lausanne. 
</P>
<P>
	There has been speculation for weeks that the IOC would call off  
the U.S. meetings for fear that IOC members would be questioned by 
FBI agents investigating the Salt Lake City bribery scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, a U.S. Congressman has threatened to subpoena IOC  
president Juan Antonio Samaranch to testify at Oct. 14 hearings 
into excesses surrounding Atlanta's winning bid for the 1996 Summer 
Games. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course, people can make a link between the two,''  
Servan-Schreiber said. ``It looks bad but there is no link.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The executive board, which opened four days of meetings in  
Athens today, discussed whether Samaranch should appear at the 
House hearing, which was called by Michigan Republican Fred Upton. 
No decision was reached. 
</P>
<P>
	``They need more time for a full discussion,'' Servan-Schreiber  
said. ``It's a complex issue. A decision will be made this 
weekend.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A report submitted to Congress last month detailed gifts, travel  
and offers of college scholarships, job assistance and other perks 
to IOC members and their families by Atlanta bid officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Upton said the report showed ``votes were for sale'' and accused  
the IOC of fostering a ``culture of corruption.'' He threatened to 
use ``all legal means'' to ensure Samaranch testifies at the 
hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch declined to testify at Senate hearings in April into  
the vote-buying scandal stemming from Salt Lake's winning bid for 
the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC said today it was exploring the possibility of being  
covered by the Convention on Combating Bribery of Foreign Public 
Officials in International Business Transactions. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Congressional leaders have pushed for the IOC to be covered  
in the United States by the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act. 
</P>
<P>
	But the IOC has said, as a Swiss-based non-governmental  
organization, it might not come under the U.S. legislation. 
Instead, it has asked the French-based Organization for Economic 
Cooperation whether it would fall under the international 
convention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
