<HEADLINE> Twins Sale Negotiations Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- With a deadline for the sale of the  
Minnesota Twins about to pass, negotiators kept up talks Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Twins owner Carl Pohlad and St. Paul Mayor Norm Coleman agreed  
last summer to find a buyer by Oct. 1 in hopes new ownership would 
make a St. Paul stadium proposal more attractive to voters. But the 
deadline wasn't firm. 
</P>
<P>
	Pohlad, Minnesota Wild owner Robert Naegele Jr. and Minnesota  
Timberwolves owner Glen Taylor have been discussed a deal in which 
the baseball team would become linked with the NBA and NHL 
franchises as part of a $100 million deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Any agreement would be conditioned to the city and state  
agreeing to build the Twins a new stadium in St. Paul. City voters 
will decide Nov. 2 whether to approve a 0.5 percentage point 
increase in the city sales tax to pay one-third the cost of a $325 
million ballpark. 
  	   	
</P>
