<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 22:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Reports Two Minor Y2K Failures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The start of the government's new fiscal year  
was marked by minor computer failures at the Energy Department and 
the National Science Foundation that officials blamed on the Year 
2000 technology problem. 
</P>
<P>
	The problems were resolved quickly, said the President's Council  
on the Year 2000 Conversion, which is monitoring agencies through 
the weekend for additional reports of problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``We thought we might have a handful of issues come up,'' said  
council spokesman Jack Gribben. 
</P>
<P>
	The Energy Department said a purchasing system failed, and the  
science foundation reported problems with a system that provides 
information to grant recipients. 
</P>
<P>
	The date system for many federal computers Friday rolled to 2000  
to mark the beginning of the government's fiscal year, offering an 
early taste of how the nation's computer systems may fare in the 
early hours of Jan. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	The so-called Y2K problem exists because many older computers  
and software programs recognize only the last two digits of the 
year and could mistakenly interpret 00 as 1900. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly all states and many companies started their fiscal years  
in July. Few problems were reported then. 
</P>
<P>
	While Friday was the first government-wide date challenge  
related to Y2K, there have been other tests in recent months: A 
date change in a satellite navigation system caused some failures, 
including problems in Japan, where thousand of drivers complained 
about the loss of their mapping computers. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Sept. 9 passed with no reports of serious problems,  
amid concerns that some older computers might interpret ``9999'' as 
a command to stop operating. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
