<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> College To Keep Policy on Admissions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATHENS, Ga. (AP) -- The University of Georgia will continue to  
give some students an edge in admissions because of their race -- a 
policy the state attorney general said will be hard to defend in 
court. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that using race as a factor in admissions, but not  
as a sole determining factor, is a legitimate approach in 
Georgia,'' school President Michael Adams said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision means the university will fight two pending  
lawsuits that contend the policy discriminates against whites. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney General Thurbert Baker, whose office will defend the  
university in court, said its prospects of winning aren't promising 
because courts have grown more hostile to racial preferences. 
</P>
<P>
	``While its chances of prevailing are slim, the university is  
entitled to have its attorneys present its case in court,'' Baker 
said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge warned in a January ruling that the university  
could not justify giving ``racial bonus points'' to some 
applicants. He did not rule on the policy because the student suing 
the university was not academically qualified for admission. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta attorney Lee Parks, who has filed three lawsuits  
claiming the school's admissions policy discriminates against 
whites, said he will keep the issue alive in the courts. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got a very politically heated situation and I think  
people in those situations would rather the courts tell them to 
stop doing something rather than for them to decide not to fight 
the fight,'' Parks said. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a 1978 Supreme Court ruling, universities may not use  
racial quotas, but they may consider race as a factor when 
selecting students. 
</P>
<P>
	Struggles to eliminate race from the admissions process have  
played out in other states -- California, Texas and Washington -- 
while experts say a current fight in Michigan could be decisive for 
the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	Minority admissions and applications have declined in Washington  
and Texas, as they have in California after a voter initiative 
there banned the use of race in admissions. 
</P>
<P>
	The Georgia policy uses the same academic standards for all  
students. However, borderline applicants, who make up 10 to 20 
percent percent of freshman admissions, get extra points for being 
minorities, as do applicants whose parents are alumni or who live 
in rural or poor areas of the state. 
</P>
<P>
	University officials have justified the system as a way to  
diversify the campus, where blacks make up 6.2 percent of the 
student body. The state population is 28.4 percent black. 
</P>
<P>
	Men, however, will no longer receive a preference in borderline  
admissions next year. The university adopted the gender preference 
because women on campus outnumber men. Adams decided to scrap the 
policy for next year because of another lawsuit Parks filed for a 
rejected female applicant. 
</P>
<P>
	Adams, in a speech to the University Council, recalled  
segregated schools and ``whites only'' water fountains from his 
boyhood in Atlanta, Macon and Albany. He said Georgia colleges were 
under court orders to admit more blacks until 1987, and everyone 
has a responsibility to deal with the ``legacy of segregation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Adams also said the university is still not doing enough to  
recruit black students. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are still too many qualified Georgia minorities choosing  
to attend public and private out-of-state schools that they 
perceive to be more prestigious,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
