<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Julio Cesar Chavez Seeks Title Bout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- After taking a beating a year ago from Oscar De  
La Hoya, Julio Cesar Chavez vowed to fight only once more before 
finally retiring. 
</P>
<P>
	Now he has a new plan, and retirement comes with a new set of  
conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	``My goal is to retire as champion. I want the title,'' Chavez  
said. ``I want to retire with dignity and I think I deserve that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chavez returns to the ring Saturday night against Willy Wise, a  
loser of three straight fights, to continue a pro career that began 
in 1980 and spans 106 fights. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mexican boxing legend has been given a favorable No. 2 super  
lightweight ranking by the WBC and wants to fight champion Kostya 
Tszyu by the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fight must take place no later than December because I  
want to retire as world champion,'' Chavez said. ``I want to 
receive the year 2000 as world champion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 37-year-old Chavez, who has held titles in three weight  
divisions, hasn't been much of a factor in the ring in recent 
years, as evidenced by his two losses to De La Hoya and some 
mediocre performances in between. 
</P>
<P>
	Chavez was once 89-0-1, but his 12-3-1 since 1994, including a  
draw with Miguel Angel Gonzalez that would have been a loss if 
scorecards had been tabulated correctly. 
</P>
<P>
	In his second loss to De La Hoya last September, Chavez fought  
gallantly but took a beating for eight rounds before his corner 
wouldn't let him go out for the ninth round. 
</P>
<P>
	He blames a lack of motivation and personal difficulties that  
included financial problems for his performances. And he says those 
are now behind him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I lost because I wasn't motivated. I haven't cared about  
winning,'' Chavez said. ``Now I'm training to win, not to lose.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chavez is back with promoter Don King, who says the fighter  
could either challenge Tszyu or perhaps move up to welterweight and 
fight Felix Trinidad, who beat De La Hoya last month. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a lot of great matches for Julio,'' King said.  
</P>
<P>
	The fight with Wise (23-6-4) is on the undercard of a title  
defense by IBF junior flyweight champion Will Grigsby (14-1-1) of 
St. Paul, Minn. against undefeated former WBC and WBA 105-pound 
champion Ricardo Lopez of Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	Lopez (47-0-1) has held the WBC title since 1990 and is moving  
up in weight for the first time to challenge Grigsby, who captured 
the vacant IBF 108-pound title with a decision over Ratanapol 
Vorapin on Dec. 18. 
</P>
<P>
	``I figure I kind of made a name for myself (with that  
victory),'' Grigsby said. ``One of the things is I want to be known 
as the best fighter out there at 108 pounds. Once I beat Lopez, I 
believe I will be the best out there.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
