<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Jobless Rate Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's jobless rate fell to 4.7 percent in August  
from the previous month's record high 4.9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	A sharp decline in the percentage of unemployed men avvounted  
for the overall decline, the government's Management and 
Coordination Agency said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The unemployment rate for men stood at 4.7 percent in August,  
down from July's record 5.1 percent. The rate for women was 
unchanged at 4.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	While the total number of jobholders fell by 350,000 to 65.11  
million in August from the year-earlier month, it was up from 
July's 64.97 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The jobless rate has risen in recent months, increasing  
pessimism about the nation's economy, which is struggling to emerge 
from its worst downturn in 50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists surveyed by Dow Jones Newswires in Tokyo had forecast  
the overall jobless rate would stay at 4.9 percent in August. 
</P>
<P>
	``Looking at the raw numbers from the latest report, there is  
brightness in the movements of the labor market,'' said Shinya 
Iijima, an agency official who briefed reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	But Iijima said that the labor situation is still severe and the  
outlook remains uncertain. ``We can't tell what the trend is just 
by looking at the August figures,'' the official said. 
</P>
<P>
	Iijima said that the flow of jobholders into temporary positions  
continued, suggesting that companies are still trying to cuts costs 
by scaling back their permanent work forces. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of permanent jobholders in August fell by 0.8 percent  
on year, for the 20th straight month of falls, while the number of 
temporary workers climbed by 6.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The trend toward an increasing number of part-timers has been in  
place for nearly three years. The pace of growth picked up in 
August compared with July's 1.0 percent growth rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, the Labor Ministry said that the ratio of job offers  
to job seekers, an indicator of demand for labor, was unchanged in 
August at 0.46 from July. 
</P>
<P>
	The figure shows that there were 46 jobs offered for every 100  
people seeking employment in August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
