<DOCNO> APW19991001.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 21:20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> La. Judge Pleads Guilty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- A former judge pleaded guilty Friday to  
helping the owner of an insurance company negotiate a favorable 
settlement with the state after the company collapsed. The case has 
led to the indictments of a former governor and two state 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Judge Foxy Sanders pleaded guilty to witness tampering  
and conspiracy to commit mail fraud. He faces up to six months in 
prison, a $25,000 fine and loss of his law license. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders, former Gov. Edwin Edwards and Insurance Commissioner  
Jim Brown were indicted Sept. 24, along with Cascade Insurance 
owner David Disiere, his lawyer and the state official who handles 
insurance company liquidations. 
</P>
<P>
	After Cascade failed in 1993, a court-appointed investigator  
looking into allegations that Disiere had illegally siphoned off $8 
million from the company had recommended the state pursue a $4.4 
million settlement with Cascade. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement Sanders approved was worth $2.5 million -- far  
short of what the state should have gotten, federal prosecutors 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The prosecutors said Edwards, Brown and Disiere had intimidated  
and threatened the judge and even sued to have him dismissed from 
the case. When that didn't work, the former governor allegedly 
offered to help quell an unrelated investigation into Sanders if 
the judge agreed to assist them. Disiere allegedly paid Edwards 
$100,000 to arrange the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	After pleading guilty Friday, Sanders told reporters, ``I take  
full responsibility.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Edwards said the $100,000 was a legitimate legal fee.  
</P>
<P>
	Another case stemming from the investigation goes to trial in  
January -- Edwards is accused of rigging state riverboat licenses. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
