<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 20:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Helps Raise Campaign Cash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- President Clinton went to Paris on Friday and  
raised money for Democrats at the Eiffel Tower. 
</P>
<P>
	Paris is a hotel and casino in this resort town, with a  
spiraling replica of the famous tower on top. Inside the tower was 
a restaurant where Clinton addressed about 40 supporters at a 
luncheon that brought in $300,000 for the Democratic Senatorial 
Campaign Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've already had more dreams fulfilled than I could have asked  
for in 10 lifetimes, but I never dreamed I'd actually get to give a 
speech in the Eiffel Tower,'' Clinton joked. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday's luncheon began a weekend of fund-raisers that were  
expected to raise $2.5 million for Democrats. Afterward, the 
president headed to Palo Alto, Calif., for a reception and dinner 
raising $625,000 for the Democratic National Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	In Palo Alto, Clinton decried resistance in Congress to his  
education proposal and accused Republicans of trying to kill it to 
prevent his Democratic administration from having ``any achievement 
that is demonstrable and tangible, that changes the lives of 
people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It is the smallest kind of politics, and who cares what  
happens to the kids?'' Clinton said. ``There is a difference 
between where we stand and where they stand. You stand with us, and 
stand with us all the way to November 2000.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The largest take, $850,000, was coming from a Saturday night  
dinner in Los Angeles organized by ANGLE, Action Now for Gay and 
Lesbian Equality, to benefit the Democratic Congressional Campaign 
Committee. More than 600 people are expected to attend. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is one of the biggest events we've ever done outside of  
Washington,'' said DCCC spokesman John Del Cecato. ``This will be 
the most successful event that the DCCC has done with the gay and 
lesbian community, ever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Friday fund-raiser's host was Arthur Goldberg, chief  
executive officer of Park Place Entertainment, which owns Paris. 
Goldberg credited Clinton with making the United States ``the 
greatest country in the world'' -- and gave the president a 
political title he's never held. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I met the distinguished gentleman with the grayish hair  
on my left, he was a senator who really gave long speeches for his 
convention,'' Goldberg said, referring to Clinton's long-winded 
address at the 1988 Democratic convention. ``We knew what would lay 
ahead. He has continued that friendship and has never forgotten the 
people who were with him early on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Goldberg's role Friday is indicative of a trend in the casino  
industry toward lobbying and contributing to campaigns. Harrah's 
has contributed more than $1 million since 1995. Mirage boosted its 
giving from $159,800 in 1995-96 to $528,846 in 1997-98. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt flew to Las  
Vegas to pick up a $250,000 check from Mirage. In August, House 
Speaker Dennis Hastert raised $600,000 at a Las Vegas lunch with 
casino executives, calling their business ``a great industry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the end of the luncheon, Clinton gave a long, affectionate  
hug to Dr. Elias Ghanem, chairman of the Nevada Athletic Commission 
and formerly Elvis Presley's physician. Clinton seemed surprised to 
see Ghanem, who has been battling cancer. They chatted briefly and 
Clinton hugged Ghanem tightly again before moving on. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said those at Friday's reception had ``a sense of  
enlightened self-interest'' in their political choices. ``You're 
intelligent enough to support Democrats so you can continue to live 
like Republicans,'' he joked. 
</P>
<P>
	He noted the $56 million that Texas Gov. George W. Bush has  
raised for his GOP presidential bid and said he was thinking of 
counting Bush's fund-raising success ``as one of the economic 
achievements of my tenure in office.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't discriminate. We allowed the Republicans to make  
money too in this economy,'' Clinton said. ``It's not our fault if 
they decide to spend it in a way different than we would like.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton noted that while he can't run for the White House again  
he'd like to choose the theme song for the 2000 election -- ``Don't 
Stop Thinking About Tomorrow,'' the same Fleetwood Mac tune he used 
for his 1992 campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every country must always have its eyes pointed toward  
tomorrow,'' Clinton said. ``The question is not whether America 
will change, it is how America will change, and whether we will 
build on what we have done that is working ... or whether we will 
basically veer off and go back to an approach that got us into an 
awful lot of trouble before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Outside of fund-raising, the president also planned to spend  
time with daughter Chelsea, who is beginning her junior year at 
Stanford University, and do some preparation work for his 
presidential library. He returns to Washington on Monday. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
