<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FBI Probes Unarmed Suspect's Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- The FBI is investigating the slaying of a black  
carjacking suspect by a Hispanic officer who has shot and killed 
three other people in 15 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said Sgt. Juan Mendez fired seven shots at Antonio  
Butler, hitting him twice, as the unarmed 19-year-old tried to 
climb a fence to get away Sept. 20. Mendez, 39, had spotted Butler 
driving a car that had been stolen at gunpoint the night before. 
</P>
<P>
	Police officials have backed Mendez, saying the officer feared  
Butler might take a hostage and thought the teen was reaching for a 
gun. 
</P>
<P>
	Mendez, who has been reassigned to a desk job while the  
department investigates, killed three Hispanic suspects in the line 
of duty. All were armed. Internal investigators determined the 
shootings were justified. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Attorney's office said Thursday the FBI was brought  
into the investigation after Rep. Carrie Meek, D-Fla., wrote a 
letter to Attorney General Janet Reno expressing concern about 
Mendez's record and racial profiling by police. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am certain that you are aware of the long history of worry  
and concern in Miami's African American community that police 
officers are more likely and particularly quick to use lethal force 
against black suspects compared to white or Hispanic suspects,'' 
Meek wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, more than 300 demonstrators snarled traffic outside  
the police department as they demanded Mendez be fired. 
</P>
<P>
	The Miami branch of the NAACP has also denounced the shooting.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
