<HEADLINE> Soybeans, Grains Move Lower / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean futures prices fell today in early  
trading on the Chicago Board of Trade, despite an estimate from a 
closely watched private analyst that production was lower than the 
government's September estimate. 
</P>
<P>
	Many traders already expected the government to lower soybean  
production in its Oct. 8 report. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures fell to a new two-month low after the analyst  
Sparks Cos. estimated production was 100 million bushels higher 
than the U.S. Agriculture Department's estimate. Wheat futures also 
fell. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasters are calling for a relatively dry weekend throughout  
most of the soybean belt, allowing the harvest to continue. 
Scattered showers are forecast for the Midwest into Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	In early trading today, wheat for December delivery fell 2 3/4  
cents to $2.73 a bushel; December corn fell 1 1/2 cents to 2.06 3/4 a 
bushel; December oats fell 1 3/4 cents to $1.12 1/2 a bushel; and 
November soybeans fell 3 1/2 cents to $4.87 3/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, meat and livestock futures prices rose in early  
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	October live cattle rose 0.08 cent to 68.35 cents a pound;  
October feeder cattle rose 0.23 cent to 81.30 cents a pound; 
October lean hogs rose 0.78 cent to 49.75 cents a pound; and 
February frozen pork bellies rose 0.90 cent to 64.80 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
