<HEADLINE> NYC Pays $40M To Resolve Cop Claims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- New York City paid out a record $40 million in  
the last fiscal year to resolve claims and lawsuits against police 
officers charged with brutality, up 40 percent from the previous 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of brutality claims seeking damages increased by 10  
percent, to 2,324, the highest number in a decade, the city 
comptroller said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	City officials dismissed the suggestion that the increases were  
a measure of more misconduct being committed by police officers. 
Instead, city lawyers pointed to a new policy that calls for more 
cases to be settled quickly to avoid the long-term costs of an 
extended court fight. 
</P>
<P>
	The $40 million includes cases that were settled and those  
decided with a court judgment. The city paid $405 million to 
resolve other lawsuits and claims, most of them personal injury 
claims stemming from accidents like sidewalk slips. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
