<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vandals Damage Georgia FB Stadium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATHENS, Ga. (AP) -- The University of Georgia said damages might  
total $100,000 after vandals broke into Sanford Stadium with bolt 
cutters and drove across the football field Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The school estimates it will cost $10,000 for a quick fix to  
make the field playable for Saturday's game against LSU. Restoring 
the field to its original condition might cost up to $100,000, 
school spokesman Pete Konenkamp said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an extensive turf restoration problem,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Two donut-shaped rings 20 to 25 feet in diameter were  
embroidered into the field. Workers began resodding areas where 
2-inch deep ruts marked the skidding vehicle's tracks. 
</P>
<P>
	Konenkamp said university groundkeepers were concerned about  
possible damage to the field's liner beneath the turf. 
</P>
<P>
	University police said they had no suspects.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991001.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-01 06:40:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Colo., Utah, Await IOC Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Just days after a congressman asked  
International Olympic Committee president Juan Antonio Samaranch to 
testify about bid excesses, the IOC has said it might call off a 
scheduled high-level meeting in the United States, 
</P>
<P>
	It denied the possible shift was linked to investigations of  
bidding scandals. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch has been asked to testify Oct. 14 before Rep. Fred  
Upton's House commerce subcommittee on oversight and investigation, 
and the matter is expected to be discussed at this week's executive 
board meetings in Athens. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC said today that, for now, it still was planning to hold  
executive board meetings in Colorado Springs and Salt Lake from 
Feb. 21-25. But it said the meetings could be postponed or canceled 
because of ``scheduling conflicts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Salt Lake Tribune said in today's edition that a letter  
faxed to U.S. Olympic Committee officials this week said the 
February meeting plans were being changed because of an apparent 
scheduling conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	However, IOC spokesman Franklin Servan-Schreiber denied that the  
meeting already had been postponed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Officially, the executive board meeting is still scheduled,''  
he said. ``There will be no discussion on that matter for the time 
being.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Olympic Committee president Bill Hybl approached the IOC in  
mid-September and said the USOC was willing to have the meeting 
changed, according to the spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	Servan-Schreiber cited a possible conflict with a Feb. 10-13  
meeting in Sydney, Australia, of the IOC panel overseeing 
preparations for the 2000 Summer Games. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a scheduling problem with Sydney,'' he said. ``The  
USOC brought this to our attention and said, `We don't need you to 
be in Salt Lake City at that time. We are ready to postpone it if 
you need to.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	Servan-Schreiber said it would be possible, if necessary, for  
the executive board to meet at Sydney or Lausanne, Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have scheduling issues all the time,'' he said. ``This  
happens a lot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The spokesman said a final decision whether to go ahead with the  
meetings would be made before the next IOC board meeting in 
December in Lausanne. 
</P>
<P>
	Upton, R-Mich., has said that if Samaranch does not appear  
voluntarily at hearings next month investigating the ``culture of 
corruption'' surrounding Atlanta's winning bid for the 1996 Summer 
Games, he would be subpoenaed. 
</P>
<P>
	That could occur any time Samaranch entered the United States.  
</P>
<P>
	Upton wants to question Samaranch about how the IOC chooses  
cities to host the Olympics. Salt Lake City has admitted to using 
expensive gifts, cash and offers of scholarships to influence the 
voting process. 
</P>
<P>
	An investigation by Upton's subcommittee found that Atlanta bid  
officials also offered lavish gifts and favors, 
</P>
<P>
	In an effort to learn more about Atlanta's bid, Upton has  
invited to his Oct. 14 hearing former Secretary of State Henry 
Kissinger and former Sen. Howard Baker, both members of the IOC 
2000 reform team; former Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young; Atlanta 
Olympic Committee president Billy Payne; and U.S. Olympic Committee 
leaders Bill Hybl and Scott Blackman -- and Samaranch. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Justice Department is probing the legality of the  
$1 million in cash and goods Salt Lake City supplied to IOC 
members. 
</P>
<P>
	The hostility between federal officials and the IOC has put the  
Salt Lake Organizing Committee in a delicate position, trying not 
to alienate either side. 
</P>
<P>
	SLOC president Mitt Romney has tried to stay away from the  
battle. ``One of the great challenges of my office is separation,'' 
he said. ``Separation from the past, separation from people with 
varying views we may or may not agree with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, it was announced that Gordon Kane is leaving his USOC  
post to join Ignite Sports Media, a Chicago-based Internet company 
that will produce Web sites for professional sports teams. 
</P>
<P>
	Kane is the second USOC marketing official to leave. John  
Krimsky quit in June for a position with American Airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	Kane, director of marketing and brand development, said his  
leaving had nothing to do with the bribery scandal, slumping sales 
or the reshuffling of USOC management. Kane said the new job offer 
was just too good to ignore. 
</P>
<P>
	Kane also served as vice president of OPUS (Olympic Properties  
of the United States), USOC's joint marketing venture with SLOC. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
