<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls on Fears of Rate Hike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar fell against other currencies Friday  
after several indications of strength in the U.S. economy renewed 
concerns that the Federal Reserve may raise interest rates when it 
meets next week. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 104.96  
Japanese yen, down from 106.27 late Thursday. The euro was quoted 
at $1.0728, up from $1.0684. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks swooned on Wall Street after a report by the National  
Association of Purchasing Management showed that U.S. manufacturing 
activity grew faster than expected in September, confirming that 
the economy is rebounding from a slow second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The NAPM also reported that prices of raw materials soared to  
the highest level in more than four years. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, the Commerce Department said the personal income of  
Americans climbed in August for the eighth consecutive month. But 
their spending rose faster, leaving the nation's savings rate 
matching a record low. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors had been hoping that the Fed would stand pat on rates  
when it meets next Tuesday, and the new reports Friday showing 
strength in the economy got financial markets worried again. 
</P>
<P>
	The decline in stocks and Treasury bonds put downward pressure  
on the dollar as demand for the currency was weakened by the 
decline in major dollar-denominated assets. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.4820 Swiss francs, down from  
1.4969, and 1.4769 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4674. The British 
pound rose to $1.6548 from $1.6464. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Friday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8229 German 
marks, down from 1.8308; 6.1139 French francs, down from 6.1403; 
and 1,804.71 Italian lire, down from 1,812.39. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
