<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Day Care Operator Sentenced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- A day care center operator convicted of fatally  
shaking a 13-month-old boy and slamming his head on the floor 
received the maximum sentence of 25 years to life in prison under a 
new state law covering fatal assaults on children. 
</P>
<P>
	Manjit Basuta, 44, was sentenced Friday in the death of Oliver  
Smith. She was convicted in June of killing the boy because he 
wanted to watch television rather than get a diaper change. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Basuta will serve at least 25 years before she is eligible  
for parole. Under the new law, Judge William Kennedy's only other 
option was probation. 
</P>
<P>
	``This defendant, even though she doesn't like to hear it, has a  
dark side to her,'' Kennedy said. ``She never showed remorse for 
the victim or his family. ... She has tried to lay blame of this 
tragedy on everyone else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Basuta's shoulders heaved in grief and she sometimes sobbed  
loudly as the judge imposed the sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	Audrey Amaral, the boy's mother, carried a photo of the boy with  
her when she addressed the court before sentencing. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Mrs. Basuta spends a lifetime in prison, it will be a small  
consequence compared to the death sentence that my son, Oliver 
Smith, has been given,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Basuto, a native of India who holds British citizenship,  
ran the day care center out of her home. 
</P>
<P>
	The only eyewitness to the killing was Cristina Carillo, Mrs.  
Basuta's housekeeper, who testified that Mrs. Basuta was angry at 
the boy because he kept watching television when she called him. 
She said Mrs. Basuto shook the boy, pushed him to the floor, then 
banged his head while changing the diaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Basuta insisted that Oliver was injured when another child  
pushed him and he hit his head on a brick patio. She did not 
testify but said later that the housekeeper had lied. 
</P>
<P>
	Since Oliver's death, his mother has pushed for the passage of  
Oliver's Law, which calls for stricter state regulations for day 
care centers and better training for child care providers. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
