<HEADLINE> Laser Pointer Mishap Brings Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- When police officer Bernard Anderson saw a  
red dot appear on his chest as he worked special duty outside a 
nightclub, he panicked, thinking it was from a laser gun sight. 
</P>
<P>
	He took cover and called for help. A police helicopter and  
patrol cars were dispatched, and soon the culprit was found: a man 
with a laser pointer. 
</P>
<P>
	Patrick O'Connor, 42, of London, Ohio, was charged with inducing  
panic and aggravated menacing for the incident in July. 
</P>
<P>
	After a preliminary hearing this week, a Nov. 10 trial date was  
set. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Connor was in a parking lot across the street from the  
nightclub and said he was just trying to get the attention of some 
friends when he accidentally aimed the laser at the officer. 
</P>
<P>
	His attorney, Kathleen Duchak, said there was no intent to harm  
or startle the officer. 
</P>
<P>
	But Anderson said: ``I can't lie. It scared the heck out of  
me.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
