<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mass. Court: Student Can Sue School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Saying a campus disciplinary hearing had serious  
flaws, a state appeals court has ruled that a former Brandeis 
University student accused of rape should be allowed to sue the 
school for suspending him. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling could have ramifications for private colleges  
everywhere. 
</P>
<P>
	A female student accused David A. Schaer of raping her in her  
dorm room in 1996; Schaer said they engaged in consensual sex. 
</P>
<P>
	Schaer, then a 20-year-old junior, was never charged criminally,  
but a school disciplinary board of six students and two faculty 
members found he was responsible for the alleged violations. 
</P>
<P>
	He was suspended from campus between May and August of 1996,  
preventing him from working on a biomedical research project at a 
university lab. Schaer tried to sue the school for damages, but a 
Middlesex Superior Court judge dismissed the case. 
</P>
<P>
	In overturning the lower court's ruling, the state Appeals Court  
questioned the validity of the campus disciplinary hearing, saying 
some of the testimony would never have been allowed in a court of 
law. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, the three-judge panel cited the testimony of a  
campus police officer. The female student, who reported the alleged 
rape a month after the encounter, ``looked like a rape victim,'' 
the officer testified. 
</P>
<P>
	``On what possible basis a police officer could know such a  
thing does not appear,'' the court said. 
</P>
<P>
	Another witness testified that Schaer was a ``self-motivated  
egotistical bastard who had no respect for women,'' something the 
court said was without foundation and ``unfairly prejudicial.'' 
</P>
<P>
	David Lipton, Schaer's attorney, said school disciplinary panels  
are akin to kangaroo courts, and added that private colleges need 
to take a closer look at the way they discipline students. 
</P>
<P>
	``They should understand the gravity, the really serious impact  
this kind of process has on people, and how it can ruin their 
lives,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Schaer graduated from Brandeis in 1997 and is now pursuing  
graduate work in biology. 
</P>
<P>
	Brandeis officials declined comment because the case is still  
pending in court, but spokesman Dennis Nealon said Brandeis does 
not take disciplinary cases lightly. 
</P>
<P>
	``Officials here go to great lengths to let students know from  
the very first day what is and what is not acceptable behavior,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheldon Steinbach, general counsel for the American Council on  
Education, said university disciplinary proceedings and conduct 
codes are ``reasonably sophisticated'' and serve an important 
purpose on American campuses. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, he said, Thursday's decision should be a reminder to  
schools to ``take a careful look at their internal processes to 
ensure that elementary fairness is available to both the accused 
and the accuser.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Appeals Court decision could have widespread effects, said  
Harvey Silverglate, a defense attorney and co-author of ``The 
Shadow University: The Betrayal of Liberty on America's Campuses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In many instances, Silverglate said, students accused of a crime  
on campus would be better off if they were prosecuted in a courts. 
</P>
<P>
	``Private colleges have generally gone on the assumption that  
they can do whatever they want,'' Silverglate said. ``Courts look 
at these on a case-by-case basis and usually private colleges get 
away with all kinds of outrageous conduct.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
