<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Soybeans Fall Sharply; Gold Rises  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean futures prices fell sharply in trading  
Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade, as forecasters called for 
relatively dry weekend weather that will allow continued 
harvesting. 
</P>
<P>
	In other commodities markets, gold finished higher and natural  
gas futures rose. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean futures prices slumped despite an estimate from a  
closely watched private analyst that production was lower than the 
government's September estimate. Many traders already expected the 
government to lower soybean production in its Oct. 8 report. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures fell to a 10-week low after an analyst estimated  
production was 100 million bushels higher than the U.S. Agriculture 
Department's estimate. Wheat futures prices also fell. 
</P>
<P>
	In trading Friday, wheat for December delivery fell 8 3/4 cents to  
$2.67 a bushel; December corn fell 3 1/4 cents to $2.05 a bushel; 
December oats fell 1 cent to $1.12 1/4 a bushel; and November soybeans 
fell 10 1/4 cent to $4.81 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Lean hog futures prices rose in trading Friday on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange, amid continued strong demand and expectations 
that exports will strengthen this fall. Live cattle and pork 
bellies futures also rose. 
</P>
<P>
	October live cattle rose 0.50 cent to 68.77 cents a pound;  
October feeder cattle rose 0.78 cent to 81.85 cents a pound; 
October lean hogs rose 1.40 cents to 50.37 cents a pound; and 
February pork bellies rose 1.70 cents to 65.60 cents a pound. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold regained some of its value Friday on the New York  
Mercantile Exchange, finished up $5.80 at $305.30 per ounce, buoyed 
by the dollar's continued decline against the yen, as well as the 
slump in bonds and stocks. Prices had retreated Thursday, reversing 
a frenzied price rally earlier in the week that saw prices as high 
as $329 Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Platinum and palladium also rose.  
</P>
<P>
	December palladium rose $7.35 to $376.75 per ounce and January  
platinum rose $2.90 to $393.80 per ounce. 
</P>
<P>
	Natural gas futures rose 4.6 cents to $2.90 per 1,000 cubic feet  
in trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange as the season's 
first cold snap prompted Midwest storage buying. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures dipped into the teens across Canada's prairie  
provinces and slipped in the upper 20s and 30s across the northern 
U.S. plains states. 
</P>
<P>
	``There has been a real tug-o-war going on in this market,''  
said analyst Tim Evans of Pegasus Econometric Group in New York. 
``We have had buying on the theory that natural gas is somehow 
undervalued relative to the crude oil market, and a little buying 
on the forward market in anticipation that the coming winter is 
going to be colder.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the rally, natural gas futures prices still have not  
reached the August high of $3.24, during hurricane season. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
