<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Oct. 1, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Close Lower; Dow Down 63.95  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks resumed their slide today after new  
reports showed the economy's surging growth has not slowed in 
recent months. The data renewed concerns that hints of inflation 
will prompt the Federal Reserve to boost interest rates next week. 
The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 63.95 at 10,273.00, 
having recovered back from a loss of as much as 135 points. The 
blue-chip index ended a fairly volatile week just 6.33 points below 
last Friday's close. Broader stock indicators were mostly lower. 
The Nasdaq composite index fell 9.30 to 2,736.86. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures as of Friday's close:  
Dow Industrials:        10273.00  - 63.95
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1258  Declines 1799  Unchgd  484
NYSE Volume:         845,617,020
Most Active NYSE issue:         Williams Comm28 3/16  UNCH
S&AMP;P 500:         1281.35  - 1.36
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          786.53  - 1.70
Nasdaq Composite Index        2736.86  - 9.30
Gold(final) -    $303.70    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Fri.

</P>
<P>
	UAW Presents Tentative GM Contracts  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- The United Auto Workers presented tentative  
contracts with General Motors Corp. and its former parts unit to 
its local union leaders today, while negotiations at Ford Motor Co. 
intensified. About 500 union officials gathered here to hear 
details of the contracts covering 185,000 workers at GM and Delphi 
Automotive Systems. The union said the deal gives the average 
assembly worker $29,900 in wage increases, bonuses and holidays 
over the next four years. The union's executive council recommended 
the contract to the local unions, where ratification votes are 
expected to be completed by Oct. 10. 

</P>
<P>
	Manufacturing Sector Grew in Sept.  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The nation's manufacturing sector grew in  
September for the eighth consecutive month, while prices of raw 
materials spurted to the highest level since May 1995. The gain 
reported in the survey released today by the National Association 
of Purchasing Management was much stronger than analysts had 
predicted. It was further evidence that the economy grew strongly 
in the third quarter after a lackluster second quarter. The index 
reading for September was 57.8 percent, compared with 54.2 percent 
in August. 

</P>
<P>
	Spending Rising Faster Than Income  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Personal income in the United States rose in  
August but spending climbed much faster, leaving the nation's 
savings rate matching a record low. Personal income -- which 
includes wages, interest and government benefits -- rose 0.5 percent 
in August, the Commerce Department said today. The gain followed a 
0.2 percent increase in July. The Federal Reserve, seeking to slow 
the economy and keep inflation at bay, bumped up interest rates 
twice this summer, making borrowing more expensive. Fed 
policy-makers meet again on Tuesday. 

</P>
<P>
	Taiwan Quake Hurts Hewlett-Packard  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Hewlett-Packard Co. warned today that it  
will report quarterly sales at the low end of Wall Street 
projections after an earthquake last month in Taiwan slowed 
production of parts that power its computers and other machines. 
Taiwan is one of the world's top producers of the semiconductor 
chips used to run computers. Hewlett-Packard said that the 
company's revenue would grow about 10 percent in the fiscal fourth 
quarter, which ends Oct 30. Wall Street had expected 
Hewlett-Packard to report sales growth ranging from 10 percent to 
13 percent. Stock in H-P fell 3 3/8 to 87 3/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Pfeiffer To Lead Intershop Board  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Eckhard Pfeiffer, former chief executive  
officer of Compaq Computer Corp., is taking over as chairman of 
Intershop, which helps clients build electronic storefronts on the 
Internet. Pfeiffer was ousted from Compaq last spring after 
disappointing earnings. Pfeiffer does not plan to work full-time 
with the company. 

</P>
<P>
	Wal-Mart Designs New Web Site  
</P>
<P>
	BENTONVILLE, Ark. (AP) -- Wal-Mart Stores Inc. will focus its  
redesigned Web site on toys and consumer electronics, taking on 
already established Internet merchants Amazon.com and eToys. The 
nation's biggest retailer said more information is expected in the 
coming weeks as it prepares for the start of the holiday shopping 
season. Industry analysts expect Wal-Mart's push online to change 
the entire retail business on the Internet, given its ability to 
keep prices down and sophisticated method of collecting consumer 
and product information. 

</P>
<P>
	Supervision of Big U.S. Banks Urged  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Though the U.S. banking system performed well  
during the past two years of global turmoil, the Asian financial 
crisis still pointed up a need for increased supervision of the 
country's 30 largest banks, a Federal Reserve official said today. 
Laurence H. Meyer, a member of the Fed's board of governors, said 
the central bank had begun to overhaul its regulatory processes to 
provide closer supervision of these huge financial institutions 
even before the Asian crisis struck in 1997. But he said that Fed 
officials realize that ``further modifications are required in both 
that approach and capital regulations'' for these institutions. 

</P>
<P>
	US Airways Has Quieter Shuttle  
</P>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- People who live near LaGuardia and Reagan  
National airports had their first chance today to hear a new 
airplane that will replace noisier US Airways jets shuttling 
between New York and Washington. The 9 a.m. shuttle between 
Washington and New York, as well as the 11 a.m. return trip, were 
flown on one of US Airways' new Airbus A-320s. Thanks to their 
high-bypass jet engines, the twin-engine planes leave noise 
footprints 10 times smaller than the route's current Boeing 727s at 
National and 17 times smaller on approaches or takeoffs at 
LaGuardia. 

</P>
<P>
	Revlon Struggles With Hard Times  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Revlon Inc., one of the best-known names in  
makeup and consumer products, is getting out of the business of 
selling products through beauty salons and shedding some Latin 
American brands after billionaire Ronald O. Perelman failed to find 
a buyer for the company. In announcing the relatively minor 
makeover Friday, Revlon also surprised Wall Street with word that 
it would post a loss for this year, and have to restructure its 
$1.8 billion debt. Shares in Revlon fell 6 1/4, or 34 percent, to 12. 

</P>
<P>
	ASEAN Nations Consider Trade Zone  
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE (AP) -- Economic ministers from Southeast Asia and  
their counterparts from Australia and New Zealand said today they 
will consider establishing a free trade zone for the region by 
2010. The idea is that their combined forces could give them a 
louder voice in international trade, according to George Yeo, 
Singapore's Minister of Trade and Industry. Trade volume between 
Southeast Asian countries and Australia and New Zealand totaled 
more than $16 billion in 1998. The Association of Southeast Asian 
Nations already has taken steps toward making the region a 
``zero-tariff'' trade area. 

</P>
