<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Fires Thrive in Dry Weather </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CORONA, Calif. (AP) -- Firefighters began to surround a blaze  
that had destroyed a home and threatened 200 others, while dozens 
of other wildfires burned out of control Friday in California and 
Oregon. 
</P>
<P>
	The Corona fire, 40 miles east of Los Angeles, was expected to  
be completely under control this weekend. It caused some anxious 
moments for George Valdez when it came within 50 feet of his house. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was traumatic,'' he said. ``It was a matter of those  
firefighters saving it or me watching it burn. Fortunately they 
saved it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, some of the dozens of wildfires that have scorched  
more than 115,000 acres in California and Oregon over the past 
month were burning in such remote, nearly inaccessible areas that 
simply getting in to fight them was difficult. 
</P>
<P>
	In the California's Los Padres National Forest, two  
lightning-sparked wildfires have scorched 69,364 acres of trees and 
brush this month. Pack mules have been used to bring food, water, 
batteries and other equipment to firefighters. 
</P>
<P>
	In Northern California, a fire that started Tuesday in the  
Sierra foothills had doubled in size to 41,111 acres. Fire crews 
protected about 50 canyon homes that were evacuated in remote 
communities. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Trinity Alps Wilderness, two large wildfires sparked by  
lightning had spread across 88,723 acres. Calmer winds and cooler 
temperatures were aiding firefighters, but creating much smokier 
conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	Near Westley, about 35 miles southeast of San Francisco Bay, a  
hotshot Texas outfit that made its name putting out refinery fires 
during the Gulf War was called in to fight a huge oil fire. 
</P>
<P>
	The 50,000 gallons of flaming oil melted off a pile of 7 million  
cast-off tires that caught fire Sept. 22 after being hit by 
lightning. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
